1
00:00:31,542 --> 00:00:33,344
[Strip the titles, back to the roots]
Undercover Chef.

2
00:00:33,344 --> 00:00:36,847
So episode one just aired.

3
00:00:38,049 --> 00:00:39,584
- My bad...
- Wait.

4
00:00:39,584 --> 00:00:41,052
Why the accent...

5
00:00:41,052 --> 00:00:43,020
[Undercover Chef kicks off all folksy]

6
00:00:43,020 --> 00:00:44,088
You caught episode one, right?

7
00:00:44,088 --> 00:00:45,356
- Yeah, saw it.
- Right.

8
00:00:45,356 --> 00:00:46,757
So how's everyone been taking it?

9
00:00:46,757 --> 00:00:48,459
Bet your staff saw it too.

10
00:00:48,459 --> 00:00:50,061
Plenty of them watched.

11
00:00:50,061 --> 00:00:52,363
For starters, my staff said it served me right.

12
00:00:52,363 --> 00:00:54,131
Served you right, huh.

13
00:00:54,131 --> 00:00:57,134
- A lot of them said it felt good to see.
- Felt good, huh.

14
00:00:57,134 --> 00:01:00,738
The outfit alone seemed to shock them first.

15
00:01:00,738 --> 00:01:02,540
- The getup, that chef's hat.
- The hat.

16
00:01:02,540 --> 00:01:04,775
- Starting with the hat.
- That puffy hat.

17
00:01:04,775 --> 00:01:08,713
[Hee Tae's hat stuns the staff in Parma]
Seeing such a wild hat on me...

18
00:01:08,713 --> 00:01:11,449
[Shook]

19
00:01:11,449 --> 00:01:14,151
[Another hat victim]
For me, folks asked if I was a pirate.

20
00:01:14,151 --> 00:01:15,720
- The hat...
- Right.

21
00:01:15,720 --> 00:01:18,122
- They stuck that oddball headscarf on me.
- Exactly.

22
00:01:18,122 --> 00:01:19,156
[Tight]

23
00:01:19,156 --> 00:01:21,792
[Sorry, hat]
Felt like my skull would burst.

24
00:01:21,792 --> 00:01:23,628
[Cute, Kwon Sung Jun?]
That's the stuff I heard.

25
00:01:23,628 --> 00:01:24,862
It got me a little embarrassed.

26
00:01:24,862 --> 00:01:27,665
What my son was most curious about

27
00:01:27,665 --> 00:01:29,934
- wasn't me, but Chef Jung Ji Sun.
- Huh?

28
00:01:29,934 --> 00:01:31,302
- Why?
- Did he recognize me?

29
00:01:31,302 --> 00:01:32,403
People didn't seem to recognize me.

30
00:01:32,403 --> 00:01:34,617
He came running over, giggling like crazy.

31
00:01:34,617 --> 00:01:35,640
When I asked why,

32
00:01:35,640 --> 00:01:38,476
he said, "Dad, how come
Chef Jung Ji Sun is a boxer?"

33
00:01:38,476 --> 00:01:40,144
Right, that part was pretty funny.

34
00:01:40,144 --> 00:01:42,013
- He said it suits you so well.
- It does suit you.

35
00:01:42,013 --> 00:01:44,248
- You actually trained for it.
- That part kind of bothered me.

36
00:01:44,248 --> 00:01:46,183
The comments say it's all set up.

37
00:01:46,183 --> 00:01:48,719
Saying the producers staged everything.

38
00:01:48,719 --> 00:01:50,888
It felt really unfair.

39
00:01:50,888 --> 00:01:52,657
With this many cameras around,

40
00:01:52,657 --> 00:01:54,959
- how could anyone pull off a fake?
- Right.

41
00:01:54,959 --> 00:01:57,562
The thing is, we didn't hide

42
00:01:57,562 --> 00:01:59,630
- that it was a TV shoot.
- Right.

43
00:01:59,630 --> 00:02:01,632
We told them it was a TV shoot.

44
00:02:01,632 --> 00:02:04,635
It's just that their jobs
aren't listed as chefs.

45
00:02:04,635 --> 00:02:06,938
A farmer, a boxer, a baseball player...

46
00:02:06,938 --> 00:02:08,806
[Airtight cover identity]
Those were our covers.

47
00:02:08,806 --> 00:02:12,642
They're framed as Korean celebs
in a documentary.

48
00:02:13,578 --> 00:02:15,313
[Documentary about chasing a second act]
These folks are learning to cook,

49
00:02:15,313 --> 00:02:18,415
with their real jobs hidden,
that's the whole premise.

50
00:02:19,617 --> 00:02:21,319
- It was so unfair.
- Yeah, really.

51
00:02:21,319 --> 00:02:22,787
- The whole thing's real.
- The comments really got me fired up.

52
00:02:22,787 --> 00:02:24,889
- Nothing was set up at all.
- Exactly.

53
00:02:24,889 --> 00:02:27,725
Sung Jun sent Ji Sun

54
00:02:27,725 --> 00:02:29,527
so many DMs, right?

55
00:02:29,527 --> 00:02:31,062
- Whiner!
- Sent some to Chef Sam Kim, too.

56
00:02:31,062 --> 00:02:33,164
- Whiner? What were you whining about?
- Whiner.

57
00:02:33,164 --> 00:02:36,400
- Something's off.
- Something's off.

58
00:02:37,568 --> 00:02:40,905
[That's how real it got]

59
00:02:40,905 --> 00:02:43,874
[Korea's top chefs]

60
00:02:43,874 --> 00:02:48,613
[Farmer] [Baseball player] [Boxer]
[Going undercover as kitchen rookies]

61
00:02:48,613 --> 00:02:50,881
[Locations infiltrated]

62
00:02:52,283 --> 00:02:54,619
[Seoul]

63
00:02:54,619 --> 00:02:55,853
[Parma, Naples, Chengdu]

64
00:02:55,853 --> 00:02:58,255
[Undercover rookies in Chengdu, Parma, Naples!]

65
00:02:58,255 --> 00:03:00,124
[Even without their top-chef stripes]

66
00:03:00,124 --> 00:03:01,258
[Can they earn respect on local turf?]

67
00:03:01,258 --> 00:03:03,160
Ni hao.

68
00:03:03,160 --> 00:03:05,395
[Within five days...]
Otherwise you don't have enough grip.

69
00:03:06,764 --> 00:03:08,299
Okay.

70
00:03:08,299 --> 00:03:14,872
[Will they pull off the final mission?]

71
00:03:14,872 --> 00:03:16,985
[Strip the titles, back to the roots]
[Undercover Chef]

72
00:03:18,342 --> 00:03:19,977
[Naples, Italy]
Chef Kwon Sung Jun

73
00:03:19,977 --> 00:03:21,112
[Sam Kwon, day one undercover]
over in Naples,

74
00:03:21,112 --> 00:03:23,047
what kind of rookie has he become?

75
00:03:23,047 --> 00:03:26,050
[Inside the Naples sister restaurant kitchen]
- Broschi. - You've finished here, right?

76
00:03:26,050 --> 00:03:27,951
Can't wait.

77
00:03:28,653 --> 00:03:30,021
I'll show my stuff today, right?

78
00:03:30,021 --> 00:03:32,523
[Posing as ex-ballplayer "Sam Kwon"]

79
00:03:32,523 --> 00:03:37,361
[Day one, slick bandana on,
130 spuds peeled by morning]

80
00:03:37,361 --> 00:03:39,263
My own hat was a shock to me,

81
00:03:39,263 --> 00:03:41,766
but seeing his, I breathed a sigh of relief.

82
00:03:41,766 --> 00:03:43,000
Mine's way too much.

83
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:44,969
- And you're the only one wearing it.
- I know, right.

84
00:03:44,969 --> 00:03:47,104
[Neck and neck]

85
00:03:47,104 --> 00:03:48,973
I'll use a little bit more oil.

86
00:03:48,973 --> 00:03:51,342
[As lunch prep wraps up]
Now I'll prepare this pasta for us.

87
00:03:51,342 --> 00:03:55,112
Alright, let's make some pasta for ourselves.

88
00:03:55,112 --> 00:03:56,981
To welcome Kwon on his first day,

89
00:03:56,981 --> 00:04:01,152
we're making eggplant pasta.

90
00:04:01,152 --> 00:04:03,254
- Okay.
- Alright?

91
00:04:03,254 --> 00:04:05,589
That's the boss, basically the head chef.

92
00:04:05,589 --> 00:04:08,525
Right. You can tell at a glance.

93
00:04:09,460 --> 00:04:11,260
[Pure charisma when she's cooking]
Charisma.

94
00:04:12,163 --> 00:04:14,265
[Mouth-watering]
Oh, that looks good.

95
00:04:14,265 --> 00:04:16,600
It's a Sicilian-style pasta,

96
00:04:16,600 --> 00:04:17,735
with fried eggplant inside.

97
00:04:17,735 --> 00:04:18,602
- Looks delicious.
- With tomato and...

98
00:04:18,602 --> 00:04:20,370
Bet it tastes amazing.

99
00:04:20,971 --> 00:04:24,008
That one's baked in the oven, like lasagna.

100
00:04:24,008 --> 00:04:26,409
Ta-da! Check this out!

101
00:04:28,379 --> 00:04:30,948
My word, look at that gorgeous color.

102
00:04:30,948 --> 00:04:33,084
- Kwon, this one's for you.
- Thank you.

103
00:04:33,084 --> 00:04:35,686
- It's all yours!
- Really?

104
00:04:35,686 --> 00:04:37,855
Too stuffed to work after this.

105
00:04:37,855 --> 00:04:40,324
Kwon, come eat!

106
00:04:40,324 --> 00:04:42,592
Oh, that's "mangiare."

107
00:04:43,794 --> 00:04:45,594
Right here?

108
00:04:46,464 --> 00:04:49,228
[Who's eating alone here?]

109
00:04:50,501 --> 00:04:51,702
[Guido, in charge of the hall]

110
00:04:51,702 --> 00:04:53,304
[One of four owners, Luisa's husband]

111
00:04:53,304 --> 00:04:54,271
- He's the husband.
- The big sister's husband?

112
00:04:54,271 --> 00:04:56,774
- Husband.
- So that's her husband.

113
00:04:56,774 --> 00:04:58,876
[Goes to grab a seat, but...]

114
00:04:58,876 --> 00:05:01,672
[Hesitation]

115
00:05:02,580 --> 00:05:05,449
[After dithering, he picks a spot]

116
00:05:05,449 --> 00:05:06,717
[Far away]

117
00:05:06,717 --> 00:05:08,552
As far as possible...

118
00:05:08,552 --> 00:05:09,887
"As far as possible."

119
00:05:09,887 --> 00:05:11,155
- Hey.
- Hi.

120
00:05:11,155 --> 00:05:12,857
[Awkward greeting, then sits down]

121
00:05:12,857 --> 00:05:16,227
[After one bite of Chef Laura's pasta]

122
00:05:16,227 --> 00:05:18,996
[Nod]

123
00:05:18,996 --> 00:05:20,431
Kwon, how is it?

124
00:05:20,431 --> 00:05:22,133
It's seriously delicious.

125
00:05:22,133 --> 00:05:24,267
Right?

126
00:05:25,836 --> 00:05:27,972
- You're digging in.
- It was tasty.

127
00:05:27,972 --> 00:05:29,106
Bet it's amazing.

128
00:05:29,106 --> 00:05:30,908
[At a table buzzing with chatter]
At the end, it's the best one.

129
00:05:30,908 --> 00:05:32,376
You buy the clothes.

130
00:05:32,376 --> 00:05:34,044
- For the festivities.
- What is it, a beignet?

131
00:05:34,044 --> 00:05:36,847
[Kwon eats in silence, lost in thought]
A pastry.

132
00:05:36,847 --> 00:05:38,816
[Deep in thought]
There was way less.

133
00:05:38,816 --> 00:05:41,385
When you eat the staff meal,

134
00:05:41,385 --> 00:05:43,554
there are a few things you need to check.

135
00:05:43,554 --> 00:05:45,489
- How the pasta is cooked.
- Yeah.

136
00:05:45,489 --> 00:05:47,424
- How al dente they cook it.
- Right.

137
00:05:47,424 --> 00:05:49,026
- And the seasoning.
- Seasoning.

138
00:05:49,026 --> 00:05:50,694
Because at the end of the day, the head chef

139
00:05:50,694 --> 00:05:52,797
- tasted it as she made it.
- Right.

140
00:05:52,797 --> 00:05:54,865
- That's the gold standard!
- Exactly.

141
00:05:54,865 --> 00:05:56,767
- So I was trying to read it.
- Makes sense.

142
00:05:56,767 --> 00:05:58,702
Tasting it, I figured out the seasoning,

143
00:05:58,702 --> 00:06:01,172
and the pasta's doneness level.

144
00:06:01,172 --> 00:06:03,607
That's the kind of stuff I was reading.

145
00:06:03,607 --> 00:06:05,776
- You're sharp, no doubt.
- Right?

146
00:06:05,776 --> 00:06:06,811
My brain doesn't get a break.

147
00:06:06,811 --> 00:06:09,847
[Turns out he's a sharp strategist]

148
00:06:09,847 --> 00:06:13,818
[Head chef's pasta, decoded]

149
00:06:13,818 --> 00:06:18,155
Kwon, take ten minutes, then we open.

150
00:06:18,155 --> 00:06:20,124
Okay.

151
00:06:20,124 --> 00:06:23,327
[Meal's done, back to the kitchen]

152
00:06:23,327 --> 00:06:27,097
[Senior An and Kwon, reunited]

153
00:06:27,097 --> 00:06:28,166
[Wipes a rag for no real reason]

154
00:06:28,166 --> 00:06:31,202
When chefs feel awkward, they wipe a rag once.

155
00:06:32,002 --> 00:06:34,839
[Memories of that morning
come flooding back...]

156
00:06:34,839 --> 00:06:37,241
[From how to fold a rag for pots...]
A friendly advice, when you do this operation

157
00:06:37,241 --> 00:06:39,510
fold the tea towel more like this.

158
00:06:39,510 --> 00:06:42,346
For water glasses,
placing them this way works better.

159
00:06:42,346 --> 00:06:44,161
[To how to set down a water glass]
- Okay. - The bottle doesn't fall,

160
00:06:44,161 --> 00:06:46,417
and you don't lose the glass.

161
00:06:46,417 --> 00:06:48,886
[Senior An, who kept Kwon on tight watch...]

162
00:06:48,886 --> 00:06:50,087
This should always be on.

163
00:06:50,087 --> 00:06:53,858
[Kwon's station with senior An during lunch]
- On a low heat, but always on. - Okay.

164
00:06:53,858 --> 00:06:57,027
[Station No. 1, Laura's pasta station]
Pasta primi.

165
00:06:57,027 --> 00:06:58,229
The mains.

166
00:06:58,229 --> 00:06:59,864
[Past Paolo's mains section, station No. 2]

167
00:06:59,864 --> 00:07:00,764
[Rookie zone: appetizers and desserts]

168
00:07:00,764 --> 00:07:04,158
It's the same thing.

169
00:07:04,158 --> 00:07:05,502
- Okay.
- Okay.

170
00:07:05,502 --> 00:07:07,438
[Working appetizers in the rookie zone]
That guy Antonio

171
00:07:07,438 --> 00:07:10,174
kept me on the hook the whole shift.

172
00:07:10,174 --> 00:07:11,817
He's my handler.

173
00:07:12,509 --> 00:07:15,579
Potato prep's done,

174
00:07:15,579 --> 00:07:18,682
so this needs to go back, too.

175
00:07:18,682 --> 00:07:22,152
[Tailing right behind senior An]

176
00:07:22,152 --> 00:07:24,822
[Machine, back in place]

177
00:07:24,822 --> 00:07:27,324
- Okay.
- Let me show you how it's done.

178
00:07:27,324 --> 00:07:29,360
[Back to prep, time for appetizers]

179
00:07:29,360 --> 00:07:31,495
[Dishes, fresh from washing]

180
00:07:31,495 --> 00:07:34,798
[Senior loaded up, Kwon's hands empty]

181
00:07:34,798 --> 00:07:38,102
[Strolling in without a care]

182
00:07:38,102 --> 00:07:41,405
Don't walk in and out
of the kitchen empty-handed.

183
00:07:41,405 --> 00:07:44,508
Same goes for dropping off dishes.

184
00:07:44,508 --> 00:07:47,344
Going into the fridge, take some dirty things.

185
00:07:47,344 --> 00:07:48,779
Coming back, you bring here

186
00:07:48,779 --> 00:07:50,448
- clean stuff.
- Okay.

187
00:07:50,448 --> 00:07:51,802
That's not what I meant...

188
00:07:51,802 --> 00:07:52,818
[Ugh]

189
00:07:52,818 --> 00:07:55,252
- "Hand that to me," shouldn't it go like that?
- Right.

190
00:07:55,252 --> 00:07:57,688
- "I'll carry it."
- "Let me grab it," that's the move.

191
00:07:57,688 --> 00:07:58,923
[Been a while being the rookie...]

192
00:07:58,923 --> 00:08:01,392
- Pots go down here.
- Yeah.

193
00:08:01,392 --> 00:08:04,195
- Pans go over this way!
- Okay.

194
00:08:04,195 --> 00:08:06,630
[After a round of Antonio's spicy nagging]

195
00:08:06,630 --> 00:08:07,831
[Stirs]

196
00:08:07,831 --> 00:08:08,632
Here?

197
00:08:08,632 --> 00:08:11,702
This is the welcome dish, bean soup.

198
00:08:11,702 --> 00:08:15,572
Bean soup goes to every table,
no matter what they order.

199
00:08:15,572 --> 00:08:17,273
[Noted]
Got it?

200
00:08:17,908 --> 00:08:21,011
[Bean soup]
Plain bean soup is pretty unique.

201
00:08:21,011 --> 00:08:22,212
[Welcome dish: bean soup for every guest]

202
00:08:22,212 --> 00:08:25,416
Is that bean soup just boiled beans? Just that?

203
00:08:25,416 --> 00:08:28,419
Beans, herbs, broth, kept simple.

204
00:08:28,419 --> 00:08:31,221
[Simple dish boiled with beans,
chestnuts, herbs]

205
00:08:31,221 --> 00:08:34,224
[What matters most in this bean soup?]

206
00:08:34,224 --> 00:08:37,761
Try a bite, check if the seasoning
and temp are right.

207
00:08:37,761 --> 00:08:39,630
[Blowing on it]

208
00:08:39,630 --> 00:08:42,199
[A big bite]

209
00:08:42,199 --> 00:08:45,302
[Senior An takes a bite, too]

210
00:08:45,302 --> 00:08:47,638
[How's it taste?]

211
00:08:47,638 --> 00:08:51,308
You're saying it's good, right? After one bite.

212
00:08:51,308 --> 00:08:53,110
[Nod]

213
00:08:53,110 --> 00:08:54,678
[Gestures of "it's good"]

214
00:08:54,678 --> 00:08:56,709
[Tastes amazing]

215
00:08:58,048 --> 00:09:00,250
- It's a bit bland to me.
- It's good...

216
00:09:00,250 --> 00:09:02,052
[Yeah, I figured...]

217
00:09:02,052 --> 00:09:02,987
I was acting.

218
00:09:02,987 --> 00:09:04,922
[Rookie rule: praise the senior's dish first]
So you were acting?

219
00:09:04,922 --> 00:09:06,223
This gesture meant it was tasty.

220
00:09:06,223 --> 00:09:08,459
[Downside: you might get caught]

221
00:09:08,459 --> 00:09:10,995
Throwing in one more pinch of salt.

222
00:09:10,995 --> 00:09:11,895
[One pinch of salt]

223
00:09:11,895 --> 00:09:13,664
And a bit of oil.

224
00:09:13,664 --> 00:09:16,800
[As the bean soup gets mostly ready]
This is always on, on low heat but always on.

225
00:09:16,800 --> 00:09:19,236
- Okay.
- Okay?

226
00:09:19,236 --> 00:09:22,039
[Lunch service begins, 1:00 PM]

227
00:09:22,039 --> 00:09:26,110
[Guests pour in the moment doors open]

228
00:09:26,110 --> 00:09:29,813
[First ticket comes in]

229
00:09:29,813 --> 00:09:31,048
So...

230
00:09:31,048 --> 00:09:32,950
Alright, let me show you how to read a ticket.

231
00:09:32,950 --> 00:09:34,551
Okay.

232
00:09:34,551 --> 00:09:36,153
- Table two.
- Table two.

233
00:09:36,153 --> 00:09:37,688
Five guests.

234
00:09:37,688 --> 00:09:42,126
So five bowls of bean soup, right?

235
00:09:42,126 --> 00:09:43,394
- Okay.
- That would be

236
00:09:43,394 --> 00:09:44,361
the soup.

237
00:09:44,361 --> 00:09:45,362
Okay.

238
00:09:45,362 --> 00:09:46,697
Five bowls.

239
00:09:46,697 --> 00:09:47,931
[Get five bowls ready for the bean soup!]

240
00:09:47,931 --> 00:09:49,566
- And five plates.
- Okay.

241
00:09:49,566 --> 00:09:51,201
Two, four, five.

242
00:09:51,201 --> 00:09:52,770
[When senior An gives the order]

243
00:09:52,770 --> 00:09:55,873
[Plate setup, commence]

244
00:09:55,873 --> 00:09:58,437
[Exactly five bowls, all set]

245
00:09:59,810 --> 00:10:01,190
I'll demo the first two for you.

246
00:10:01,190 --> 00:10:03,380
- You handle the rest.
- Okay.

247
00:10:03,380 --> 00:10:09,274
[Loaded with chunks, two ladles per bowl]

248
00:10:09,953 --> 00:10:12,489
[Peek]

249
00:10:12,489 --> 00:10:14,591
Grab me a few napkins.

250
00:10:14,591 --> 00:10:16,026
- Paper towel?
- Yes, paper towel.

251
00:10:16,026 --> 00:10:18,595
[Order drops, action follows]

252
00:10:19,903 --> 00:10:22,466
- A turn of oil.
- Okay.

