- He's quick on his feet and reads the room.

506
00:20:14,691 --> 00:20:16,491
[And the cheese...]
For sure.

507
00:20:17,627 --> 00:20:18,828
Is this enough?

508
00:20:18,828 --> 00:20:21,082
- Just right.
- Okay.

509
00:20:21,082 --> 00:20:22,999
- Off to the oven now...
- So.

510
00:20:22,999 --> 00:20:26,169
Be careful when you open the oven.

511
00:20:26,169 --> 00:20:28,905
- When you open it, always stand back here.
- Okay.

512
00:20:28,905 --> 00:20:30,907
[Heat means burn risk, open from behind]
You wait a couple of seconds.

513
00:20:30,907 --> 00:20:32,609
And then open the door.

514
00:20:32,609 --> 00:20:35,945
- This way you dodge the heat from the oven.
- Okay.

515
00:20:35,945 --> 00:20:39,749
He's teaching him like a total beginner.

516
00:20:39,749 --> 00:20:42,752
[Antonio has no clue Sung Jun is a pro]
- Or you'll get a lot of hot air. - Okay.

517
00:20:42,752 --> 00:20:43,965
Yank it open all at once,

518
00:20:43,965 --> 00:20:45,855
- heat blasts out like a sauna.
- Okay.

519
00:20:45,855 --> 00:20:48,525
[Kind, yeah, but...]

520
00:20:48,525 --> 00:20:49,626
My head's everywhere.

521
00:20:49,626 --> 00:20:51,227
[The endless nagging has him losing focus]

522
00:20:51,227 --> 00:20:53,858
[While the food in the oven cooks...]

523
00:20:55,598 --> 00:20:57,300
[Fumble]

524
00:20:57,300 --> 00:20:59,469
[Grabs one polenta to fry]
Oh, so the polenta needs frying now.

525
00:20:59,469 --> 00:21:01,538
Excuse me.

526
00:21:01,538 --> 00:21:03,406
[Straight to the fryer]

527
00:21:03,406 --> 00:21:05,797
[Gentle, just like senior An showed]

528
00:21:06,910 --> 00:21:09,379
Come on, Kwon.

529
00:21:09,379 --> 00:21:11,747
- Keep going.
- Okay.

530
00:21:12,415 --> 00:21:15,719
Cold items always go first,
lay the cold one down first.

531
00:21:15,719 --> 00:21:18,354
[Cold one?]

532
00:21:18,354 --> 00:21:20,223
- Beef roll.
- Beef roll.

533
00:21:20,223 --> 00:21:21,324
[Oops]
Okay.

534
00:21:21,324 --> 00:21:24,516
[Snatches up the beef roll in a hurry]

535
00:21:25,428 --> 00:21:28,665
[Quick onto the plate]
Beef roll, set it on the plate.

536
00:21:28,665 --> 00:21:31,735
Sprinkle the cheese.

537
00:21:31,735 --> 00:21:33,636
[Sneaky glance]

538
00:21:33,636 --> 00:21:35,905
- Did you drop the polenta in the fryer?
- Yes.

539
00:21:35,905 --> 00:21:38,908
He dropped the polenta in earlier, right?

540
00:21:38,908 --> 00:21:42,178
[But when did I actually put it in?]

541
00:21:42,178 --> 00:21:44,448
[Swoosh]

542
00:21:44,448 --> 00:21:47,584
[Polenta fritter, completely slipped his mind]

543
00:21:47,584 --> 00:21:49,252
- He put it in way too early.
- Hurry.

544
00:21:49,252 --> 00:21:51,887
Check, did it burn?

545
00:21:53,591 --> 00:21:56,572
[Big strides]

546
00:21:58,995 --> 00:22:01,431
- Looks amazing.
- Yeah?

547
00:22:01,431 --> 00:22:03,767
- Came out great.
- Of course.

548
00:22:03,767 --> 00:22:04,768
[Lucky break...]

549
00:22:04,768 --> 00:22:06,970
Excuse me.

550
00:22:06,970 --> 00:22:09,339
[Just about to plate again, but...]

551
00:22:09,339 --> 00:22:12,642
- Pull the food out of the oven!
- Yes.

552
00:22:12,642 --> 00:22:15,678
[Tagging along]

553
00:22:15,678 --> 00:22:17,814
[Opens from behind, just as the senior taught]

554
00:22:17,814 --> 00:22:19,524
[Swish]

555
00:22:20,583 --> 00:22:21,818
[No escaping senior An's watch]

556
00:22:21,818 --> 00:22:23,620
- Do you remember?
- Yes.

557
00:22:23,620 --> 00:22:25,797
[Beat...]

558
00:22:30,093 --> 00:22:33,280
[Is one appetizer really this brutal?]

559
00:22:37,700 --> 00:22:40,336
Did you sprinkle the cheese powder?

560
00:22:40,336 --> 00:22:41,971
[Freeze]

561
00:22:41,971 --> 00:22:43,740
I sprinkled the cheese powder.

562
00:22:43,740 --> 00:22:45,041
- I used it.
- I'm asking if you did it before the oven.

563
00:22:45,041 --> 00:22:46,042
[Second freeze]

564
00:22:46,042 --> 00:22:47,977
- No.
- It has to go on before the oven.

565
00:22:47,977 --> 00:22:50,346
- It had to go on before the oven?
- I did. I sprinkled it.

566
00:22:50,346 --> 00:22:51,147
Parmigiano cheese.

567
00:22:51,147 --> 00:22:52,448
- Really?
- I sprinkled it.

568
00:22:52,448 --> 00:22:56,119
[Pretty sure he sprinkled it
before the oven...]

569
00:22:56,119 --> 00:22:57,453
[Forgot he even did it...]

570
00:22:57,453 --> 00:23:00,155
- Rice here.
- Yes.

571
00:23:03,026 --> 00:23:04,093
[Oh, the meatball...]

572
00:23:04,093 --> 00:23:05,995
The meatball.

573
00:23:05,995 --> 00:23:07,463
The meatball.

574
00:23:07,463 --> 00:23:09,292
[Side eye]

575
00:23:10,034 --> 00:23:13,503
- Use a spoon when you move the meatball.
- Okay.

576
00:23:13,503 --> 00:23:15,972
[Scrambling]
On top of that, the sauce needs to go on too.

577
00:23:15,972 --> 00:23:17,707
This is right, isn't it?

578
00:23:17,707 --> 00:23:20,276
The plating needs to spread out wider overall.

579
00:23:20,276 --> 00:23:22,111
- Wider.
- Okay.

580
00:23:22,111 --> 00:23:24,180
- Tomato.
- Yes.

581
00:23:24,180 --> 00:23:26,616
[While Kwon is losing his head like this...]
My head's spinning.

582
00:23:26,616 --> 00:23:27,617
[Current situation in the hall]

583
00:23:27,617 --> 00:23:30,119
These folks are waiting too.

584
00:23:31,020 --> 00:23:33,289
[Antipasto platter orders: 13 total]

585
00:23:33,289 --> 00:23:37,201
[Sent out: zero...]

586
00:23:38,127 --> 00:23:39,395
[Everyone is just waiting on the platter...]

587
00:23:39,395 --> 00:23:40,463
- They're waiting?
- No way.

588
00:23:40,463 --> 00:23:42,700
- Right now they're stuck waiting on apps.
- No way, it got held up?

589
00:23:42,700 --> 00:23:44,968
[Starving...]

590
00:23:44,968 --> 00:23:46,369
Go on, finish it.

591
00:23:46,369 --> 00:23:48,071
[Kwon has no clue what's happening out front]

592
00:23:48,071 --> 00:23:50,073
[Still waiting]
The meatballs are different.

593
00:23:50,073 --> 00:23:51,541
They are different.

594
00:23:51,541 --> 00:23:53,243
- Table nine.
- Okay.

595
00:23:53,243 --> 00:23:56,245
Their work lunch break is short,
hurry it up, okay.

596
00:23:56,946 --> 00:24:01,351
[Crisis right out of the gate]

597
00:24:01,351 --> 00:24:04,220
[With everyone watching]

598
00:24:04,220 --> 00:24:06,155
How do we prepare it?

599
00:24:07,023 --> 00:24:08,458
Look here.

600
00:24:08,458 --> 00:24:11,127
[Big trouble]
- Then I'll show you slowly. - Okay.

601
00:24:11,127 --> 00:24:14,197
[Senior An jumps in to help]

602
00:24:14,197 --> 00:24:17,033
- The polenta goes here.
- Okay.

603
00:24:17,033 --> 00:24:19,168
[The two of them tag-team a quick save]

604
00:24:19,168 --> 00:24:22,240
[After a nagging blitz, one platter is done]

605
00:24:22,240 --> 00:24:26,824
[Heads out to the table of guests who waited]

606
00:24:27,682 --> 00:24:29,746
[One platter and he's already
looking hollowed out...]

607
00:24:29,746 --> 00:24:31,114
- Okay?
- Okay.

608
00:24:31,114 --> 00:24:32,815
[Plenty of backed-up orders still left]
Now, here,

609
00:24:32,815 --> 00:24:35,018
- we organize the antipasto.
- Yes.

610
00:24:35,018 --> 00:24:38,021
[Straight into prepping three more platters]
3 rice cakes, 3 potato cakes, 6 meatballs.

611
00:24:38,021 --> 00:24:39,222
Okay.

612
00:24:39,222 --> 00:24:41,914
[This time, three full servings on his own]

613
00:24:42,692 --> 00:24:44,394
[Rice cake set first]
A few more reps and he'll have it down, no?

614
00:24:44,394 --> 00:24:46,863
[Potato cake too]
Right, for a first try, he's doing well.

615
00:24:46,863 --> 00:24:50,400
[Three of each, same as before]

616
00:24:50,400 --> 00:24:53,269
[This time, get through it without the nagging]

617
00:24:53,269 --> 00:24:55,204
You've got to do it this way

618
00:24:55,204 --> 00:24:57,173
so the meatball fits.

619
00:24:57,173 --> 00:24:58,841
- Right.
- Rows and columns.

620
00:24:58,841 --> 00:25:00,257
Right.

621
00:25:01,277 --> 00:25:04,414
[All that's left is to slide it in the oven]
[Let me see...]

622
00:25:04,414 --> 00:25:06,983
- Hold on, come over here.
- Yes.

623
00:25:06,983 --> 00:25:08,952
Hold on, come over here.

624
00:25:08,952 --> 00:25:11,487
- Hold on, stop.
- He didn't sprinkle the cheese.

625
00:25:11,487 --> 00:25:13,289
Hold on, come over here.

626
00:25:13,289 --> 00:25:16,084
Forget something? The olive oil goes on first.

627
00:25:16,084 --> 00:25:17,593
[Another slip-up...]
Olive oil has to go on.

628
00:25:17,593 --> 00:25:20,029
- They're already fried. Okay.
- Okay.

629
00:25:20,029 --> 00:25:21,881
The meatball skips the olive oil,

630
00:25:21,881 --> 00:25:22,899
- so do this first.
- Okay.

631
00:25:22,899 --> 00:25:24,300
[Patient hands-on demo again]

632
00:25:24,300 --> 00:25:26,703
Olive oil, then cheese on top.

633
00:25:26,703 --> 00:25:28,738
- And immediately out.
- Okay.

634
00:25:28,738 --> 00:25:30,139
[On the receiving end of rapid-fire lessons]
We can also do like this.

635
00:25:30,139 --> 00:25:32,809
When Antonio gets antsy like that,
what's he supposed to do?

636
00:25:32,809 --> 00:25:34,010
[Up next, plating the meatball]
[Tagging along]

637
00:25:34,010 --> 00:25:36,312
[Glued on]

638
00:25:36,312 --> 00:25:37,314
- So.
- Cheese.

639
00:25:37,314 --> 00:25:40,383
Look, this one has more tomato sauce.

640
00:25:40,383 --> 00:25:44,387
- Okay.
- Baking it in the oven brings some grease out.

641
00:25:44,387 --> 00:25:48,324
So tomato sauce on its own is plenty.

642
00:25:48,324 --> 00:25:50,493
- Got it?
- Okay.

643
00:25:50,493 --> 00:25:52,595
It depends on the meatball.

644
00:25:52,595 --> 00:25:56,032
If you think about how the meatball
and tomato sauce go in...

645
00:25:56,032 --> 00:25:57,233
He's way too close.

646
00:25:57,233 --> 00:25:58,801
- Okay?
- Okay.

647
00:25:58,801 --> 00:26:00,203
Way too close...

648
00:26:00,203 --> 00:26:01,771
I bet you'd miss him.

649
00:26:01,771 --> 00:26:04,073
Antonio is great.

650
00:26:04,073 --> 00:26:05,808
That kind of attention
really would wear you out.

651
00:26:05,808 --> 00:26:09,345
[Drilling it into his ear...]
Right next to him, just talking nonstop.

652
00:26:09,345 --> 00:26:12,648
- Feels almost like dating...
- He'll show up in dreams now.

653
00:26:14,384 --> 00:26:17,375
[Finally slides the food into the oven...]

654
00:26:18,755 --> 00:26:21,491
[Wobble]

655
00:26:21,491 --> 00:26:23,926
[Mind in a fog...]

656
00:26:23,926 --> 00:26:27,163
[Rookie wiped out by senior's nagging]
Antonio teaches in a really detailed way,

657
00:26:27,163 --> 00:26:29,064
and honestly that makes it harder.

658
00:26:29,699 --> 00:26:30,767
[Hollow-eyed]

659
00:26:30,767 --> 00:26:31,934
- It's rough.
- It was rough.

660
00:26:31,934 --> 00:26:33,136
After he said it was good and all.

661
00:26:33,136 --> 00:26:34,370
- It was good.
- Now he's saying it's rough.

662
00:26:34,370 --> 00:26:36,171
Guess I was struggling back then...

663
00:26:36,171 --> 00:26:37,907
[Whether Kwon is dazed or not... ]
I know why.

664
00:26:37,907 --> 00:26:39,441
[2 platters]

665
00:26:40,587 --> 00:26:41,577
[4 platters]

666
00:26:41,577 --> 00:26:44,514
[3 platters]
Gummy candy.

667
00:26:44,514 --> 00:26:45,748
Table eight, please.

668
00:26:45,748 --> 00:26:46,916
Handle it solo just fine.

669
00:26:46,916 --> 00:26:49,552
[Sending dishes out on autopilot]
Send them to the first table.

670
00:26:49,552 --> 00:26:51,019
- Okay.
- Okay.

671
00:26:51,019 --> 00:26:52,321
[Burners also packed]
The burners...

672
00:26:52,321 --> 00:26:53,923
- No room left.
- It's packed.

673
00:26:53,923 --> 00:26:56,859
[With every station in full chaos]

674
00:26:56,859 --> 00:26:58,394
[Following senior An
through the cramped kitchen]

675
00:26:58,394 --> 00:27:02,498
[Running around left and right]

676
00:27:02,498 --> 00:27:05,697
[Antipasto platter, fully served]

677
00:27:06,571 --> 00:27:09,238
[Antipasto done, finally catching his breath]
Day one was kind of brutal.

678
00:27:09,238 --> 00:27:10,873
Dessert orders will be coming in soon!

679
00:27:10,873 --> 00:27:12,563
I have to handle dessert too.

680
00:27:13,276 --> 00:27:15,499
[Dessert order arrives]

681
00:27:16,446 --> 00:27:18,281
[Checking the ticket]

682
00:27:18,281 --> 00:27:19,348
So,

683
00:27:19,348 --> 00:27:21,551
[Two plates of mille-feuille]
- here's the order. - Yes.

684
00:27:21,551 --> 00:27:24,787
- You know how to use a piping bag?
- A piping bag.

685
00:27:24,787 --> 00:27:26,489
- For sure.
- Okay.

686
00:27:26,489 --> 00:27:28,024
[For the mille-feuille, see...]

687
00:27:28,024 --> 00:27:31,494
Always pipe a little custard cream
onto the plate first.

688
00:27:31,494 --> 00:27:34,197
[Pull out the lightly warmed pastry]

689
00:27:34,197 --> 00:27:37,029
[Just layer cream on top and you're set]

690
00:27:37,934 --> 00:27:41,852
[Right as the plating wraps up]

691
00:27:42,772 --> 00:27:45,042
Powdered sugar, ready.

692
00:27:45,042 --> 00:27:47,710
[Now he reads it and rolls with it]

693
00:27:47,710 --> 00:27:51,213
But Chef Kwon,
everything kind of shows on his face.

694
00:27:52,281 --> 00:27:55,083
It's like, "I'm about to get praised for this."

695
00:27:56,152 --> 00:28:00,165
["Praise me, please"]
- Look, that face, every time. - That face.

696
00:28:01,424 --> 00:28:03,526
- When he's pleased with himself.
- Right.

697
00:28:03,526 --> 00:28:06,529
[Hahaha]

698
00:28:06,529 --> 00:28:09,892
[With a quick-witted rookie's help]

699
00:28:09,892 --> 00:28:12,350
[Mille-feuille done]
- Looks delicious. - Three.

700
00:28:13,903 --> 00:28:14,971
The work just never ends.

701
00:28:14,971 --> 00:28:17,440
[Same order as before]
Two and a half mille-feuille.

702
00:28:17,440 --> 00:28:19,642
- Okay.
- You remember how to do it?

703
00:28:19,642 --> 00:28:21,089
- Yes.
- The number of layers

704
00:28:21,089 --> 00:28:23,379
[Kwon takes a solo crack at it this time]
is always like that.

705
00:28:23,379 --> 00:28:24,447
Okay.

706
00:28:24,447 --> 00:28:25,882
[For mille-feuille, what comes first is...]

707
00:28:25,882 --> 00:28:27,917
- That's not it.
- It's not?

708
00:28:27,917 --> 00:28:29,352
- That's not it.
- It's not?

709
00:28:29,352 --> 00:28:31,154
[Wrong move, blocked from grabbing parchment]

710
00:28:31,154 --> 00:28:33,589
[Kwon stumbles right out of the gate...]

711
00:28:33,589 --> 00:28:36,859
[Watching to see if he's doing it right]

712
00:28:36,859 --> 00:28:39,962
[Into the oven for now]

713
00:28:39,962 --> 00:28:41,731
I still don't know where things are.

714
00:28:41,731 --> 00:28:44,902
[Whoops]
It's my first day of service. It's not easy.

715
00:28:44,902 --> 00:28:47,904
[Senior An's eyes darting around busily]

716
00:28:47,904 --> 00:28:50,695
[Under the senior's close watch]

717
00:28:52,008 --> 00:28:53,476
[Eyes on him]

718
00:28:53,476 --> 00:28:55,511
There's not enough cream.

719
00:28:55,511 --> 00:28:59,215
Pipe more here and here,
and more over here too.

720
00:28:59,215 --> 00:29:02,440
[Senior An, not happy with how Kwon piped it]

721
00:29:03,352 --> 00:29:04,887
More here.

722
00:29:04,887 --> 00:29:07,056
Here too.

723
00:29:07,056 --> 00:29:10,726
[Just one note after another...]
This place is a real challenge too.

724
00:29:10,726 --> 00:29:13,529
When you pipe the cream in the middle,
push deep and let it rise up.

725
00:29:13,529 --> 00:29:17,233
[The voice keeps getting louder...]
You can even go deeper with the sac-a-poche.

726
00:29:17,233 --> 00:29:18,546
As if you wanted to continue

727
00:29:18,546 --> 00:29:20,269
[A look as if he doesn't quite follow]
what you have here.

728
00:29:20,269 --> 00:29:23,438
- Okay? Put the cherry on now.
- Yes.

729
00:29:25,174 --> 00:29:28,144
[The mood turns frosty in an instant]

730
00:29:28,144 --> 00:29:30,880
[Now No. 2 is watching too...]

731
00:29:30,880 --> 00:29:33,716
- Big, stable ones go on the bottom.
- Okay.

732
00:29:33,716 --> 00:29:37,787
Thin or broken ones go on top.

733
00:29:37,787 --> 00:29:42,358
Always stack them in alternating directions.

734
00:29:42,358 --> 00:29:43,593
I didn't catch that one either.

735
00:29:43,593 --> 00:29:46,329
[Tries it the way he understood it...]

736
00:29:46,329 --> 00:29:50,233
[In the end, Antonio's hands take over...]

737
00:29:50,233 --> 00:29:53,669
[A mille-feuille built out of nagging...]

738
00:29:53,669 --> 00:29:56,533
[Even for a seasoned chef]

739
00:29:56,533 --> 00:29:59,942
[Someone else's kitchen is tough...]
Going back to being the rookie,

740
00:29:59,942 --> 00:30:02,845
- honestly, as you can see, it's no joke.
- It isn't easy.

741
00:30:02,845 --> 00:30:06,349
Ever wanted to bail halfway?
Like, "I just want to go home?"

742
00:30:06,349 --> 00:30:08,551
- Yes.
- Had a moment like that here?

743
00:30:08,551 --> 00:30:09,552
Right there.

744
00:30:09,552 --> 00:30:11,320
- Oh, this part? At the very end?
- Yes.

745
00:30:11,320 --> 00:30:13,256
- From day one?
- From day one.

746
00:30:13,256 --> 00:30:15,290
Something's off.

747
00:30:16,892 --> 00:30:20,863
[After nothing but nagging, lunch wraps up]

748
00:30:20,863 --> 00:30:22,398
- Kwon, see you later.
- Yes.

749
00:30:22,398 --> 00:30:25,768
- Yes, see you later.
- Have a good evening, rest well.

750
00:30:25,768 --> 00:30:27,336
[Currently 3:00 PM, restaurant break time]

751
00:30:27,336 --> 00:30:29,839
End of lunch service.

752
00:30:29,839 --> 00:30:32,275
What time should I come in for dinner prep?

753
00:30:32,275 --> 00:30:36,345
Come in by 6:30 PM.

754
00:30:36,345 --> 00:30:38,180
6:30.

755
00:30:38,180 --> 00:30:40,283
- Okay.
- 6:30.

756
00:30:40,283 --> 00:30:43,141
[On the long break, the staff all head home]

757
00:30:44,887 --> 00:30:48,391
[Our Kwon trudges home too]

758
00:30:48,391 --> 00:30:51,727
[Arrives at his place, 3:15 PM]

759
00:30:51,727 --> 00:30:53,829
[Back home, his choice is...]

760
00:30:53,829 --> 00:30:56,065
[Bedtime]

761
00:30:56,065 --> 00:30:58,384
<i>When you put cream in the center,</i>

762
00:30:58,384 --> 00:31:02,932
[Senior An's nagging still seems to echo in his ears]
<i>you can even go deeper.</i>

763
00:31:06,275 --> 00:31:10,813
[Rookie life took its toll, Kwon crashes hard]

764
00:31:10,813 --> 00:31:11,981
[But then]

765
00:31:11,981 --> 00:31:14,015
Wait, what?

766
00:31:16,552 --> 00:31:18,854
[Time keeps ticking by...]

767
00:31:18,854 --> 00:31:20,289
[6:10 PM]

768
00:31:20,289 --> 00:31:22,258
- What?
- 20 minutes out.

769
00:31:22,258 --> 00:31:23,259
[20 minutes to be back already...]

770
00:31:23,259 --> 00:31:26,062
- He's not going to wake up, is he?
- Seriously?

771
00:31:26,062 --> 00:31:28,230
No way.

772
00:31:29,965 --> 00:31:32,702
[At the same hour]
As we did before.

773
00:31:32,702 --> 00:31:33,836
The seniors clocked in early.

774
00:31:33,836 --> 00:31:36,714
[The seniors are already in,
prepping for service...]

775
00:31:38,007 --> 00:31:42,688
[Sam Kwon, late on day one?]

776
00:31:44,180 --> 00:31:46,148
[Parma, Italy]
So now, after 27 years,

777
00:31:46,148 --> 00:31:47,583
he's the rookie again.

778
00:31:47,583 --> 00:31:50,118
[Undercover rookie Hee Tae, day one]
He pulled a little stunt recently.

779
00:31:51,820 --> 00:31:53,923
[Eggshell slipped in while separating yolks]
A piece of shell fell in.

780
00:31:53,923 --> 00:31:56,225
[Boss caught it right away]
- Right. - Of all things, it caught his eye.

781
00:31:56,225 --> 00:32:00,129
[Boss fishes it out himself]

782
00:32:00,129 --> 00:32:02,264
- This one's fun.
- I'm curious.

783
00:32:02,264 --> 00:32:03,966
I'm looking forward to it.

784
00:32:03,966 --> 00:32:07,585
[After the eggshell incident...]

785
00:32:10,473 --> 00:32:13,509
[Eyes on him]

786
00:32:13,509 --> 00:32:16,979
[Get it together!]

787
00:32:16,979 --> 00:32:18,080
- One.
- Yes.

788
00:32:18,080 --> 00:32:19,315
[Lunch prep continues with senior Lu]
And one.

789
00:32:19,315 --> 00:32:21,484
- We'll open it and put it in.
- Okay.

790
00:32:21,484 --> 00:32:22,918
- Pasta?
- Yes.

791
00:32:22,918 --> 00:32:24,086
[Time to make the pasta dough]

792
00:32:24,086 --> 00:32:26,021
Yellow pasta.

793
00:32:26,889 --> 00:32:29,892
[Pasta at the Parma restaurant
Hee Tae infiltrated]

794
00:32:29,892 --> 00:32:32,695
What sets our restaurant apart is

795
00:32:32,695 --> 00:32:36,031
fresh pasta made on the spot.

796
00:32:36,031 --> 00:32:39,702
[Fresh pasta made on the spot, daily]
Every single pasta here is fresh.

797
00:32:39,702 --> 00:32:41,470
- When an order comes in...
- Right then?

798
00:32:41,470 --> 00:32:43,038
- That's when you roll the dough.
- For real?

799
00:32:43,038 --> 00:32:44,540
[Once ordered, cooked from the dough stage]

800
00:32:44,540 --> 00:32:46,041
[Cheese tortellini]
So wide varieties too.

801
00:32:46,041 --> 00:32:47,143
[Pheasant agnolotti]
Pheasant.

802
00:32:47,143 --> 00:32:49,445
[Broth anolini]
Broth. Dumpling soup.

803
00:32:49,445 --> 00:32:51,279
[Potato tortelli]
This one's potato.

804
00:32:51,881 --> 00:32:53,716
[Packed with guests from all over Italy
for the fresh pasta]

805
00:32:53,716 --> 00:32:55,451
- They do all that live.
- That's wild.

806
00:32:55,451 --> 00:32:56,652
Why go that far?

807
00:32:56,652 --> 00:33:00,222
- To use the freshest pasta possible.
- For fresher pasta.

808
00:33:00,222 --> 00:33:02,425
They do that every single day.

809
00:33:02,425 --> 00:33:04,493
That's no easy feat.

810
00:33:04,493 --> 00:33:08,063
[The yolks Hee Tae worked hard separating]
You get eggs, this, and...

811
00:33:08,063 --> 00:33:09,764
Put them in here.

812
00:33:12,187 --> 00:33:14,303
[Mixed with flour]
No water goes in this?

813
00:33:14,303 --> 00:33:15,638
- No water.
- You don't add water for pasta.

814
00:33:15,638 --> 00:33:18,607
Okay. Then press the start button.

815
00:33:19,775 --> 00:33:22,111
- Yes. Okay.
- Some regions use water,

816
00:33:22,111 --> 00:33:23,245
some use only eggs,

817
00:33:23,245 --> 00:33:25,392
[Yolks plus flour, run through the mixer]
some use only yolks. It all varies.

818
00:33:25,392 --> 00:33:26,559
- Okay.
- Finish?

819
00:33:26,559 --> 00:33:28,484
Yes. Open.

820
00:33:28,484 --> 00:33:30,252
[Yellow pasta dough comes together easily]

821
00:33:31,592 --> 00:33:32,688
Okay.

822
00:33:32,688 --> 00:33:35,191
[Putting the dough into a bag, but...]

823
00:33:35,191 --> 00:33:36,392
[Peek]

824
00:33:36,392 --> 00:33:38,226
Oh, what?

825
00:33:38,994 --> 00:33:41,464
[The boss is watching]

826
00:33:41,464 --> 00:33:42,731
So scary.

827
00:33:42,731 --> 00:33:44,333
But his face is, well, basically...

828
00:33:44,333 --> 00:33:46,101
I couldn't work there.

829
00:33:46,101 --> 00:33:48,036
I couldn't work in a place like that.

830
00:33:49,182 --> 00:33:51,052
[Hee Tae, hit with random spot checks nonstop]
He's really like a school principal.

831
00:33:51,052 --> 00:33:52,325
So uncomfortable.

832
00:33:52,325 --> 00:33:53,659
- Let's go.
- Yes.

833
00:33:53,659 --> 00:33:55,921
[But his real identity, as you know...]

834
00:33:57,446 --> 00:33:59,315
[Korea's pasta maestro, Sam Kim]

835
00:33:59,315 --> 00:34:01,519
Right.

836
00:34:01,519 --> 00:34:05,287
[Fresh pasta is basically
master-level for him!]

837
00:34:05,287 --> 00:34:08,924
[Will he show his skill while undercover?]

838
00:34:08,924 --> 00:34:10,693
- You've got to push the air out of here.
- Okay.

839
00:34:10,693 --> 00:34:12,261
- Put out the air.
- Yes.

840
00:34:12,261 --> 00:34:14,184
[All the air must come out of the bag]

841
00:34:14,184 --> 00:34:15,258
[Press]

842
00:34:15,258 --> 00:34:17,399
- Okay.
- What's this step you're doing now?

843
00:34:17,399 --> 00:34:19,325
To let the dough rest, so...

844
00:34:19,325 --> 00:34:21,737
[Knows this all too well]
- That's okay. - Oh, balling it up.

845
00:34:21,737 --> 00:34:24,406
[Now, green pasta dough with spinach]
- That one has spinach in it? - Spinach.

846
00:34:24,406 --> 00:34:26,208
Press the button.

847
00:34:26,208 --> 00:34:28,509
- Until it all comes together.
- Okay.

848
00:34:29,912 --> 00:34:34,016
[Instructions are just a helping hand]

849
00:34:34,016 --> 00:34:35,384
It's all good.

850
00:34:35,384 --> 00:34:37,853
[Harder for the maestro to mess up]

851
00:34:37,853 --> 00:34:40,422
[Add the spinach base into the flour and...]

852
00:34:40,422 --> 00:34:43,634
[Today's green pasta dough batch, ready]

853
00:34:46,896 --> 00:34:49,865
[Air out in no time flat too]

854
00:34:49,865 --> 00:34:51,033
Lu.

855
00:34:51,033 --> 00:34:52,067
Looks good.

856
00:34:52,067 --> 00:34:54,202
On the cart.

857
00:34:54,937 --> 00:34:59,542
[Difficulty: easy]
[Today's dough prep, cleared]

858
00:34:59,542 --> 00:35:02,244
[Model rookie vibes from day one]
Okay.

859
00:35:02,244 --> 00:35:03,612
[Next prep task: making gelato]
We make gelato.

860
00:35:03,612 --> 00:35:05,180
- Gelato.
- Okay.

861
00:35:05,180 --> 00:35:08,350
This place is super famous for that gelato.

862
00:35:08,350 --> 00:35:10,386
Just looking at it, it looks delicious.

863
00:35:10,386 --> 00:35:12,054
Look at it stretch.

864
00:35:12,054 --> 00:35:13,856
- Did you bring the recipe back?
- I've got it.

865
00:35:13,856 --> 00:35:15,257
Share some with me too...

866
00:35:15,257 --> 00:35:16,425
What's he saying?

867
00:35:16,425 --> 00:35:17,893
- Go learn it yourself.
- No.

868
00:35:17,893 --> 00:35:19,962
- Go to Parma and learn it.
- Just the recipe. That boss is scary.

869
00:35:19,962 --> 00:35:21,764
- The ingredients are different.
- Just the recipe.

870
00:35:21,764 --> 00:35:23,198
[Sam Kim, 27-year veteran, undercover]
Gelato?

871
00:35:23,198 --> 00:35:24,733
I've never made gelato before.

872
00:35:24,733 --> 00:35:26,447
But it's not really difficult,

873
00:35:26,447 --> 00:35:28,971
it's all about the ratios.

874
00:35:28,971 --> 00:35:30,706
- Four!
- Four?

875
00:35:30,706 --> 00:35:32,174
- Latte.
- Latte.

876
00:35:32,174 --> 00:35:34,476
- Just four cartons of milk.
- Yes.

877
00:35:34,476 --> 00:35:36,847
[Can he breeze through first-time gelato?]

878
00:35:37,813 --> 00:35:42,084
[Pours in four liters of milk]

879
00:35:42,084 --> 00:35:47,122
One coffee bean per liter of milk.

880
00:35:47,122 --> 00:35:49,792
Four liters of milk, so four beans.

881
00:35:49,792 --> 00:35:50,993
[Four coffee beans, plop]

882
00:35:50,993 --> 00:35:52,761
Okay?

883
00:35:52,761 --> 00:35:54,997
[What does Lucrezia pull out next?]

884
00:35:54,997 --> 00:35:57,333
- Vanilla?
- Exactly.

885
00:35:57,333 --> 00:35:59,201
[Vanilla bean]
That gets lightly...

886
00:35:59,201 --> 00:36:01,737
- steeped, together with the vanilla bean.
- Yes.

887
00:36:01,737 --> 00:36:02,838
[Four coffee beans,
vanilla bean for color and aroma]

888
00:36:02,838 --> 00:36:04,106
[Gulp]

889
00:36:04,106 --> 00:36:07,343
[First tool appears!]

890
00:36:07,343 --> 00:36:08,777
[Press]
Vanilla bean.

891
00:36:08,777 --> 00:36:11,447
[The form is already on point]
Now that's real vanilla.

892
00:36:11,447 --> 00:36:14,483
[Splitting the vanilla bean like a pro]

893
00:36:14,483 --> 00:36:15,918
[Side glance]

894
00:36:15,918 --> 00:36:17,718
[He's pretty good, huh?]
Okay.

895
00:36:20,422 --> 00:36:21,490
[Precise]

896
00:36:21,490 --> 00:36:22,570
Detail.

897
00:36:22,570 --> 00:36:24,293
You've got to scrape the seeds out from inside.

898
00:36:24,293 --> 00:36:27,229
Stuff like that,
the body just reacts on its own.

899
00:36:27,229 --> 00:36:28,998
So when you see this kind of thing,

900
00:36:28,998 --> 00:36:31,634
honestly, because prepping vanilla is...

901
00:36:31,634 --> 00:36:33,068
- Right.
- Non-chefs don't really know how.

902
00:36:33,068 --> 00:36:35,738
They can't help but pick up on it, honestly.

903
00:36:35,738 --> 00:36:38,173
"This guy's pretty at home in a kitchen."

904
00:36:38,173 --> 00:36:40,643
[Lips pressed tight]
This is too obvious, isn't it?

905
00:36:40,643 --> 00:36:42,244
[Staring]

906
00:36:42,244 --> 00:36:44,008
Okay.

907
00:36:45,214 --> 00:36:47,716
[Passed]

908
00:36:47,716 --> 00:36:49,752
[Vanilla bean, in it goes]

909
00:36:49,752 --> 00:36:50,786
[Adding lemon zest, too]

910
00:36:50,786 --> 00:36:52,586
Zest.

911
00:36:53,922 --> 00:36:57,004
[Just the yellow part, swift and clean]
If you go all the way into the pith,

912
00:36:57,004 --> 00:36:59,194
[Now that's a veteran rookie]
some folks accidentally shave that by mistake.

913
00:36:59,194 --> 00:37:01,530
If you do, it turns bitter,

914
00:37:01,530 --> 00:37:03,332
so you shouldn't, but he's doing it just right.

915
00:37:03,332 --> 00:37:05,000
This needs to be boiled.

916
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:06,702
- Got it.
- Okay.

917
00:37:06,702 --> 00:37:09,271
[Senior Lu hands off the base-boiling task]
You can put it here.

918
00:37:09,271 --> 00:37:12,608
[Then steps away for a moment...]
Giampi, I'll go see granchef, be back in a sec.

919
00:37:12,608 --> 00:37:15,644
[But...]

920
00:37:15,644 --> 00:37:16,879
[He's supposed to boil it...]

921
00:37:16,879 --> 00:37:18,647
He's not boiling it.

922
00:37:18,647 --> 00:37:19,415
[Why is he hesitating...?]

923
00:37:19,415 --> 00:37:21,950
[Glancing around]

924
00:37:21,950 --> 00:37:23,919
[Surveys the burner situation]

925
00:37:23,919 --> 00:37:25,869
[Busy]

926
00:37:26,922 --> 00:37:29,258
- It's like, "Am I even allowed to do that?"
- Exactly.

927
00:37:29,258 --> 00:37:30,926
Right.

928
00:37:30,926 --> 00:37:34,662
- So that's why you keep hesitating.
- He's reading the room.

929
00:37:35,330 --> 00:37:37,130
[Side glance]

930
00:37:38,901 --> 00:37:42,004
What's your favorite Italian dish?

931
00:37:42,004 --> 00:37:46,110
[Head chef hits him with a question]
What's your favorite Italian dish?

932
00:37:46,110 --> 00:37:47,376
[Tense]
Italian plate.

933
00:37:47,376 --> 00:37:48,510
- Italian plate.
- Pasta.

934
00:37:48,510 --> 00:37:49,611
- Pasta?
- Yes.

935
00:37:49,611 --> 00:37:51,213
[A textbook answer with a smile]

936
00:37:51,213 --> 00:37:53,417
Out of pastas like carbonara or tortellini,

937
00:37:53,417 --> 00:37:57,052
what's your absolute favorite?

938
00:37:57,052 --> 00:38:00,391
- Tomato and basil!
- Tomato and basil? Okay.

939
00:38:00,391 --> 00:38:02,477
Tomato pasta?

940
00:38:02,477 --> 00:38:04,393
[Head chef pleased]
Hee Tae knows the classics!

941
00:38:04,393 --> 00:38:06,228
[Smile]

942
00:38:06,228 --> 00:38:08,497
- Oh, he likes hearing this kind of thing.
- It matters.

943
00:38:08,497 --> 00:38:10,432
- It's the classic.
- You've got to go classic.

944
00:38:10,432 --> 00:38:12,835
- Classic, no question.
- If you say, "I like cod roe pasta..."

945
00:38:12,835 --> 00:38:15,170
- No, you can't do that, it shows right away.
- You can't do that.

946
00:38:15,170 --> 00:38:17,072
It's clear as day what answer he wants.

947
00:38:17,072 --> 00:38:18,674
[Deep reflection]
So cod roe pasta is a no-go, huh.

948
00:38:18,674 --> 00:38:19,975
- Cod roe.
- No way.

949
00:38:19,975 --> 00:38:21,210
[Firm]
Cod roe, oh man.

950
00:38:21,210 --> 00:38:22,111
The classic pasta is tomato.

951
00:38:22,111 --> 00:38:24,713
- You've got to go classic.
- Pomodoro pasta.

952
00:38:24,713 --> 00:38:26,515
[With Simone's help]
That's the base.

953
00:38:26,515 --> 00:38:27,416
[Boiling the gelato base]

954
00:38:27,416 --> 00:38:29,485
- We'll leave this here.
- Yes.

955
00:38:29,485 --> 00:38:32,688
- In the meantime, you need to crack the eggs.
- Eggs.

956
00:38:32,688 --> 00:38:34,589
Yolks only.

957
00:38:35,657 --> 00:38:37,192
They really use a ton of eggs.

958
00:38:37,192 --> 00:38:38,726
[Probably the 187th egg cracked]

959
00:38:44,133 --> 00:38:46,435
[He clearly said to separate the yolks, but...]

960
00:38:46,435 --> 00:38:48,503
He said "tuorlo," didn't he?

961
00:38:49,738 --> 00:38:50,973
[Skips separating, just drops them in]

962
00:38:50,973 --> 00:38:53,341
Chef, you made a lot of slip-ups at first.

963
00:38:53,976 --> 00:38:55,210
[Cracking a whole tray with no separating]

964
00:38:55,210 --> 00:38:58,265
[Why is he doing that?]

965
00:39:00,315 --> 00:39:02,973
[Maybe he misheard?]

966
00:39:05,654 --> 00:39:07,589
Oh, he separates them by hand.

967
00:39:07,589 --> 00:39:09,191
[Fishing the yolks back out by hand]

968
00:39:09,191 --> 00:39:10,526
You can do it faster that way.

969
00:39:10,526 --> 00:39:12,828
By hand, separating like that. Knew it.

970
00:39:12,828 --> 00:39:14,496
- Veteran energy showing through.
- Definitely.

971
00:39:14,496 --> 00:39:16,665
[That right there is a 27-year veteran class]

972
00:39:16,665 --> 00:39:18,267
[Yolks separated clean and done]

973
00:39:18,267 --> 00:39:20,269
- Yeah, way faster.
- Way faster.

974
00:39:20,269 --> 00:39:22,738
[A 27-year vet rookie moves on another level]

975
00:39:22,738 --> 00:39:24,506
This.

976
00:39:24,506 --> 00:39:27,042
[The gelato base he boiled earlier]

977
00:39:27,042 --> 00:39:28,844
Yeah.

978
00:39:28,844 --> 00:39:30,579
- It's good.
- Yeah, it's good.

979
00:39:30,579 --> 00:39:32,548
[Friendly mentor and model rookie]
Good.

980
00:39:32,548 --> 00:39:34,817
Pour this in.

981
00:39:34,817 --> 00:39:37,653
[Time to mix the gelato base into the eggs]

982
00:39:37,653 --> 00:39:40,055
Slowly?

983
00:39:40,055 --> 00:39:42,024
No. Stop.

984
00:39:42,024 --> 00:39:43,225
No. Stop.

985
00:39:43,225 --> 00:39:44,793
He spilled it all.

986
00:39:44,793 --> 00:39:46,895
[Spills]
Oh, no.

987
00:39:46,895 --> 00:39:49,097
- Did you spill it on purpose?
- You messed up on purpose, right?

988
00:39:49,097 --> 00:39:50,566
[Immediate interrogation mode: ON]
- To play up the rookie thing. - No, no.

989
00:39:50,566 --> 00:39:51,967
- He is Undercover Chef, after all.
- That's such a waste.

990
00:39:51,967 --> 00:39:53,802
- The measurements are getting blown apart.
- That's...

991
00:39:53,802 --> 00:39:56,572
The editing makes it look worse,
I only spilled a little...

992
00:39:56,572 --> 00:39:58,407
- It looked like a lot.
- That much is seriously...

993
00:39:58,407 --> 00:40:00,075
- That's the Han River.
- It's a whole scoop.

994
00:40:00,075 --> 00:40:01,443
- It's the Han River.
- A whole scoop.

995
00:40:01,443 --> 00:40:02,878
Slowly?

996
00:40:02,878 --> 00:40:04,613
No. Stop.

997
00:40:04,613 --> 00:40:07,115
[Flustered]

998
00:40:07,115 --> 00:40:08,917
If I can give you some advice...

999
00:40:08,917 --> 00:40:11,753
[Tensing up]

1000
00:40:11,753 --> 00:40:13,288
Not like this.

1001
00:40:13,288 --> 00:40:14,556
Like this,

1002
00:40:14,556 --> 00:40:16,158
but...

1003
00:40:16,158 --> 00:40:18,460
[Senior Lu demonstrates hands-on]
Got it.

1004
00:40:18,460 --> 00:40:20,996
- All at once!
- Got it.

1005
00:40:20,996 --> 00:40:24,233
I worried the yolks would overcook.

1006
00:40:24,233 --> 00:40:25,601
Since the base temperature is high.

1007
00:40:25,601 --> 00:40:28,604
So you let some drip
on the floor on purpose, too.

1008
00:40:28,604 --> 00:40:30,772
[Teasing]

1009
00:40:30,772 --> 00:40:32,474
[Doing great until one slip-up]

1010
00:40:32,474 --> 00:40:36,879
[Reading the room out of nowhere]

1011
00:40:36,879 --> 00:40:39,848
[Pour it in here]

1012
00:40:39,848 --> 00:40:44,887
[Once the gelato base is ready too]

1013
00:40:44,887 --> 00:40:46,922
[Lunch service begins, 12:00 PM]

1014
00:40:46,922 --> 00:40:48,156
- Is that an actual bell?
- Yeah.

1015
00:40:48,156 --> 00:40:49,691
The cathedral is right next door.

1016
00:40:49,691 --> 00:40:51,226
- So when it rings, work starts.
- Yeah.

1017
00:40:51,226 --> 00:40:53,828
[The bell tolls noon]

1018
00:40:54,463 --> 00:40:58,467
[First service! Hee Tae's debut guests arrive]

1019
00:40:58,467 --> 00:41:02,437
[Once service kicks off]

1020
00:41:02,437 --> 00:41:05,574
[Everyone's swamped with their own work]

1021
00:41:05,574 --> 00:41:09,611
[Except, well, one guy...]

1022
00:41:09,611 --> 00:41:12,047
[Everyone but Hee Tae is busy]

1023
00:41:12,047 --> 00:41:13,582
[Tsk...]
Well...

1024
00:41:13,582 --> 00:41:16,184
- Everyone's busy except me.
- Got to just stand still, I guess.

1025
00:41:16,184 --> 00:41:18,987
Why didn't you ask them what to do?

1026
00:41:18,987 --> 00:41:20,122
Honestly,

1027
00:41:20,122 --> 00:41:22,557
I have no idea what to do.

1028
00:41:22,557 --> 00:41:25,260
- You just should read the room.
- Everyone is moving like crazy.

1029
00:41:25,260 --> 00:41:28,730
So at a moment like that,
a writer or producer...

1030
00:41:28,730 --> 00:41:31,466
They should step in, right?

1031
00:41:31,466 --> 00:41:33,168
[Crew that played dumb to the end]
Right, no one's looking out for him.

1032
00:41:33,168 --> 00:41:34,336
In a moment like this...

1033
00:41:34,336 --> 00:41:36,571
[Sam Kim, 27-year veteran, former owner chef]
When a new hire comes to our restaurant,

1034
00:41:36,571 --> 00:41:39,041
they look exactly like that,
right at the start of service.

1035
00:41:39,041 --> 00:41:41,943
- It reminded me of our new hires.
- Yeah.

1036
00:41:43,578 --> 00:41:45,547
- Lu.
- Yes.

1037
00:41:45,547 --> 00:41:47,700
Need a hand?

1038
00:41:47,700 --> 00:41:48,750
No.

1039
00:41:48,750 --> 00:41:52,120
- Anything I can do?
- Now...

1040
00:41:52,120 --> 00:41:53,889
Not just yet.

1041
00:41:53,889 --> 00:41:55,324
- Yes.
- Okay.

1042
00:41:55,324 --> 00:41:56,987
[Total chaos]

1043
00:42:00,028 --> 00:42:02,631
[Are you doing any work?]

1044
00:42:02,631 --> 00:42:05,500
- Look at his face. That look is just...
- Terrifying.

1045
00:42:05,500 --> 00:42:09,304
Looks like, "Is this really the time for that?"

1046
00:42:09,304 --> 00:42:11,440
[Always watching]

1047
00:42:11,440 --> 00:42:14,810
- Now, watch carefully what Lucrezia does,
- Yes.

1048
00:42:14,810 --> 00:42:16,445
[Senior Lu's fresh pasta task]
then you give it a try.

1049
00:42:16,445 --> 00:42:18,146
- Okay?
- Yes.

1050
00:42:18,146 --> 00:42:20,248
[Fresh pasta already?]

1051
00:42:20,248 --> 00:42:21,116
[A golden chance, finally here]

1052
00:42:21,116 --> 00:42:24,586
He showed up
and they're throwing him straight in.

1053
00:42:24,586 --> 00:42:29,157
How many years have you worked here?

1054
00:42:29,157 --> 00:42:32,227
Me? Six years.

1055
00:42:32,227 --> 00:42:33,528
Six years?

1056
00:42:33,528 --> 00:42:36,165
She said she's the rookie,
but she was way too good from the jump.

1057
00:42:36,165 --> 00:42:38,533
- She was the rookie for six whole years.
- She's been there a while.

1058
00:42:38,533 --> 00:42:40,168
[Six-year work, rookie Hee Tae has to do?]

1059
00:42:40,168 --> 00:42:43,338
I'll show you the cheese tortelli now.

1060
00:42:43,338 --> 00:42:46,408
You'll try it yourself with what I prepped.

1061
00:42:46,408 --> 00:42:49,894
[Cheese tortelli?]

1062
00:42:50,746 --> 00:42:52,914
[Parma restaurant's signature, cheese tortelli]

1063
00:42:52,914 --> 00:42:54,683
[One of the fresh pasta items on the menu]
Tortelli in Korean terms is basically

1064
00:42:54,683 --> 00:42:55,751
- like a dumpling.
- It's a dumpling.

1065
00:42:55,751 --> 00:42:57,386
[Filling made of cheese and eggs]
Pasta with filling inside.

1066
00:42:57,386 --> 00:43:00,389
This place's signature item, basically.

1067
00:43:00,389 --> 00:43:01,990
The pasta is eaten the most in that region.

1068
00:43:01,990 --> 00:43:03,692
Honestly, you find it at every spot.

1069
00:43:03,692 --> 00:43:05,427
[Most beloved tortelli in northern Italy]

1070
00:43:05,427 --> 00:43:06,795
- This one would be tasty though.
- Hands down delicious.

1071
00:43:06,795 --> 00:43:08,096
[Stuffing packed inside fresh pasta]
It's good.

1072
00:43:08,096 --> 00:43:10,065
[Cheese tortelli filling]

1073
00:43:10,065 --> 00:43:12,401
[Yum]

1074
00:43:12,401 --> 00:43:13,335
Is it ricotta?

1075
00:43:13,335 --> 00:43:15,971
Yes, ricotta cheese and spinach-type greens,

1076
00:43:15,971 --> 00:43:17,639
parmesan cheese,

1077
00:43:17,639 --> 00:43:19,574
and eggs.

1078
00:43:20,667 --> 00:43:23,211
[Yolks plus flour, run through the mixer]
The machine is so nice.

1079
00:43:23,211 --> 00:43:25,714
- A dough-rolling machine.
- That's unusual.

1080
00:43:25,714 --> 00:43:28,050
[Piping out the filling with a bag]

1081
00:43:28,050 --> 00:43:30,218
Honestly...

1082
00:43:30,218 --> 00:43:32,120
filled-style

1083
00:43:32,120 --> 00:43:35,023
dumpling-style pasta isn't
something I've done much.

1084
00:43:35,023 --> 00:43:36,625
Usually, with fresh pasta,

1085
00:43:36,625 --> 00:43:40,562
it's long noodles,
which is mostly what I worked with.

1086
00:43:40,562 --> 00:43:43,031
This format wasn't really familiar to me.

1087
00:43:43,031 --> 00:43:44,525
The thing is, in Korea,

1088
00:43:44,525 --> 00:43:47,369
[Tough]
this kind of pasta is rarely made, really.

1089
00:43:47,369 --> 00:43:48,538
[Sam Kim's actual pasta]

1090
00:43:48,538 --> 00:43:51,273
[Could be unfamiliar
to a long-pasta cook like him]

1091
00:43:51,273 --> 00:43:53,708
Because in our country, dumplings dominate.

1092
00:43:53,708 --> 00:43:54,409
- Right.
- Exactly.

1093
00:43:54,409 --> 00:43:56,344
- That's part of it.
- We always go for the basics...

1094
00:43:56,344 --> 00:43:57,546
When you take a bite of tortelli,

1095
00:43:57,546 --> 00:43:59,114
it has to beat a dumpling.

1096
00:43:59,114 --> 00:44:01,583
Koreans hear "pasta"
and picture spaghetti, so...

1097
00:44:01,583 --> 00:44:04,252
- Right.
- Most people don't see that as pasta.

1098
00:44:04,252 --> 00:44:08,190
[Watching closely]

1099
00:44:08,190 --> 00:44:10,725
[Cover with dough, wrap the filling]

1100
00:44:10,725 --> 00:44:12,994
[Dividing the filling by hand]

1101
00:44:12,994 --> 00:44:15,464
- Oh, so this is how they shape it.
- Yeah.

1102
00:44:15,464 --> 00:44:16,998
[Focused]
They don't weigh anything in grams.

1103
00:44:16,998 --> 00:44:18,567
- They don't.
- There's no such thing as grams here.

1104
00:44:18,567 --> 00:44:20,035
Italians don't do that, never.

1105
00:44:20,035 --> 00:44:23,171
[Handwork fascinates
even a 27-year veteran rookie]

1106
00:44:23,171 --> 00:44:25,173
[Squish]
She does it by hand like this.

1107
00:44:25,173 --> 00:44:28,043
- Yes, all like that...
- That kind of approach is fun too.

1108
00:44:28,043 --> 00:44:29,077
What about this way?

1109
00:44:29,077 --> 00:44:30,312
Yes.

1110
00:44:30,312 --> 00:44:31,413
[Technique like this!]

1111
00:44:31,413 --> 00:44:34,716
I use this finger,
but you can use a different one.

1112
00:44:34,716 --> 00:44:35,784
How...

1113
00:44:35,784 --> 00:44:37,052
[Full-on engaged mode]

1114
00:44:37,052 --> 00:44:38,265
Each chef's hands would give it

1115
00:44:38,265 --> 00:44:39,354
- a different shape.
- Right.

1116
00:44:39,354 --> 00:44:41,523
- Depending on thickness and such.
- That's the charm of it.

1117
00:44:41,523 --> 00:44:43,658
[Picking up the craft naturally]
The charm of Italian food.

1118
00:44:44,392 --> 00:44:46,228
She teaches it really well.

1119
00:44:46,228 --> 00:44:48,897
One more round and I think I could pull it off.

1120
00:44:48,897 --> 00:44:50,432
[Brimming with confidence]

1121
00:44:50,432 --> 00:44:52,567
Order in!

1122
00:44:52,567 --> 00:44:55,237
[Orders start pouring in now]
Okay, one culaccia, two cakes, one polenta

1123
00:44:55,237 --> 00:44:57,873
a parmigiano, then risotto.

1124
00:44:57,873 --> 00:44:59,608
Yes.

1125
00:44:59,608 --> 00:45:03,111
- There are so many guests.
- It really is a place that's always packed.

1126
00:45:03,111 --> 00:45:05,981
There's also a room in the back here,

1127
00:45:05,981 --> 00:45:08,550
and the room was nearly full too.

1128
00:45:08,550 --> 00:45:11,019
[Quick peek]

1129
00:45:11,019 --> 00:45:12,687
They write it all out by hand.

1130
00:45:12,687 --> 00:45:14,001
But since it's all handwritten,

1131
00:45:14,001 --> 00:45:15,590
- it's harder.
- Handwriting makes it hard to read.

1132
00:45:15,590 --> 00:45:17,605
I can't make out a single word.

1133
00:45:17,605 --> 00:45:19,580
What are you prepping right now?

1134
00:45:19,580 --> 00:45:20,795
Yeah.

1135
00:45:20,795 --> 00:45:23,064
We make the cheese tortelli first.

1136
00:45:27,169 --> 00:45:31,373
Eight tortelli per serving.

1137
00:45:31,373 --> 00:45:33,541
- Eight?
- Yes.

1138
00:45:34,676 --> 00:45:36,978
[Lay eight fillings on top of the dough]

1139
00:45:36,978 --> 00:45:38,907
Make them match.

1140
00:45:38,907 --> 00:45:40,115
[Fold it in half]

1141
00:45:40,115 --> 00:45:41,816
Stretch a bit.

1142
00:45:41,816 --> 00:45:44,594
Set it nicely behind.

1143
00:45:44,594 --> 00:45:45,690
Okay.

1144
00:45:45,690 --> 00:45:47,262
[Eagle eye]
What about the flour?

1145
00:45:47,262 --> 00:45:49,163
Oh, sorry.

1146
00:45:54,196 --> 00:45:55,275
You've got to sprinkle the flour.

1147
00:45:55,275 --> 00:45:56,765
- You've got to sprinkle flour.
- Flour needs to go on.

1148
00:45:56,765 --> 00:45:58,099
- Because it's fresh pasta.
- Right.

1149
00:45:58,099 --> 00:45:59,759
If you skip it, everything sticks together.

1150
00:45:59,759 --> 00:46:01,503
- Oh, right.
- Do it like this.

1151
00:46:01,503 --> 00:46:03,805
If you like, rest your index finger,

1152
00:46:03,805 --> 00:46:05,907
then pinch with your pinky.

1153
00:46:05,907 --> 00:46:08,143
Pinch and pull.

1154
00:46:08,143 --> 00:46:10,412
Pinch and pull.

1155
00:46:10,412 --> 00:46:11,781
Give it a try.

1156
00:46:16,618 --> 00:46:18,186
Okay.

1157
00:46:18,186 --> 00:46:19,554
The tortelli gets made
and sent out on the spot too?

1158
00:46:19,554 --> 00:46:20,355
Right, on the spot.

1159
00:46:20,355 --> 00:46:22,099
- That makes no sense.
- Everything is live here.

1160
00:46:22,099 --> 00:46:23,679
It's unreal.

1161
00:46:24,326 --> 00:46:26,861
Next up...

1162
00:46:27,529 --> 00:46:29,053
Pull more.

1163
00:46:30,699 --> 00:46:32,599
- Pull more.
- I see.

1164
00:46:34,402 --> 00:46:35,937
After that...

1165
00:46:35,937 --> 00:46:39,207
[Like this!]

1166
00:46:39,207 --> 00:46:40,275
Here.

1167
00:46:40,275 --> 00:46:42,859
[Trims the top with a carving knife]

1168
00:46:45,580 --> 00:46:47,090
As thin as possible!

1169
00:46:48,583 --> 00:46:50,852
Give it a try.

1170
00:46:50,852 --> 00:46:53,755
Out of five days, you're not even halfway in.

1171
00:46:53,755 --> 00:46:55,723
Not even half a day done.

1172
00:46:55,723 --> 00:46:56,691
Just half a day.

1173
00:46:56,691 --> 00:46:59,013
- It's all good, no worries.
- Right.

1174
00:47:01,096 --> 00:47:02,030
Okay.

1175
00:47:02,030 --> 00:47:04,666
[Wild hands, Hee Tae on mission impossible]

1176
00:47:04,666 --> 00:47:05,967
Looks good.

1177
00:47:05,967 --> 00:47:08,336
- Put this here.
- Yes.

1178
00:47:08,336 --> 00:47:09,971
Then, these...

1179
00:47:09,971 --> 00:47:12,607
[Star rookie Hee Tae breezes through tortelli]
on a tray.

1180
00:47:12,607 --> 00:47:13,642
We put them here.

1181
00:47:13,642 --> 00:47:15,210
The food going out is slow, isn't it?

1182
00:47:15,210 --> 00:47:17,145
No, it's not slow at all.

1183
00:47:17,145 --> 00:47:18,680
That pasta moves seriously fast.

1184
00:47:18,680 --> 00:47:20,448
[Faster than ramen, tortelli in two min flat]
Drop them in and they're out in two minutes.

1185
00:47:20,448 --> 00:47:22,050
[Surprised]
Really?

1186
00:47:22,050 --> 00:47:24,752
[Not cheese tortelli this time!]
Now we'll do potato tortelli.

1187
00:47:26,187 --> 00:47:28,089
- The potato tortelli, no.
- No?

1188
00:47:28,089 --> 00:47:30,257
The closure is a "pinch" style.

1189
00:47:32,827 --> 00:47:34,129
Take them and pinch them.

1190
00:47:34,129 --> 00:47:35,697
This one is shaped this way too?

1191
00:47:35,697 --> 00:47:37,899
[Potato tortelli sealed by pinching the dough]
Tight and pinch.

1192
00:47:37,899 --> 00:47:42,145
[So what is the difference between the two?]

1193
00:47:42,145 --> 00:47:43,738
[Cheese tortelli has a square shape]

1194
00:47:43,738 --> 00:47:45,440
The shape is tortelli for both,

1195
00:47:45,440 --> 00:47:47,208
- but the grip is a bit different.
- Oh, the grip is different.

1196
00:47:47,208 --> 00:47:48,209
The shape.

1197
00:47:48,209 --> 00:47:51,613
[Potato tortelli is pinched
on both sides, round]

1198
00:47:51,613 --> 00:47:54,816
[Potato tortelli, Cheese tortelli]
To tell them apart, too.

1199
00:47:54,816 --> 00:47:57,218
Then I'll cut this here, hold it,

1200
00:47:57,218 --> 00:47:59,687
grip it precisely again...

1201
00:48:00,288 --> 00:48:04,359
And these need to be sealed.

1202
00:48:04,359 --> 00:48:06,261
Be careful.

1203
00:48:06,261 --> 00:48:08,863
- She teaches every little thing while busy?
- This part has too much

1204
00:48:08,863 --> 00:48:11,232
- Things are about to get seriously hectic.
- excess on the edges.

1205
00:48:11,232 --> 00:48:14,336
It was when a couple of parties
started coming in.

1206
00:48:14,336 --> 00:48:16,438
Looks good, yes.

1207
00:48:16,438 --> 00:48:17,605
Looks good.

1208
00:48:17,605 --> 00:48:19,107
[Swoosh]

1209
00:48:19,107 --> 00:48:20,136
[Swoosh]

1210
00:48:21,843 --> 00:48:23,345
[What's good?]

1211
00:48:23,345 --> 00:48:25,613
Parmigiano?

1212
00:48:25,613 --> 00:48:28,783
[Watching the rookie's every move]

1213
00:48:28,783 --> 00:48:30,851
[Two watchtowers]

1214
00:48:31,553 --> 00:48:34,022
The edges are too wide.

1215
00:48:34,022 --> 00:48:36,725
- Got it.
- When you press down,

1216
00:48:36,725 --> 00:48:40,762
keep it tight, don't spread it out.

1217
00:48:40,762 --> 00:48:44,899
[Tense]

1218
00:48:44,899 --> 00:48:46,935
[Watchtower one]

1219
00:48:46,935 --> 00:48:49,971
[Watching his every move...]

1220
00:48:49,971 --> 00:48:52,373
Let's do one more cheese tortelli.

1221
00:48:53,708 --> 00:48:55,442
Switch spots with me.

1222
00:48:55,442 --> 00:48:58,747
He's thrown straight into the deep end.

1223
00:48:58,747 --> 00:49:01,015
Right, they're piling it on early.

1224
00:49:01,015 --> 00:49:04,454
[Hee Tae mimics what he learned]

1225
00:49:09,958 --> 00:49:11,025
On purpose?

1226
00:49:11,025 --> 00:49:12,127
No, no way.

1227
00:49:12,127 --> 00:49:13,428
[Flinching]

1228
00:49:13,428 --> 00:49:15,663
- It looks kind of spread out.
- More.

1229
00:49:15,663 --> 00:49:17,265
Something looks off.

1230
00:49:17,265 --> 00:49:18,433
More?

1231
00:49:18,433 --> 00:49:20,601
Yeah, just a bit more.

1232
00:49:21,302 --> 00:49:24,907
[Adjusting the spacing]

1233
00:49:27,409 --> 00:49:29,444
That's the fabric part.

1234
00:49:29,444 --> 00:49:32,580
[Carefully piping each one out...]
If it's too full, it won't come out.

1235
00:49:32,580 --> 00:49:34,082
[Hee Tae's tortelli looks uneven]

1236
00:49:34,082 --> 00:49:35,417
[Hee Tae's work, Senior Lu's work]

1237
00:49:35,417 --> 00:49:38,486
[Even spacing, even shape]

1238
00:49:38,486 --> 00:49:40,155
[Well...]

1239
00:49:40,155 --> 00:49:42,558
[Something feels off]

1240
00:49:44,125 --> 00:49:49,630
[The shape looks pretty square at least]

1241
00:49:49,630 --> 00:49:51,866
- You didn't add flour.
- Semolina.

1242
00:49:51,866 --> 00:49:53,168
- Flour.
- Use lots and lots of flour.

1243
00:49:53,168 --> 00:49:55,061
They really dust it heavily here.

1244
00:49:55,061 --> 00:49:56,104
Okay.

1245
00:49:56,104 --> 00:49:57,984
Lots and lots.

1246
00:49:58,740 --> 00:50:00,926
- You can go bigger.
- Bigger?

1247
00:50:00,926 --> 00:50:02,431
Yes.

1248
00:50:03,211 --> 00:50:05,079
- But be careful.
- Okay.

1249
00:50:05,079 --> 00:50:06,714
The filling can't come out.

1250
00:50:06,714 --> 00:50:09,751
Got it?
Next time, make the tortelli a bit bigger.

1251
00:50:09,751 --> 00:50:11,653
- But, okay.
- Yes, thank you.

1252
00:50:11,653 --> 00:50:13,054
[As Hee Tae's tortelli got corrected again]

1253
00:50:13,054 --> 00:50:15,790
[Another order]
Four asparagus, two rabbits,

1254
00:50:15,790 --> 00:50:18,092
[One more cheese tortelli ordered]
one gnocchi, one pasta, grilled, two potatoes.

1255
00:50:18,092 --> 00:50:19,761
Now we do...

1256
00:50:19,761 --> 00:50:21,095
One cheese tortelli, please.

1257
00:50:21,095 --> 00:50:22,764
- Cheese tortelli.
- Yes.

1258
00:50:22,764 --> 00:50:25,341
[Hee Tae's solo chance has arrived]

1259
00:50:26,401 --> 00:50:30,004
[Pulling himself together to make it]

1260
00:50:30,004 --> 00:50:32,841
[Focused]

1261
00:50:32,841 --> 00:50:35,343
[Tense right along with him]

1262
00:50:35,343 --> 00:50:39,314
[The filling looks just right now]

1263
00:50:39,314 --> 00:50:43,218
[Hee Tae moves step by step]

1264
00:50:43,218 --> 00:50:46,696
[But...]

1265
00:50:46,696 --> 00:50:49,223
[At nearly every table]
There's a real crowd today.

1266
00:50:49,223 --> 00:50:51,392
[Cheese tortelli ordered]
It's just simple spinach.

1267
00:50:51,392 --> 00:50:52,927
- Right.
- And ricotta inside.

1268
00:50:52,927 --> 00:50:54,729
[Tables still waiting on tortelli]
The seasoning is spot on.

1269
00:50:54,729 --> 00:50:57,932
The umami inside is incredible.

1270
00:50:57,932 --> 00:51:00,802
[Fumbling]

1271
00:51:00,802 --> 00:51:04,572
[Hee Tae works carefully despite the rush]

1272
00:51:04,572 --> 00:51:06,107
Okay, check the orders.

1273
00:51:06,107 --> 00:51:09,210
[Yet another order!]
One more tortelli order.

1274
00:51:09,210 --> 00:51:11,346
[Cheese tortelli orders keep rolling in]
One tortelli, one agnolotti, a first or...

1275
00:51:11,346 --> 00:51:13,781
Gosh, I can't read any of that.

1276
00:51:13,781 --> 00:51:16,439
[Order rush, no time left!]

1277
00:51:17,852 --> 00:51:22,490
I was getting nervous and anxious.

1278
00:51:22,490 --> 00:51:23,892
From a rookie's standpoint,

1279
00:51:23,892 --> 00:51:25,527
she's got a ton of work to do,

1280
00:51:25,527 --> 00:51:27,562
[Other dishes fly out fast]
and having to babysit me,

1281
00:51:27,562 --> 00:51:28,596
- Pressure...
- I'm stealing her time.

1282
00:51:28,596 --> 00:51:30,064
Right, that's true.

1283
00:51:30,064 --> 00:51:32,834
Are you making the tortelli?

1284
00:51:32,834 --> 00:51:35,136
[Glaring]
The boss is pushing now.

1285
00:51:35,136 --> 00:51:37,738
- Cheese tortelli ready?
- Yes.

1286
00:51:38,606 --> 00:51:40,742
[Finally]

1287
00:51:40,742 --> 00:51:44,479
I'll finish it, give me two minutes.

1288
00:51:44,479 --> 00:51:46,147
[Lucrezia takes over]
She's lost her patience.

1289
00:51:46,147 --> 00:51:48,782
Orders are piling up, knock them out.

1290
00:51:49,654 --> 00:51:52,587
[Lightning speed]

1291
00:51:52,587 --> 00:51:55,405
[Whoa...]

1292
00:51:57,325 --> 00:52:00,761
Service won't run smoothly
if she doesn't move that fast.

1293
00:52:05,433 --> 00:52:07,602
- She's basically a machine.
- A real machine.

1294
00:52:07,602 --> 00:52:09,037
- Hire her as sous chef.
- She'd be one back home.

1295
00:52:09,037 --> 00:52:11,505
[Six years of speed!]
She deserves to be a sous chef.

1296
00:52:12,140 --> 00:52:14,523
[Classic Lucrezia]

1297
00:52:16,010 --> 00:52:17,178
I'll put it here.

1298
00:52:17,178 --> 00:52:18,848
[Cheese tortelli ready in no time]

1299
00:52:20,515 --> 00:52:24,052
Hee Tae was slow on some things,
which is to be expected.

1300
00:52:24,052 --> 00:52:27,622
But during service, there's no time to spare.

1301
00:52:27,622 --> 00:52:30,291
[Nodding]
He has to understand that.

1302
00:52:30,291 --> 00:52:33,061
We've got deadlines to keep.

1303
00:52:33,061 --> 00:52:34,896
That's why I handed it to Lu.

1304
00:52:34,896 --> 00:52:36,506
Now...

1305
00:52:37,966 --> 00:52:40,401
One potato tortelli this time.

1306
00:52:41,269 --> 00:52:44,799
[Now's my real chance to shine!]

1307
00:52:45,840 --> 00:52:48,798
[I, Kim Hee Tae, will prove myself]

1308
00:52:50,144 --> 00:52:54,215
[Careful for the guest, but faster]

1309
00:52:54,215 --> 00:52:56,684
Potato and onion,

1310
00:52:56,684 --> 00:52:58,353
[Fold it in half first]
pureed and mixed in.

1311
00:52:58,353 --> 00:52:59,587
Looks delicious.

1312
00:52:59,587 --> 00:53:02,023
[Doesn't forget the flour either]

1313
00:53:02,023 --> 00:53:05,492
[Quick and no mistakes]

1314
00:53:06,361 --> 00:53:09,988
[Make it perfect and pretty!]

1315
00:53:12,100 --> 00:53:15,003
[Back view begging for praise!]

1316
00:53:15,003 --> 00:53:17,639
[All done? Okay]
Just a moment, please.

1317
00:53:17,639 --> 00:53:20,241
Look there.

1318
00:53:20,241 --> 00:53:21,509
Well...

1319
00:53:21,509 --> 00:53:23,511
- No!
- No?

1320
00:53:23,511 --> 00:53:25,063
What?

1321
00:53:25,063 --> 00:53:26,488
What's the problem?

1322
00:53:27,115 --> 00:53:29,950
- No?
- It's not this shape.

1323
00:53:33,955 --> 00:53:37,859
Potato tortelli is sealed by pinching.

1324
00:53:37,859 --> 00:53:40,028
It's different from cheese tortelli.

1325
00:53:40,028 --> 00:53:42,042
[Cheese tortelli, Potato tortelli]

1326
00:53:42,042 --> 00:53:47,135
[Two tortelli with different seals]

1327
00:53:47,135 --> 00:53:51,973
[Info overload, Hee Tae mixed up the seals]

1328
00:53:51,973 --> 00:53:55,943
[The rookie's mistake falls on Lucrezia]

1329
00:53:55,943 --> 00:53:58,755
[She tries to salvage it...]

1330
00:54:00,682 --> 00:54:02,383
[Tossed out!]
I'm so sorry.

1331
00:54:02,383 --> 00:54:05,353
She tossed it. Oh no.

1332
00:54:05,353 --> 00:54:06,888
[A complete shock]
- Lu's mad. - I'm so sorry.

1333
00:54:06,888 --> 00:54:08,489
- Lu's mad.
- Hold on.

1334
00:54:08,489 --> 00:54:10,858
- She tossed it?
- She tossed it.

1335
00:54:12,293 --> 00:54:13,327
I'm sorry.

1336
00:54:13,327 --> 00:54:14,328
[Easier to toss than to fix]

1337
00:54:14,328 --> 00:54:18,900
[Ears turning red]

1338
00:54:18,900 --> 00:54:21,903
I remember that part too.

1339
00:54:21,903 --> 00:54:23,237
[Shielding him]
He did it on purpose.

1340
00:54:23,237 --> 00:54:25,506
- He faked the mistake.
- It was a real mistake.

1341
00:54:25,506 --> 00:54:26,441
[Tearing up]
Really.

1342
00:54:26,441 --> 00:54:28,176
[Aw...]

1343
00:54:28,176 --> 00:54:29,577
But the thing is...

1344
00:54:29,577 --> 00:54:32,547
That dish was brand new to me.

1345
00:54:32,547 --> 00:54:35,183
If it was something I made daily,

1346
00:54:35,183 --> 00:54:36,184
sure, I'd have been mad.

1347
00:54:36,184 --> 00:54:39,420
But it was my first time trying.

1348
00:54:39,420 --> 00:54:40,767
That's a bit harsh though.

1349
00:54:40,767 --> 00:54:42,924
[Hee Tae sweating]
Day one for a farmer?

1350
00:54:42,924 --> 00:54:44,892
[Pouting]

1351
00:54:44,892 --> 00:54:46,894
I'm sorry.

1352
00:54:52,800 --> 00:54:55,035
<i>It's all fine.</i>

1353
00:54:56,771 --> 00:54:58,571
Thank you.

1354
00:54:59,474 --> 00:55:01,242
He's adorable.

1355
00:55:01,242 --> 00:55:03,544
[Choked up]
That gave me a little comfort.

1356
00:55:03,544 --> 00:55:05,113
- I thought he'd chew me out.
- Right.

1357
00:55:05,113 --> 00:55:08,216
[The thoughtful boss]
He even ran the translation.

1358
00:55:08,216 --> 00:55:10,450
<i>It's all fine.</i>

1359
00:55:12,086 --> 00:55:14,222
Thank you.

1360
00:55:14,222 --> 00:55:18,748
[Dead silent except for Hee Tae]

1361
00:55:19,761 --> 00:55:23,059
[The boss kept it light, but still...]

1362
00:55:23,965 --> 00:55:27,067
[Hee Tae steps aside for his senior]

1363
00:55:27,828 --> 00:55:29,624
[Further and further back]
It's just my first day,

1364
00:55:29,624 --> 00:55:32,573
standing in the middle just gets in the way.

1365
00:55:32,573 --> 00:55:34,776
Better to stay out of it.

1366
00:55:34,776 --> 00:55:36,878
[Quietly]

1367
00:55:36,878 --> 00:55:40,081
In just half a day, the data load,

1368
00:55:40,081 --> 00:55:41,482
- it's too much.
- Way too much.

1369
00:55:41,482 --> 00:55:43,217
They show it once and say, "Do it!"

1370
00:55:43,217 --> 00:55:44,685
- It's confusing.
- It really was tough.

1371
00:55:44,685 --> 00:55:45,453
Yeah, hard.

1372
00:55:45,453 --> 00:55:47,789
[Kim Pung, upset for Sam]
But she just tossed it like that.

1373
00:55:47,789 --> 00:55:50,237
- Nothing I could do.
- She seemed annoyed.

1374
00:55:50,237 --> 00:55:51,759
- She was annoyed.
- Lu was a little annoyed.

1375
00:55:51,759 --> 00:55:52,794
Did you feel sorry?

1376
00:55:52,794 --> 00:55:54,629
- I felt awful.
- Right.

1377
00:55:54,629 --> 00:55:56,831
- She tossed it.
- I wasn't helping.

1378
00:55:56,831 --> 00:55:57,865
But on the other hand...

1379
00:55:57,865 --> 00:55:59,667
There was this thought too.

1380
00:55:59,667 --> 00:56:01,902
"Fine! Just wait a bit."

1381
00:56:03,171 --> 00:56:05,372
[Legendary chef confidence]
A few tries and I'll have it.

1382
00:56:06,774 --> 00:56:10,311
[The dining room nearly cleared out]

1383
00:56:10,311 --> 00:56:12,446
[Service is almost done]

1384
00:56:12,446 --> 00:56:13,714
Thank you.

1385
00:56:13,714 --> 00:56:15,817
[Pulled from pasta after the slip]
After one mistake, you tread carefully.

1386
00:56:15,817 --> 00:56:18,386
He's walking on eggshells now.

1387
00:56:18,386 --> 00:56:20,221
[One thought consumes him]
How...

1388
00:56:20,221 --> 00:56:22,556
can I move up?

1389
00:56:23,791 --> 00:56:26,828
How do I break into this system?

1390
00:56:26,828 --> 00:56:29,297
That's all I kept thinking about.

1391
00:56:29,297 --> 00:56:32,333
[The stove zone]
It's literally only two or three meters.

1392
00:56:32,333 --> 00:56:34,769
[But it feels so far]
Yet breaking in is so hard.

1393
00:56:34,769 --> 00:56:36,404
Right, two or three meters,

1394
00:56:36,404 --> 00:56:37,939
- feels like two or three kilometers.
- Exactly.

1395
00:56:37,939 --> 00:56:40,374
- Feels that far.
- Yeah.

1396
00:56:40,374 --> 00:56:41,609
It's not easy.

1397
00:56:41,609 --> 00:56:43,593
[Can he cross that gap in five days?]

1398
00:56:46,514 --> 00:56:50,318
[Hee Tae pulls out his notebook]

1399
00:56:50,318 --> 00:56:52,919
- What's he writing?
- What is he writing?

1400
00:56:53,988 --> 00:56:56,757
I wrote the recipes down from memory.

1401
00:56:56,757 --> 00:56:59,277
Everything I could recall, top to bottom.

1402
00:56:59,277 --> 00:57:00,336
[Yellow pasta dough recipe]

1403
00:57:00,336 --> 00:57:02,063
[1kg durum, 1kg flour, 15 yolks, 15 eggs]

1404
00:57:02,063 --> 00:57:03,209
[Gelato base recipe]

1405
00:57:03,209 --> 00:57:04,365
[35 yolks, 500g sugar, 4L milk, 1L cream
4 coffee beans, zest of 1 lemon]

1406
00:57:04,365 --> 00:57:06,267
But the dough ratios,

1407
00:57:06,267 --> 00:57:07,802
they don't sit you down to write,

1408
00:57:07,802 --> 00:57:10,037
- they just call it out as they go.
- Right.

1409
00:57:10,037 --> 00:57:13,207
You should bring a recorder next time.

1410
00:57:13,207 --> 00:57:14,809
- Didn't think of a recorder.
- Smart idea.

1411
00:57:14,809 --> 00:57:16,743
A recorder would've worked.

1412
00:57:17,411 --> 00:57:19,947
I'm not used to it yet.

1413
00:57:19,947 --> 00:57:22,416
[Notes are survival]
You have to write it down quickly.

1414
00:57:22,416 --> 00:57:25,486
[Star rookie reviews the recipes]

1415
00:57:25,486 --> 00:57:29,957
[And lunch service wraps up]
Break time at three?

1416
00:57:29,957 --> 00:57:31,459
Come on out.

1417
00:57:31,459 --> 00:57:32,326
[Grabs his beloved notebook]

1418
00:57:32,326 --> 00:57:35,996
Rest up, round two tonight.

1419
00:57:36,864 --> 00:57:37,832
Yeah.

1420
00:57:37,832 --> 00:57:41,030
[Break starts, dreading round two]

1421
00:57:42,637 --> 00:57:44,205
[Pure leisure for the locals]
The weather is gorgeous.

1422
00:57:44,205 --> 00:57:46,274
So nice.

1423
00:57:46,274 --> 00:57:47,308
[Hee Tae has no time to relax]

1424
00:57:47,308 --> 00:57:50,310
- Came back to the room on break?
- Yes.

1425
00:57:51,112 --> 00:57:53,313
[Spreads his notes out again]

1426
00:57:54,248 --> 00:57:58,185
[Studying like it's an exam]

1427
00:57:58,185 --> 00:58:02,389
[Memorizing every recipe he wrote down]
Trying to memorize it all since it's day one.

1428
00:58:03,057 --> 00:58:07,061
[Shaken by the tossed pasta incident]

1429
00:58:07,061 --> 00:58:08,763
[Gives up his break]
He can't even sleep.

1430
00:58:08,763 --> 00:58:10,932
Busy memorizing all that.

1431
00:58:10,932 --> 00:58:14,314
[Three full hours of studying]

1432
00:58:14,314 --> 00:58:17,438
This is showing everything raw.

1433
00:58:17,438 --> 00:58:18,539
[A 27-year veteran chef caught doing homework]

1434
00:58:18,539 --> 00:58:19,707
For sure.

1435
00:58:19,707 --> 00:58:23,778
[Current time, 6:00 PM]

1436
00:58:23,778 --> 00:58:28,049
[Back to work for round two]

1437
00:58:28,049 --> 00:58:31,152
[Unlike his easy morning]

1438
00:58:31,152 --> 00:58:34,221
[Striding in with perfect form]

1439
00:58:34,221 --> 00:58:36,057
His walk got faster.

1440
00:58:36,057 --> 00:58:39,093
[A determined evening commute]

1441
00:58:39,093 --> 00:58:42,531
[Hee Tae heads back in, focused]

1442
00:58:45,800 --> 00:58:47,600
Huh?

1443
00:58:48,336 --> 00:58:50,705
- Isn't everything set up?
- Must be the last one in.

1444
00:58:50,705 --> 00:58:53,007
Wait... no one's here?

1445
00:58:53,007 --> 00:58:55,576
[Empty]
- What's going on? - Not a soul.

1446
00:58:55,576 --> 00:58:57,678
- It's six and nobody's here?
- That's Italy for you.

1447
00:58:57,678 --> 00:58:59,780
[Ten minutes early, zero people]
I went in a little early.

1448
00:58:59,780 --> 00:59:01,949
Around ten minutes before.

1449
00:59:01,949 --> 00:59:03,250
[The "right on the dot" people]
Everyone is punctual

1450
00:59:03,250 --> 00:59:05,519
- to the minute.
- Italian sharp.

1451
00:59:05,519 --> 00:59:08,155
[Meerkat mode on]

1452
00:59:08,155 --> 00:59:12,526
[Alone in the empty kitchen]

1453
00:59:12,526 --> 00:59:15,096
[He cautiously nears the stove zone]

1454
00:59:15,096 --> 00:59:16,130
[Scanning his seniors' territory]

1455
00:59:16,130 --> 00:59:19,166
[The stove zone]

1456
00:59:19,166 --> 00:59:21,368
I kept wrestling with it.

1457
00:59:22,503 --> 00:59:26,474
[The strict division of labor]
Every job is locked in tight.

1458
00:59:26,474 --> 00:59:29,709
[No crossing into other zones]
He's on meat, he's on the fryer.

1459
00:59:30,344 --> 00:59:33,047
- You look pretty worn out.
- I don't know why...

1460
00:59:33,047 --> 00:59:35,816
- He looks so different.
- Dad keeps doing the interview for him.

1461
00:59:35,816 --> 00:59:37,585
- He looks half asleep.
- Exactly.

1462
00:59:37,585 --> 00:59:38,919
[Forget undercover, this post-work interview]

1463
00:59:38,919 --> 00:59:41,956
- He's already asleep.
- His words keep slurring.

1464
00:59:41,956 --> 00:59:45,426
Lu, she'd never grill meat there.

1465
00:59:45,426 --> 00:59:48,629
Just garnish and plating, that's all.

1466
00:59:48,629 --> 00:59:50,031
[Number one head chef, number two sous chef]

1467
00:59:50,031 --> 00:59:52,899
[The only two allowed at the stove]
I really wanted to squeeze in there.

1468
00:59:54,068 --> 00:59:58,906
[Past pasta to the stove in five days?]

1469
00:59:58,906 --> 01:00:01,709
[Let's see...]

1470
01:00:01,709 --> 01:00:04,645
[All he thinks about is climbing up]
<i>Can I get on the cook line?</i>

1471
01:00:04,645 --> 01:00:07,281
<i>Can I move up?</i>

1472
01:00:07,281 --> 01:00:10,451
[He roams freely while no one's there]

1473
01:00:10,451 --> 01:00:12,386
[Number two arrives]
Number two.

1474
01:00:12,386 --> 01:00:14,221
He's here.

1475
01:00:16,076 --> 01:00:19,436
[The owner of the stove area returns]

1476
01:00:20,826 --> 01:00:23,236
[Naturally retreats to the fresh pasta zone]

1477
01:00:26,836 --> 01:00:29,636
[It seems to pass without incident...]

1478
01:00:30,690 --> 01:00:32,196
[He slowly moves back to his spot...]

1479
01:00:32,196 --> 01:00:34,456
[Pretending to be busy]
What are you doing?

1480
01:00:34,456 --> 01:00:36,856
You might as well just squat down.

1481
01:00:36,856 --> 01:00:39,276
[Awkwardly doesn't know what to do]
So awkward, so awkward.

1482
01:00:39,276 --> 01:00:41,049
[I'm checking the ingredients]
Ingredients...

1483
01:00:41,049 --> 01:00:43,234
- What ingredients are you checking?
- Oh...

1484
01:00:44,586 --> 01:00:47,996
[Taking a breath]
I think he's just pacing because he's awkward.

1485
01:00:47,996 --> 01:00:49,786
[Approaching No. 2...]

1486
01:00:50,436 --> 01:00:52,666
Si... Simone... No... Lu?

1487
01:00:52,666 --> 01:00:54,186
Lu here.

1488
01:00:54,186 --> 01:00:57,756
[Pretending to look for Lu]
- Lu? - Is she outside?

1489
01:00:57,756 --> 01:00:58,986
- Lu?
- Lu?

1490
01:00:58,986 --> 01:01:01,919
- Is she outside?
- Huh? She's outside?

1491
01:01:03,076 --> 01:01:06,236
[End of conversation]

1492
01:01:06,236 --> 01:01:07,737
Just like Lu.

1493
01:01:07,737 --> 01:01:09,766
He tried to start a conversation,

1494
01:01:09,766 --> 01:01:11,356
He tried to make an effort.

1495
01:01:11,356 --> 01:01:14,050
But they didn't really respond.

1496
01:01:15,203 --> 01:01:18,867
I thought, "Are they not interested?"

1497
01:01:21,036 --> 01:01:24,056
[Teary]
They didn't seem to care much...

1498
01:01:24,056 --> 01:01:25,947
He felt left out.

1499
01:01:27,496 --> 01:01:29,376
[27-year veteran, hurt by indifference]

1500
01:01:29,376 --> 01:01:30,905
I understood.

1501
01:01:31,926 --> 01:01:34,006
- You did?
- Okay.

1502
01:01:34,006 --> 01:01:37,306
Okay, give me the list.

1503
01:01:38,196 --> 01:01:39,876
Already got it?

1504
01:01:39,876 --> 01:01:42,376
[Work begins with the head chef's word]

1505
01:01:42,376 --> 01:01:44,246
Asparagus.

1506
01:01:44,246 --> 01:01:46,246
- Asparagus.
- Come!

1507
01:01:46,246 --> 01:01:48,776
[Quickly follows the charismatic call]
- Come! - Yes, sir!

1508
01:01:48,776 --> 01:01:49,996
Follow me.

1509
01:01:49,996 --> 01:01:51,286
[Arrived at the storage room]

1510
01:01:51,286 --> 01:01:53,766
Okay, asparagus.

1511
01:01:53,766 --> 01:01:55,206
Did you get the mushrooms?

1512
01:01:55,206 --> 01:01:56,556
- Okay.
- Yes, we have potatoes.

1513
01:01:56,556 --> 01:01:58,216
We just need more dessert ingredients.

1514
01:01:58,216 --> 01:01:59,978
- I'll come back later.
- Did you get the guinea fowl?

1515
01:01:59,978 --> 01:02:01,096
No.

1516
01:02:01,096 --> 01:02:03,386
[Sharp]
- Get five. - Yes, sir.

1517
01:02:03,386 --> 01:02:07,096
[Sensing the intensity]
There's a lot of prep to do.

1518
01:02:07,096 --> 01:02:08,886
[No. 1 seems sharper than this morning]

1519
01:02:08,886 --> 01:02:11,556
[Feeling restless]

1520
01:02:11,556 --> 01:02:14,056
Time is especially tight for dinner.

1521
01:02:14,056 --> 01:02:18,166
[Three hours of prep for lunch]
But we only have an hour for dinner prep.

1522
01:02:18,166 --> 01:02:20,586
But in Italy, dinner service is the real deal.

1523
01:02:20,586 --> 01:02:23,076
Because they eat full courses.

1524
01:02:23,076 --> 01:02:25,546
[A mountain of prep for course meals...]

1525
01:02:25,546 --> 01:02:27,766
[And the Parma restaurant
that Sam Kim infiltrated]

1526
01:02:27,766 --> 01:02:30,166
No reservations. Dinner is full.

1527
01:02:30,166 --> 01:02:31,636
Full.

1528
01:02:31,636 --> 01:02:33,196
No reservations?

1529
01:02:33,196 --> 01:02:34,756
It's full now?

1530
01:02:34,756 --> 01:02:36,255
We're in trouble.

1531
01:02:36,255 --> 01:02:38,156
[Full dinner reservations]
Emergency. Emergency.

1532
01:02:38,156 --> 01:02:39,368
[Customers will be here soon!]

1533
01:02:40,075 --> 01:02:41,626
I can see people are nervous.

1534
01:02:41,626 --> 01:02:42,696
Kitchen chefs

1535
01:02:42,696 --> 01:02:44,916
already feel the pressure.

1536
01:02:44,916 --> 01:02:47,276
[Ready for business]

1537
01:02:47,926 --> 01:02:50,806
[Hee Tae is in position]

1538
01:02:51,476 --> 01:02:52,996
[Glance]

1539
01:02:52,996 --> 01:02:55,596
Lu! Keep an eye out for what he's doing.

1540
01:02:55,596 --> 01:02:58,531
- Sure.
- Keep an eye on him.

1541
01:02:58,531 --> 01:03:00,086
[Cause: He caused a big trouble once]

1542
01:03:00,086 --> 01:03:01,496
I'm scared.

1543
01:03:02,666 --> 01:03:05,693
[Beware Wan]
Look at him looking at Simone.

1544
01:03:06,352 --> 01:03:08,116
Teach Hee Tae how to make torta bread dough.

1545
01:03:08,116 --> 01:03:10,111
- Okay.
- Bread dough?

1546
01:03:10,806 --> 01:03:13,356
[Hee Tae has his first mission]

1547
01:03:16,116 --> 01:03:19,516
[Fried Torta Bread Knead]

1548
01:03:20,216 --> 01:03:22,789
[The dough is cut into cubes]

1549
01:03:22,789 --> 01:03:25,076
[Fluff it up and fry it]
It's plain bread, nothing inside.

1550
01:03:25,076 --> 01:03:26,486
No, bread dough.

1551
01:03:26,486 --> 01:03:28,026
You deep-fry it.

1552
01:03:28,026 --> 01:03:29,236
Like gonggalbbang.

1553
01:03:29,236 --> 01:03:31,652
Like gonggalbbang.

1554
01:03:32,426 --> 01:03:34,426
[Prosciutto on top]
- This looks good. - It's good.

1555
01:03:34,426 --> 01:03:36,006
- It's definitely good.
- Damn it.

1556
01:03:36,006 --> 01:03:38,076
This looks so good. Here.

1557
01:03:38,076 --> 01:03:42,913
[Fried tortas, Parma regional food]
Wherever you go, eat it with that bread.

1558
01:03:43,606 --> 01:03:46,316
[The restaurant's must-order signature dish]
I want to eat it again.

1559
01:03:47,036 --> 01:03:48,728
It's tough.

1560
01:03:48,728 --> 01:03:52,106
[The savory taste of the ham in
between the plain bread is excellent]

1561
01:03:52,106 --> 01:03:55,306
[It's going to sell a lot this evening]

1562
01:03:55,306 --> 01:03:57,996
I wouldn't leave the dough
to someone new like you.

1563
01:03:57,996 --> 01:03:59,956
- That's really important.
- That's right.

1564
01:03:59,956 --> 01:04:01,847
- Someone has to do it.
- Hands are important.

1565
01:04:01,847 --> 01:04:03,556
The hands.

1566
01:04:03,556 --> 01:04:05,336
[Hee Tae is preparing the flour]

1567
01:04:05,336 --> 01:04:07,156
[Senior's comeback]
Okay.

1568
01:04:07,156 --> 01:04:10,996
[The main chef has issued
a strict surveillance order]

1569
01:04:10,996 --> 01:04:13,546
Open the milk.

1570
01:04:13,546 --> 01:04:15,797
Put it in.

1571
01:04:18,216 --> 01:04:20,782
[Starting with opening the milk, step by step]
One liter.

1572
01:04:21,766 --> 01:04:24,966
- Everyone?
- One liter.

1573
01:04:25,656 --> 01:04:29,816
[In this kitchen, I'm a kitchen junior but...]

1574
01:04:30,616 --> 01:04:34,231
[With 27 years of experience,
making dough is a piece of cake]

1575
01:04:34,231 --> 01:04:36,586
[Baking powder]
Okay.

1576
01:04:36,586 --> 01:04:38,236
[Eggs]

1577
01:04:38,236 --> 01:04:39,836
[Fresh yeast]

1578
01:04:39,836 --> 01:04:43,397
[And finally, olive oil]
Next, olive oil.

1579
01:04:44,676 --> 01:04:47,846
[A huge batch of Torta dough
completed in an instant]

1580
01:04:47,846 --> 01:04:52,836
[While Hee Tae shows off his skills
to regain their trust...]

1581
01:04:53,496 --> 01:04:56,876
[Someone enters the kitchen]

1582
01:04:58,086 --> 01:05:00,716
- I'm here.
- Hi, Sorem.

1583
01:05:00,716 --> 01:05:02,966
Hi, Sorem.

1584
01:05:02,966 --> 01:05:04,906
Who is he? Is he new?

1585
01:05:04,906 --> 01:05:06,601
No, he's a regular employee.

1586
01:05:07,256 --> 01:05:09,816
[The mysterious young man
greets everyone casually]

1587
01:05:09,816 --> 01:05:11,036
Hi, Sorem.

1588
01:05:11,036 --> 01:05:13,013
- Hi, Sorem.
- Who is he?

1589
01:05:14,776 --> 01:05:16,806
[Who is he?]

1590
01:05:16,806 --> 01:05:19,303
[The main chef takes the young man
away as soon as he arrives]

1591
01:05:19,956 --> 01:05:23,286
Forget the tuna sauce and mille-feuille.

1592
01:05:23,286 --> 01:05:26,486
Go and get the quails...

1593
01:05:26,486 --> 01:05:27,706
Ten quails!

1594
01:05:27,706 --> 01:05:29,786
[Springing into action]

1595
01:05:31,386 --> 01:05:33,176
Sorem!

1596
01:05:33,176 --> 01:05:34,746
- Sorem.
- Is he Italian?

1597
01:05:34,746 --> 01:05:36,966
- He's Italian.
- Really?

1598
01:05:36,966 --> 01:05:39,606
You need a container for the quails...

1599
01:05:39,606 --> 01:05:42,276
You need something to carry them in...

1600
01:05:42,276 --> 01:05:43,686
How are you going to bring them?

1601
01:05:43,686 --> 01:05:46,116
[Take a plate]
Where did you want to put them?

1602
01:05:46,116 --> 01:05:47,716
Go.

1603
01:05:47,716 --> 01:05:49,946
[Who is this clumsy young man?]
Perfect. Take also the focaccia.

1604
01:05:49,946 --> 01:05:51,236
He's a catfish.

1605
01:05:51,236 --> 01:05:53,153
A catfish?

1606
01:05:53,153 --> 01:05:56,236
[The catfish of the Parma restaurant?]
My name is Sorem, and I'm 23 years old.

1607
01:05:56,236 --> 01:05:59,286
I've been working here since October...

1608
01:05:59,286 --> 01:06:01,076
[Sorem, a senior with 6 months of experience]

1609
01:06:01,076 --> 01:06:04,085
I'm in charge of fresh pasta dough.

1610
01:06:04,906 --> 01:06:06,936
[Another member of the fresh pasta zone]

1611
01:06:06,936 --> 01:06:09,446
They're all so handsome.

1612
01:06:11,156 --> 01:06:12,906
This is a feast for the eyes!

1613
01:06:12,906 --> 01:06:14,566
- Yeah.
- He is quite good-looking.

1614
01:06:14,566 --> 01:06:17,956
[A hidden card for the rush hour]
He's a part-time employee.

1615
01:06:17,956 --> 01:06:21,036
[The junior line along with Hee Tae]

1616
01:06:21,786 --> 01:06:24,826
[Fresh pasta part-timer, Sorem No. 4]

1617
01:06:26,296 --> 01:06:28,476
[The catfish senior appears
to meet the new junior]

1618
01:06:29,816 --> 01:06:33,067
Hello, I'm Hee Tae.

1619
01:06:34,089 --> 01:06:36,144
I'm Hee Tae.

1620
01:06:36,144 --> 01:06:37,976
[Successful contact]
Where is this style from?

1621
01:06:37,976 --> 01:06:39,866
Why the two-handed handshake?

1622
01:06:39,866 --> 01:06:42,076
- I'm Sorem.
- Sorem.

1623
01:06:42,076 --> 01:06:43,246
Yes.

1624
01:06:43,926 --> 01:06:46,876
[What was your first impression
of the catfish senior?]

1625
01:06:46,876 --> 01:06:50,406
He seemed... just nice.

1626
01:06:50,406 --> 01:06:54,516
Like a student? A young man...

1627
01:06:54,516 --> 01:06:57,243
Actually, I'm still analyzing him...

1628
01:06:57,243 --> 01:06:58,966
Since he's a new person,

1629
01:06:58,966 --> 01:07:01,336
- I have to analyze him too.
- That's part of it.

1630
01:07:01,336 --> 01:07:02,876
He keeps falling behind in the ranks.

1631
01:07:02,876 --> 01:07:05,036
- You're right.
- I have to beat one more person.

1632
01:07:05,036 --> 01:07:08,746
- There's another one above me.
- There's one more person to beat.

1633
01:07:08,746 --> 01:07:11,446
[Intense competition at the bottom
of the Parma restaurant]

1634
01:07:11,446 --> 01:07:14,296
Hee Tae! Hee Tae!

1635
01:07:14,296 --> 01:07:16,826
[No. 2 approaches Hee Tae]
Hee Tae, Hee Tae.

1636
01:07:16,826 --> 01:07:20,056
His name isn't Sorem.

1637
01:07:20,056 --> 01:07:21,857
- Babo.
- Babo?

1638
01:07:21,857 --> 01:07:24,076
- Babo.
- Babo?

1639
01:07:24,076 --> 01:07:25,446
[Doubting his ears]
- Babo. - Babo?

1640
01:07:25,446 --> 01:07:26,784
Babo.

1641
01:07:26,784 --> 01:07:28,702
- That's Korean for... babo...
- Yes, that babo.

1642
01:07:28,702 --> 01:07:31,162
[Raising his hand cautiously]
- That's Korean for babo. - Yes.

1643
01:07:31,162 --> 01:07:32,956
- Babo.
- Babo.

1644
01:07:32,956 --> 01:07:34,316
You're calling him a babo?

1645
01:07:34,316 --> 01:07:36,476
A real babo?

1646
01:07:36,476 --> 01:07:38,536
- No, they're just teasing him.
- They looked it up.

1647
01:07:38,536 --> 01:07:40,486
Oh, really?

1648
01:07:40,486 --> 01:07:42,836
They even used the word "babo..."

1649
01:07:42,836 --> 01:07:45,036
- They found it.
- They found it to tell him.

1650
01:07:45,036 --> 01:07:46,806
Like, "This guy is a babo."

1651
01:07:46,806 --> 01:07:48,586
But Italian friends play like that.

1652
01:07:48,586 --> 01:07:49,796
That kind of thing is...

1653
01:07:49,796 --> 01:07:52,876
You have to play along with the teasing.
If you don't, it's a bit...

1654
01:07:52,876 --> 01:07:55,228
You know how soccer players sometimes...

1655
01:07:55,228 --> 01:07:57,036
slap each other's cheeks to show affection?

1656
01:07:57,036 --> 01:07:58,858
- Like that?
- But you shouldn't get offended.

1657
01:07:58,858 --> 01:08:01,353
- I shouldn't get offended?
- You have to hit them back.

1658
01:08:01,353 --> 01:08:03,493
[Italy's rough affection]
- I totally get it. - Right.

1659
01:08:03,493 --> 01:08:04,806
It feels a bit rough.

1660
01:08:04,806 --> 01:08:07,422
That's how you become part of the group.

1661
01:08:08,136 --> 01:08:09,836
[Sorem babo!]

1662
01:08:10,426 --> 01:08:12,935
[Genuinely flustered]
Babo? Babo?

1663
01:08:13,876 --> 01:08:15,396
Babozino.

1664
01:08:15,396 --> 01:08:16,836
Pass me the knife.

1665
01:08:16,836 --> 01:08:19,286
[No. 1 joins in on teasing Sorem]

1666
01:08:19,286 --> 01:08:21,816
Everybody has to know.

1667
01:08:21,816 --> 01:08:25,126
[Hehehe]

1668
01:08:26,376 --> 01:08:30,006
[Hee Tae is concerned]

1669
01:08:30,726 --> 01:08:32,396
Sorem, what do you have to do now?

1670
01:08:32,396 --> 01:08:34,676
I need to finish the biscuits.

1671
01:08:34,676 --> 01:08:39,016
I'll just empty this bin
and be back in two seconds.

1672
01:08:39,016 --> 01:08:43,116
[Sorem is called away by Lu's SOS]

1673
01:08:48,906 --> 01:08:51,356
No "babo."

1674
01:08:51,356 --> 01:08:53,396
[Genuinely worried]

1675
01:08:53,396 --> 01:08:55,656
He's being so serious right now.

1676
01:08:55,656 --> 01:08:56,886
No "babo."

1677
01:08:56,886 --> 01:08:58,493
[You're... not a babo...]

1678
01:08:58,493 --> 01:08:59,955
Seriously?

1679
01:09:02,106 --> 01:09:04,006
- His eyes are so...
- So serious.

1680
01:09:04,006 --> 01:09:06,326
He looks so sincere.

1681
01:09:06,326 --> 01:09:08,556
[Like the lead in a drama]
You're not a babo. It's okay.

1682
01:09:08,556 --> 01:09:10,906
He's so kind.

1683
01:09:11,967 --> 01:09:13,459
Seriously?

1684
01:09:13,459 --> 01:09:15,876
[The undercover junior worries
about the kind young man]

1685
01:09:15,876 --> 01:09:19,276
[His Italian is too limited
for what he wants to say]

1686
01:09:19,276 --> 01:09:21,036
"Babo" means "stupid," right?

1687
01:09:21,036 --> 01:09:23,176
- You speak English!
- Yes.

1688
01:09:23,176 --> 01:09:24,943
[Exactly]
Yes, it means "stupid" in Korean.

1689
01:09:24,943 --> 01:09:27,445
- So...
- I don't think so.

1690
01:09:27,445 --> 01:09:28,636
I don't think so.

1691
01:09:28,636 --> 01:09:30,609
[Getting to know each other]
- What's your name? - Sorem.

1692
01:09:30,609 --> 01:09:32,987
He speaks English well.

1693
01:09:33,626 --> 01:09:36,776
[The mischievous seniors appear one by one]

1694
01:09:38,556 --> 01:09:40,774
How do you know the word "babo?"

1695
01:09:40,774 --> 01:09:42,076
[His true charismatic self]
Babo!

1696
01:09:42,076 --> 01:09:44,346
- Babo! Babo!
- Babo, babo.

1697
01:09:44,346 --> 01:09:45,959
- No, he's not.
- Yes, he is.

1698
01:09:45,959 --> 01:09:47,176
[Immature leaders]
Babozino.

1699
01:09:47,176 --> 01:09:49,336
- They keep teasing him.
- Why are they teasing him?

1700
01:09:49,336 --> 01:09:50,566
Calling him a babo.

1701
01:09:50,566 --> 01:09:53,116
But every time they use a Korean word,

1702
01:09:53,116 --> 01:09:55,594
it actually makes me feel more comfortable.

1703
01:09:55,594 --> 01:09:56,630
Babozino.

1704
01:09:56,630 --> 01:10:00,221
It's "babo" in a cute way.

1705
01:10:01,572 --> 01:10:02,696
How is it today?

1706
01:10:02,696 --> 01:10:03,876
It's fine. It's okay.

1707
01:10:03,876 --> 01:10:05,286
Since it's my first day.

1708
01:10:05,286 --> 01:10:07,595
[It's your first day]
Sure.

1709
01:10:09,226 --> 01:10:12,566
- Hee Tae makes better tortelli than you.
- Really?

1710
01:10:12,566 --> 01:10:14,026
Yes.

1711
01:10:14,026 --> 01:10:17,287
- Hee Tae makes better tortelli than you.
- Really?

1712
01:10:17,287 --> 01:10:18,199
Yes.

1713
01:10:18,784 --> 01:10:21,306
You're better at it than Sorem.

1714
01:10:21,306 --> 01:10:23,276
[No. 1 teases him one more time]
Really?

1715
01:10:23,276 --> 01:10:25,146
- Really?
- Yeah.

1716
01:10:25,146 --> 01:10:28,746
He says you're better at tortelli than I do.

1717
01:10:28,746 --> 01:10:30,516
No way.

1718
01:10:31,796 --> 01:10:35,356
[Silence]

1719
01:10:36,086 --> 01:10:40,756
[It was clearly meant as a joke]

1720
01:10:42,796 --> 01:10:44,346
[But Sorem's expression is dark]

1721
01:10:44,346 --> 01:10:46,447
Does Sorem look upset?

1722
01:10:48,836 --> 01:10:54,026
[The silent junior duo]

1723
01:10:54,026 --> 01:10:56,822
[Is Sorem... angry?]
- Why? - He really looks upset...

1724
01:10:56,822 --> 01:10:58,056
You're not sulking, are you?

1725
01:10:58,056 --> 01:11:00,156
- Not exactly...
- Is he a bit hurt?

1726
01:11:00,156 --> 01:11:03,123
He probably thought
he finally had someone under him.

1727
01:11:05,120 --> 01:11:06,566
[A moment later]

1728
01:11:06,566 --> 01:11:10,389
- Learn from him.
- Learn from Hee Tae.

1729
01:11:10,389 --> 01:11:12,463
- This is a blow to my pride.
- It's very...

1730
01:11:12,463 --> 01:11:13,714
Wait a minute...

1731
01:11:13,714 --> 01:11:15,720
[That's a bit out of line]
He can't be happy about this.

1732
01:11:15,720 --> 01:11:16,776
He's jealous.

1733
01:11:16,776 --> 01:11:18,216
Hee Tae!

1734
01:11:18,216 --> 01:11:22,476
[The undercover junior is praised]
- Good job. - Oh, thank you.

1735
01:11:22,476 --> 01:11:26,136
[His position is being threatened]

1736
01:11:26,136 --> 01:11:28,966
[The junior who came under me]

1737
01:11:28,966 --> 01:11:32,696
[is trying to surpass me?]

1738
01:11:33,676 --> 01:11:37,036
[One spot, two juniors]

1739
01:11:38,246 --> 01:11:40,536
[Who will become the master
of the pasta station?]

1740
01:11:41,868 --> 01:11:45,126
[Sunny's 1st day as a kitchen junior]
In Chengdu, China, she became a junior again

1741
01:11:45,126 --> 01:11:46,266
after 24 years.

1742
01:11:46,266 --> 01:11:48,570
- Chef Jung Ji Sun.
- That was fun.

1743
01:11:49,526 --> 01:11:50,619
[Thud]

1744
01:11:52,776 --> 01:11:54,166
It's moving! What do I do?

1745
01:11:54,166 --> 01:11:57,804
[Still terrifying to watch]

1746
01:11:57,804 --> 01:11:59,516
- Don't be scared.
- Okay.

1747
01:11:59,516 --> 01:12:01,416
Okay, okay.

1748
01:12:01,416 --> 01:12:04,596
Wow, this isn't easy.

1749
01:12:04,596 --> 01:12:05,796
What should I do?

1750
01:12:05,796 --> 01:12:09,606
Whoa... Whoa!

1751
01:12:10,396 --> 01:12:13,046
[Finishing her first prep work
under intense scrutiny]

1752
01:12:14,312 --> 01:12:18,876
[It's already 10:50 AM]

1753
01:12:18,876 --> 01:12:23,556
[Ten minutes before lunch service begins]

1754
01:12:25,016 --> 01:12:29,248
[The banquet hall is
busy preparing for service]

1755
01:12:29,248 --> 01:12:33,596
- I'm realizing this again, this place is huge.
- It's really big.

1756
01:12:33,596 --> 01:12:35,569
You wouldn't even know if

1757
01:12:35,569 --> 01:12:37,275
a staff member was hiding in the restroom.

1758
01:12:37,275 --> 01:12:39,046
- True, true.
- Right?

1759
01:12:39,046 --> 01:12:41,176
If it were me, I'd live in the restroom.

1760
01:12:41,176 --> 01:12:44,106
[Glare]
You'd live there?

1761
01:12:44,106 --> 01:12:45,876
[As it's a large-scale banquet hall]

1762
01:12:45,876 --> 01:12:49,206
[Everything must be ready for service]
It's duck. Wow, this is a masterpiece.

1763
01:12:50,116 --> 01:12:51,676
[What's the next job?]

1764
01:12:51,676 --> 01:12:53,736
- So, service has started now?
- Yes, it has.

1765
01:12:53,736 --> 01:12:54,856
This is the important part.

1766
01:12:54,856 --> 01:12:58,086
[Go to the Wok station once it starts]
When you're done here,

1767
01:12:58,086 --> 01:12:59,706
you can go over there.

1768
01:12:59,706 --> 01:13:01,596
Just hand it over to Chef Li.

1769
01:13:01,596 --> 01:13:04,163
[Coordination is key during service]
You can help with the prep.

1770
01:13:04,163 --> 01:13:06,038
There's a separate team that does the cooking,

1771
01:13:06,038 --> 01:13:08,356
- and a separate team for prep.
- That's right.

1772
01:13:08,356 --> 01:13:11,446
[When an order comes in]

1773
01:13:12,696 --> 01:13:15,356
[First, check the menu]

1774
01:13:15,356 --> 01:13:16,906
[Prep station]
Plating and...

1775
01:13:16,906 --> 01:13:19,336
gathering all the ingredients
is the prep station's job.

1776
01:13:19,336 --> 01:13:23,316
[Gathering ingredients together]

1777
01:13:23,316 --> 01:13:26,246
[Handing over to the Wok Cooking station]

1778
01:13:26,246 --> 01:13:27,606
[Cooking in a heated wok station]

1779
01:13:27,606 --> 01:13:29,777
The cooking station just cooks.

1780
01:13:30,406 --> 01:13:34,376
[Setting the dishes]

1781
01:13:35,236 --> 01:13:40,702
[Preparing the right dish for the food
is the key]

1782
01:13:42,996 --> 01:13:47,846
[Hectic service hours!
Can undercover commis chef Sunny do well?]

1783
01:13:48,506 --> 01:13:51,946
When do we open for service?

1784
01:13:51,946 --> 01:13:53,596
It's starting right now.

1785
01:13:53,596 --> 01:13:55,681
I'm getting the food ready.

1786
01:13:55,681 --> 01:13:58,506
[Assisting the No.3 prep senior first]
Customers must be coming in now.

1787
01:13:58,506 --> 01:14:00,346
- We...
- That guy is number three.

1788
01:14:00,346 --> 01:14:01,407
- Yes, the third in Prep.
- Orders are coming in,

1789
01:14:01,407 --> 01:14:03,916
and customers keep arriving.

1790
01:14:03,916 --> 01:14:05,946
[11:00 AM Chengdu
Grandmother Restaurant opens]

1791
01:14:05,946 --> 01:14:08,502
Service starts at 11:00.

1792
01:14:09,366 --> 01:14:12,773
[First guests enter as soon as it opens]

1793
01:14:12,773 --> 01:14:16,236
[What is service like in a mega hall?]
With this many chairs, even if it's not full...

1794
01:14:16,236 --> 01:14:17,401
- It'll be hectic.
- Exactly.

1795
01:14:17,401 --> 01:14:18,516
- Exactly.
- Right.

1796
01:14:18,516 --> 01:14:21,286
[Large groups of guests pouring in]
Sit here.

1797
01:14:21,286 --> 01:14:24,958
All of us together.

1798
01:14:25,786 --> 01:14:28,556
Look at all those people.

1799
01:14:30,619 --> 01:14:32,486
[The large hall is filled
with guests even for a weekday lunch]

1800
01:14:32,486 --> 01:14:35,002
It's already crazy. Already.

1801
01:14:35,716 --> 01:14:37,066
So many people are coming.

1802
01:14:37,066 --> 01:14:39,116
- Basically...
- This is enough to fill...

1803
01:14:39,116 --> 01:14:40,836
Chef Kwon Sung Jun's entire restaurant.

1804
01:14:40,836 --> 01:14:43,097
We're already full.

1805
01:14:44,886 --> 01:14:47,556
We come here four times a year.

1806
01:14:48,376 --> 01:14:51,786
[A local favorite frequented by
three generations of regulars]

1807
01:14:51,786 --> 01:14:54,886
[Grandma, please feed us]

1808
01:14:54,886 --> 01:14:58,776
Chicken with scallions and chilies,
and stir-fried cabbage.

1809
01:14:58,776 --> 01:15:00,824
[Taking orders from customers]
Please wait a moment.

1810
01:15:02,516 --> 01:15:05,916
[Service begins! The orders arrive]

1811
01:15:05,916 --> 01:15:07,446
[Orders pouring in one after another]

1812
01:15:07,446 --> 01:15:09,126
Chinese cuisine has so many menu items.

1813
01:15:09,126 --> 01:15:11,147
- Isn't 100 items the standard?
- Exactly.

1814
01:15:11,147 --> 01:15:12,426
It'll be hard just to memorize names.

1815
01:15:12,426 --> 01:15:13,706
- I know.
- You're right.

1816
01:15:13,706 --> 01:15:15,796
- There are so many!
- Is that even possible?

1817
01:15:15,796 --> 01:15:18,078
[The order war begins]
How do you even read that?

1818
01:15:18,746 --> 01:15:20,106
Follow Xu Jian Kai.

1819
01:15:20,106 --> 01:15:23,196
- He'll show you what to do.
- Okay, okay.

1820
01:15:23,196 --> 01:15:26,376
[Prep station delivers orders to the Wok]

1821
01:15:26,376 --> 01:15:28,476
Braised beef.

1822
01:15:28,476 --> 01:15:29,596
Braised beef.

1823
01:15:29,596 --> 01:15:33,876
[Oh, that's my dish]

1824
01:15:33,876 --> 01:15:35,392
This is ours.

1825
01:15:35,392 --> 01:15:37,676
[Everyone supports the Wok station]

1826
01:15:37,676 --> 01:15:39,126
[Material delivery]

1827
01:15:39,126 --> 01:15:41,276
- Did this come from the prep station?
- Yes.

1828
01:15:41,276 --> 01:15:44,818
[Cooperation between Prep and Wok]
We're handing it over to the Wok station.

1829
01:15:46,036 --> 01:15:48,966
- The division of labor is clear.
- I know.

1830
01:15:48,966 --> 01:15:50,156
[A massive amount]

1831
01:15:50,156 --> 01:15:52,456
Do you stir-fry three portions at once?

1832
01:15:52,456 --> 01:15:54,246
Basically, here...

1833
01:15:54,246 --> 01:15:55,496
They start with five portions.

1834
01:15:55,496 --> 01:15:57,436
Wow, five portions at once?

1835
01:15:57,436 --> 01:16:00,536
That looks like a huge amount.

1836
01:16:00,536 --> 01:16:05,016
[Another order arrives]

1837
01:16:07,146 --> 01:16:08,956
It's overwhelming. I can't keep up.

1838
01:16:08,956 --> 01:16:10,516
[Serious]

1839
01:16:10,516 --> 01:16:12,076
Look at them pouring in.

1840
01:16:12,076 --> 01:16:13,816
Oh, I hate this.

1841
01:16:13,816 --> 01:16:15,126
[Orders pouring in]
Stir-fried potatoes and meat.

1842
01:16:15,126 --> 01:16:17,916
Mapo tofu, and mapo tofu with extra meat.

1843
01:16:17,916 --> 01:16:20,536
[So busy, so busy]

1844
01:16:21,496 --> 01:16:24,296
We're out of ingredients here.

1845
01:16:24,296 --> 01:16:26,906
[While everyone is busy]

1846
01:16:26,906 --> 01:16:30,166
[Looking around aimlessly]

1847
01:16:31,076 --> 01:16:33,728
Wait, I'll set up the food over there first.

1848
01:16:35,356 --> 01:16:37,031
Three portions, right?

1849
01:16:38,136 --> 01:16:39,436
But what are you doing?

1850
01:16:39,436 --> 01:16:40,666
I just didn't know what to do.

1851
01:16:40,666 --> 01:16:41,946
It's the same.

1852
01:16:41,946 --> 01:16:43,295
I know that feeling all too well.

1853
01:16:43,295 --> 01:16:44,311
- You just left them there.
- No.

1854
01:16:44,311 --> 01:16:46,276
- Why aren't you doing anything?
- It's not that.

1855
01:16:46,276 --> 01:16:48,456
- Come on.
- I had to assess the situation.

1856
01:16:48,456 --> 01:16:49,976
- It was the first day.
- Oh, please.

1857
01:16:49,976 --> 01:16:51,336
- A bit disappointing?
- Suddenly.

1858
01:16:51,336 --> 01:16:53,316
I didn't want to mess up by jumping in.

1859
01:16:53,316 --> 01:16:55,402
I'm a little disappointed.

1860
01:16:56,346 --> 01:16:58,398
[After standing there for a long time...]

1861
01:16:58,398 --> 01:17:00,685
[Sliding into the corner]
It's like the show "Misaeng."

1862
01:17:00,685 --> 01:17:03,018
I'd work hard if I were told what to do.

1863
01:17:03,688 --> 01:17:04,986
There really was nothing for me to do.

1864
01:17:04,986 --> 01:17:07,548
At least there's plenty of space here.

1865
01:17:08,316 --> 01:17:10,326
Everyone looks the same in this situation.

1866
01:17:10,326 --> 01:17:11,526
It was a bit hectic.

1867
01:17:11,526 --> 01:17:13,076
So chaotic...

1868
01:17:13,076 --> 01:17:16,076
I felt like I was walking on eggshells.

1869
01:17:16,756 --> 01:17:20,273
I kept thinking, "What do I do?"

1870
01:17:21,706 --> 01:17:26,566
[Can she succeed like this
within five days?]

1871
01:17:27,548 --> 01:17:31,308
I just feel like I need to be helpful quickly.

1872
01:17:31,308 --> 01:17:32,764
I should try whatever I can.

1873
01:17:32,764 --> 01:17:35,068
- She's doing something.
- What is she trying to do?

1874
01:17:35,068 --> 01:17:36,556
What is she trying to do?

1875
01:17:36,556 --> 01:17:39,896
[Just then, a dish comes out]

1876
01:17:40,876 --> 01:17:44,172
[Slides in]

1877
01:17:45,063 --> 01:17:46,536
[Checks the order slip first]

1878
01:17:46,536 --> 01:17:50,170
- Stir-fried beef with bamboo shoots.
- Stir-fried beef with bamboo shoots.

1879
01:17:51,068 --> 01:17:53,276
[When the chef puts down an empty plate]

1880
01:17:54,156 --> 01:17:55,612
[Clears it away quickly]

1881
01:17:55,612 --> 01:17:57,276
Give me a plate.

1882
01:17:57,276 --> 01:18:01,068
[When a dish is finished]

1883
01:18:01,068 --> 01:18:03,750
[Passes it to the hall staff]
I told you to bring me a plate.

1884
01:18:06,252 --> 01:18:08,358
And over there where the orders are...

1885
01:18:08,358 --> 01:18:10,796
[Keep the pickup area clean!]
This area must always be clean.

1886
01:18:10,796 --> 01:18:12,700
- You have to clear it right away.
- Keep wiping it.

1887
01:18:14,700 --> 01:18:17,391
[Another dish is finished]
That looks delicious.

1888
01:18:19,532 --> 01:18:23,020
[Sunny has naturally found her place]

1889
01:18:23,020 --> 01:18:26,300
Make sure the fish is clearly visible.

1890
01:18:26,300 --> 01:18:28,167
[Got it]
Fish?

1891
01:18:28,940 --> 01:18:31,776
[In the kitchen busy with incoming orders]
Make the presentation look pretty.

1892
01:18:31,776 --> 01:18:33,116
- It looks delicious.
- Make it look pretty.

1893
01:18:33,116 --> 01:18:37,284
- Shape the dish.
- They said to put the main ingredients on top.

1894
01:18:37,948 --> 01:18:41,884
[The aura of a master
scouting with a fierce gaze]

1895
01:18:43,388 --> 01:18:47,356
[The final boss approaches]

1896
01:18:51,660 --> 01:18:54,444
[Working next to the final boss...]

1897
01:18:54,444 --> 01:18:57,004
[Feeling nervous]

1898
01:18:59,484 --> 01:19:02,844
[She glances at Sunny]

1899
01:19:07,068 --> 01:19:09,484
Don't you need to use the bathroom?

1900
01:19:09,484 --> 01:19:11,308
Don't you need to use the bathroom?

1901
01:19:11,308 --> 01:19:13,148
No, I'm fine.

1902
01:19:13,148 --> 01:19:14,956
[Concerned]

1903
01:19:14,956 --> 01:19:18,516
Then shall I get you a glass of warm water?

1904
01:19:18,516 --> 01:19:20,736
- Warm water?
- Warm water?

1905
01:19:21,873 --> 01:19:23,500
[Grateful]
- I'm okay. - You won't drink any water?

1906
01:19:23,500 --> 01:19:25,793
It's your first day.

1907
01:19:25,793 --> 01:19:27,226
Of course I have to care.

1908
01:19:27,226 --> 01:19:28,376
She's very kind.

1909
01:19:28,376 --> 01:19:29,816
She has such a pleasant expression.

1910
01:19:29,816 --> 01:19:33,404
I think Sunny is doing a great job.

1911
01:19:33,404 --> 01:19:35,674
She's quick-witted and fast with her hands.

1912
01:19:35,674 --> 01:19:39,388
She doesn't just do one thing,
she tries to help with everything.

1913
01:19:39,388 --> 01:19:43,164
Leaders love diligent people.

1914
01:19:43,164 --> 01:19:44,428
[True, true]
That's right.

1915
01:19:44,428 --> 01:19:45,740
They love diligent people.

1916
01:19:45,740 --> 01:19:48,134
That's why I want to look after her more.

1917
01:19:49,234 --> 01:19:50,956
[Final check before serving the guests]
Give it to me.

1918
01:19:50,956 --> 01:19:53,340
- Grandmother is working right beside you?
- Yes.

1919
01:19:53,340 --> 01:19:54,876
She's always right there.

1920
01:19:54,876 --> 01:19:56,412
She oversees everything.

1921
01:19:56,412 --> 01:19:59,030
[Grandmother, 82, leads the kitchen]
She always checks...

1922
01:19:59,030 --> 01:20:01,148
- To see if the dish is perfect.
- That's the final step.

1923
01:20:01,148 --> 01:20:03,446
That's really amazing of her.

1924
01:20:03,446 --> 01:20:04,860
Watching her do that,

1925
01:20:04,860 --> 01:20:07,468
I thought, "I could do that too."

1926
01:20:07,468 --> 01:20:08,764
It gave me a new perspective.

1927
01:20:08,764 --> 01:20:12,284
I've never really had a role model in my life.

1928
01:20:12,284 --> 01:20:14,620
But seeing someone live like that,

1929
01:20:14,620 --> 01:20:19,269
makes me think I can do more too.

1930
01:20:19,269 --> 01:20:22,422
[Grandma's passion makes her a role model]
It's important to have a role model.

1931
01:20:22,422 --> 01:20:23,924
True.

1932
01:20:24,620 --> 01:20:26,524
This one is...

1933
01:20:26,524 --> 01:20:28,445
Four orders of Salted Egg Corn Fritters.

1934
01:20:28,445 --> 01:20:29,772
- Salted Egg Corn Fritters?
- Yes.

1935
01:20:29,772 --> 01:20:31,341
[Preparing four plates]
You opened four cans earlier.

1936
01:20:31,341 --> 01:20:34,109
Four orders. Here are the plates.

1937
01:20:36,572 --> 01:20:40,480
[Corn fritters fried to a golden yellow]
This looks delicious. The fried corn.

1938
01:20:41,180 --> 01:20:44,780
[Sweet and salty addictive corn fritters]
- It has to be good. - That's a guaranteed win.

1939
01:20:44,780 --> 01:20:46,727
It looks sweet and tasty.

1940
01:20:47,996 --> 01:20:51,046
[Staring intensely at the corn]
You're watching very closely.

1941
01:20:51,046 --> 01:20:53,324
You can try some if you're curious.

1942
01:20:53,324 --> 01:20:56,444
- Can I try it?
- Use your chopsticks to try some.

1943
01:20:56,444 --> 01:20:58,065
Thank you.

1944
01:21:01,212 --> 01:21:03,496
This goes out as is, right?

1945
01:21:05,628 --> 01:21:07,868
[Passing it over to be served]

1946
01:21:07,868 --> 01:21:10,196
It looks so good.

1947
01:21:13,484 --> 01:21:17,070
[Sunny tastes the Salted Egg Corn Fritters]
I was curious since the style is unique.

1948
01:21:21,100 --> 01:21:23,116
[I added egg yolks]
These are egg yolks.

1949
01:21:23,116 --> 01:21:25,788
- Egg yolks?
- Yes, yolks.

1950
01:21:25,788 --> 01:21:27,244
They're salted duck eggs.

1951
01:21:27,244 --> 01:21:28,604
You crush them,

1952
01:21:28,604 --> 01:21:30,156
make them foam up, and stir-fry them.

1953
01:21:30,156 --> 01:21:31,916
Then the umami...

1954
01:21:31,916 --> 01:21:33,676
- The umami flavor intensifies.
- The yolks provide the umami.

1955
01:21:33,676 --> 01:21:35,468
- It must be delicious.
- Exactly.

1956
01:21:35,468 --> 01:21:38,098
This is similar to western cuisine.

1957
01:21:39,740 --> 01:21:41,397
One more plate!

1958
01:21:42,425 --> 01:21:44,140
[A shy thumbs up]

1959
01:21:45,436 --> 01:21:48,062
I heard you were a boxer. Is that true?

1960
01:21:48,062 --> 01:21:50,124
- You're a boxer?
- He's asking now! Oh my goodness.

1961
01:21:50,124 --> 01:21:51,736
Are you a boxer?

1962
01:21:51,736 --> 01:21:53,388
- Shouldn't you show us a move?
- I didn't know boxing

1963
01:21:53,388 --> 01:21:55,563
[Like this]
what it was called in Chinese.

1964
01:21:56,188 --> 01:21:58,540
[Jab]

1965
01:21:59,644 --> 01:22:01,436
You look healthy, maybe from the exercise.

1966
01:22:01,436 --> 01:22:03,436
- She looks healthy.
- She does.

1967
01:22:03,436 --> 01:22:04,668
She looks strong.

1968
01:22:04,668 --> 01:22:07,020
I guess no one would dare bully her.

1969
01:22:07,020 --> 01:22:08,220
[Jab, jab]

1970
01:22:08,220 --> 01:22:09,948
Break time.

1971
01:22:09,948 --> 01:22:11,286
I was really fascinated.

1972
01:22:11,286 --> 01:22:12,444
Because she's a boxer.

1973
01:22:12,444 --> 01:22:14,996
Does that mean you're a taekwondo athlete?

1974
01:22:15,724 --> 01:22:19,148
[Interested]

1975
01:22:19,148 --> 01:22:20,652
Is it taekwondo?

1976
01:22:20,652 --> 01:22:25,046
[Vague response]

1977
01:22:28,476 --> 01:22:31,612
[Plops down in the corner of the Prep station]

1978
01:22:32,652 --> 01:22:37,076
Is she really here to learn?

1979
01:22:37,884 --> 01:22:39,500
I think she knows what she's doing.

1980
01:22:39,500 --> 01:22:41,683
I think she knows what she's doing.

1981
01:22:42,360 --> 01:22:44,136
- Oh, that's what they were saying.
- I think...

1982
01:22:44,136 --> 01:22:45,859
[Seeds of doubt]
She knows what she's doing.

1983
01:22:45,859 --> 01:22:48,860
She must have studied before coming here.

1984
01:22:48,860 --> 01:22:50,556
Did she get trained before coming here?

1985
01:22:50,556 --> 01:22:52,162
A little bit...

1986
01:22:52,162 --> 01:22:54,043
[Caught on day one?]
Did she get some training?

1987
01:22:54,043 --> 01:22:56,878
[Exciting]
- It's bound to show. - It must have shown.

1988
01:22:59,564 --> 01:23:03,500
[A boxer-turned-suspicious kitchen junior?]

1989
01:23:03,500 --> 01:23:04,554
[Speaking of which...]

1990
01:23:04,554 --> 01:23:08,636
She knew to remove the fish head and tail.

1991
01:23:08,636 --> 01:23:09,772
She probably saw you do it.

1992
01:23:09,772 --> 01:23:12,332
Of course she did, but...

1993
01:23:12,332 --> 01:23:13,808
Can you copy it just by watching?

1994
01:23:13,808 --> 01:23:16,130
Anyway, I think she's been trained.

1995
01:23:16,908 --> 01:23:21,052
[A while ago, when she was with No. 3]

1996
01:23:22,108 --> 01:23:23,276
The fish dish is out.

1997
01:23:23,276 --> 01:23:25,231
It's out.

1998
01:23:29,516 --> 01:23:30,876
Like that.

1999
01:23:30,876 --> 01:23:32,835
She placed it exactly like that.

2000
01:23:32,835 --> 01:23:34,636
[Suspicious point 1, perfect plating]
- Straight like this. - Right.

2001
01:23:34,636 --> 01:23:35,884
Shaping it like this.

2002
01:23:35,884 --> 01:23:37,692
And then adding the sauce.

2003
01:23:37,692 --> 01:23:39,324
- She did that on her own.
- Then...

2004
01:23:39,324 --> 01:23:42,396
Doing it without being told means...

2005
01:23:42,396 --> 01:23:45,956
[Suspicious point 2,
wiping down without being asked]

2006
01:23:45,956 --> 01:23:47,956
- Those habits are ingrained in her.
- Exactly.

2007
01:23:47,956 --> 01:23:50,636
[Suspicious point 3, seasoning expert]
- I don't wipe down. - Right.

2008
01:23:50,636 --> 01:23:52,620
I don't know how because I wasn't taught.

2009
01:23:52,620 --> 01:23:53,964
- Wiping with a cloth.
- Right.

2010
01:23:53,964 --> 01:23:55,884
It's always messy.

2011
01:23:55,884 --> 01:24:00,604
[The more they think,
the more her basics seem solid...]

2012
01:24:00,604 --> 01:24:03,452
She must be a celebrity working with us.

2013
01:24:03,452 --> 01:24:05,916
[Is that right?]
She's probably not a celebrity.

2014
01:24:05,916 --> 01:24:08,636
[How far will the suspicion spread?]

2015
01:24:08,636 --> 01:24:09,980
They talked about me a lot.

2016
01:24:09,980 --> 01:24:11,199
They did.

2017
01:24:11,199 --> 01:24:13,692
[Ingrained skills]
It's bound to show, actually.

2018
01:24:13,692 --> 01:24:15,336
This gossip is fun.

2019
01:24:15,336 --> 01:24:16,908
Since they didn't know the backstory...

2020
01:24:16,908 --> 01:24:18,172
That backstory is so funny.

2021
01:24:18,172 --> 01:24:19,540
The backstory is great.

2022
01:24:19,540 --> 01:24:20,926
[Current Time 1:00 PM]

2023
01:24:20,926 --> 01:24:22,591
1:00 PM.

2024
01:24:23,676 --> 01:24:27,100
[Lunch service is over before they know it]
So it's from 11:00 to 1:00.

2025
01:24:28,460 --> 01:24:29,980
[The orders that filled the board...]

2026
01:24:29,980 --> 01:24:31,580
[Are all gone!]

2027
01:24:32,236 --> 01:24:33,372
[Order board cleared]

2028
01:24:33,372 --> 01:24:35,228
Now that the battle is over...

2029
01:24:35,228 --> 01:24:38,012
[The kitchen has finally quieted down]

2030
01:24:38,012 --> 01:24:40,716
[Prepping ingredients again?]

2031
01:24:42,348 --> 01:24:45,148
[They're heading to the cooking station?]

2032
01:24:45,148 --> 01:24:47,288
They're heading to the cooking station.

2033
01:24:47,288 --> 01:24:49,372
Why? What is it?

2034
01:24:49,372 --> 01:24:51,698
Everyone is grabbing something.

2035
01:24:52,782 --> 01:24:56,116
[Service is over, so why the cooking station?]

2036
01:24:56,116 --> 01:24:58,452
Everyone is moving over there.

2037
01:24:59,772 --> 01:25:01,708
[A giant wok appears?]

2038
01:25:01,708 --> 01:25:03,644
A massive one just came out.

2039
01:25:03,644 --> 01:25:05,473
Look at the size of that wok.

2040
01:25:06,188 --> 01:25:07,676
Well, there are many staff members.

2041
01:25:07,676 --> 01:25:09,004
They didn't have any small woks.

2042
01:25:09,004 --> 01:25:11,134
All the woks are that size.

2043
01:25:11,134 --> 01:25:13,356
All the woks are that size.

2044
01:25:13,356 --> 01:25:15,996
- It looks like it'll be a hearty meal.
- About this meat...

2045
01:25:15,996 --> 01:25:18,092
We just need to heat it up a bit.

2046
01:25:18,092 --> 01:25:21,852
[He seems to be in a great mood]

2047
01:25:21,852 --> 01:25:24,588
What time is it now, Senior?

2048
01:25:24,588 --> 01:25:26,572
It's time for the staff meal!

2049
01:25:26,572 --> 01:25:28,764
Staff meal, staff meal.

2050
01:25:28,764 --> 01:25:30,460
I knew it.

2051
01:25:30,460 --> 01:25:31,596
It looks delicious.

2052
01:25:31,596 --> 01:25:34,044
Everyone is moving to the cooking station.

2053
01:25:34,044 --> 01:25:35,728
[A giant wok dancing over the fire]

2054
01:25:35,728 --> 01:25:38,299
Look at that.

2055
01:25:39,052 --> 01:25:40,300
That's some big-scale wok-cooking.

2056
01:25:40,300 --> 01:25:42,417
It's so rhythmic.

2057
01:25:42,417 --> 01:25:44,865
[Bouncing to the rhythm of the wok]

2058
01:25:45,740 --> 01:25:47,100
[Staff meal is ready!]

2059
01:25:47,100 --> 01:25:49,672
This is the meal.

2060
01:25:49,672 --> 01:25:51,052
[A mountain of food]
When they cook...

2061
01:25:51,052 --> 01:25:52,732
That's the usual portion size.

2062
01:25:52,732 --> 01:25:55,612
[Scooping hot rice for the staff]
- That looks so good. - I know.

2063
01:25:55,612 --> 01:25:57,052
- That...
- It's really delicious.

2064
01:25:57,052 --> 01:25:59,036
- Pung would love this.
- Is it my style?

2065
01:25:59,036 --> 01:26:00,796
- You like this kind of food too.
- I do.

2066
01:26:00,796 --> 01:26:02,522
- You just mix the rice in and...
- Exactly.

2067
01:26:02,522 --> 01:26:03,878
- And just eat it.
- That's right.

2068
01:26:03,878 --> 01:26:06,764
[Another mass movement
begins after the meeting]

2069
01:26:06,764 --> 01:26:11,612
[Kitchen staff pouring out
carrying their own dishes]

2070
01:26:12,524 --> 01:26:17,324
[New kitchen junior Sunny joins them]

2071
01:26:17,324 --> 01:26:19,747
[Staff eating in the dining area]
Sit here.

2072
01:26:19,747 --> 01:26:21,276
[Even though customers are still here]

2073
01:26:21,276 --> 01:26:23,260
- They eat with the customers.
- Really?

2074
01:26:23,260 --> 01:26:26,472
[Staff meal while guests are present?]
- That's... - Their meal times are strict.

2075
01:26:27,228 --> 01:26:30,092
- That's so unique.
- I've never seen them eat with guests.

2076
01:26:30,092 --> 01:26:32,608
- It's unique.
- Why is our table so full of food?

2077
01:26:33,372 --> 01:26:36,516
[A hearty spread of Sichuan cuisine]
It looks delicious.

2078
01:26:36,516 --> 01:26:38,651
I want to work there.

2079
01:26:40,300 --> 01:26:42,364
Try this! Mapo tofu!

2080
01:26:42,364 --> 01:26:44,668
Mapo tofu.

2081
01:26:44,668 --> 01:26:48,124
[Taking a bite of the recommended Mapo tofu]

2082
01:26:50,364 --> 01:26:52,604
Does the food suit your palate?

2083
01:26:52,604 --> 01:26:55,884
- It's delicious.
- It is, isn't it?

2084
01:26:55,884 --> 01:26:59,196
[The owner warmly looks after her with a smile]
- The owner is so kind. - He is.

2085
01:26:59,196 --> 01:27:00,476
[Glance]

2086
01:27:00,476 --> 01:27:01,628
Have some more rice!

2087
01:27:01,628 --> 01:27:03,196
No, I've had enough.

2088
01:27:03,196 --> 01:27:05,605
[Shy]
There's more rice over there.

2089
01:27:06,316 --> 01:27:08,892
The staff opened up to her really quickly.

2090
01:27:08,892 --> 01:27:10,744
They did.

2091
01:27:11,896 --> 01:27:14,172
[Heartwarming]

2092
01:27:15,976 --> 01:27:20,486
[Tang Wei, Prep Station Chief]
She is... how should I put it...

2093
01:27:20,486 --> 01:27:23,740
I think she's a gentle person.

2094
01:27:23,740 --> 01:27:26,828
And she seems like a good person.

2095
01:27:26,828 --> 01:27:31,196
[Yang Tang Chun, Cooking Station Chief]
Her basic skills were decent.

2096
01:27:31,196 --> 01:27:33,372
She was very neat and clean.

2097
01:27:33,996 --> 01:27:36,556
Sunny has only been in this industry
for a single day.

2098
01:27:36,556 --> 01:27:40,835
Everything in cooking requires a process.

2099
01:27:41,576 --> 01:27:46,669
[As the meal is coming to an end]

2100
01:27:48,460 --> 01:27:50,668
[The chefs start leaving in a hurry]

2101
01:27:50,668 --> 01:27:53,706
Why are they leaving so suddenly?

2102
01:27:56,668 --> 01:27:58,972
What do you do after eating?

2103
01:27:59,692 --> 01:28:01,260
It's break time.

2104
01:28:01,260 --> 01:28:02,508
Break time?

2105
01:28:02,508 --> 01:28:04,404
- Break time?
- Break time.

2106
01:28:06,407 --> 01:28:08,828
We come back to work at 4:30 PM.

2107
01:28:08,828 --> 01:28:10,966
We come back at 4:30.

2108
01:28:10,966 --> 01:28:14,236
You can think of it as
getting off work for a bit.

2109
01:28:14,236 --> 01:28:17,532
[Now that I think about it...]

2110
01:28:17,532 --> 01:28:19,756
[Eating hurriedly]

2111
01:28:19,756 --> 01:28:22,012
[In a rush, in a rush]

2112
01:28:22,012 --> 01:28:24,188
[Thinking about going home quickly]

2113
01:28:24,796 --> 01:28:27,314
[Average meal time]

2114
01:28:27,314 --> 01:28:28,764
[Finished in 5 minutes, Stands up 1]

2115
01:28:28,764 --> 01:28:31,066
[Stands up 2, Stands up 3]

2116
01:28:31,804 --> 01:28:34,124
[The desire to leave work
early is universal...]

2117
01:28:34,124 --> 01:28:36,062
[Whoosh]
Seriously.

2118
01:28:37,516 --> 01:28:40,673
- It's amazing how they vanish after eating.
- I know.

2119
01:28:41,375 --> 01:28:43,025
- 4:30 PM.
- I'm leaving work now.

2120
01:28:43,025 --> 01:28:45,212
What will you do during the break?
Can I go take a nap?

2121
01:28:45,212 --> 01:28:46,588
- That's right.
- You can.

2122
01:28:46,588 --> 01:28:49,116
So they completely leave you alone
during this time.

2123
01:28:49,116 --> 01:28:51,270
Are you finished eating?

2124
01:28:51,270 --> 01:28:54,060
I'll clear the table.

2125
01:28:54,060 --> 01:28:56,972
[Employee break time 2:30 PM - 4:30 PM]

2126
01:28:58,380 --> 01:29:00,524
[Late afternoon]

2127
01:29:00,524 --> 01:29:02,803
[Everyone is taking a short break]

2128
01:29:03,631 --> 01:29:05,452
[What is Sunny doing during her first break?]

2129
01:29:05,452 --> 01:29:07,732
What is she doing?

2130
01:29:11,996 --> 01:29:13,308
Where is the...

2131
01:29:13,308 --> 01:29:14,748
[Huh?]

2132
01:29:14,748 --> 01:29:16,543
Where is what?

2133
01:29:18,747 --> 01:29:20,556
Is there anyone still working?

2134
01:29:20,556 --> 01:29:23,228
- Is there no one here?
- There's a person on duty here.

2135
01:29:23,228 --> 01:29:24,908
Just for deliveries.

2136
01:29:24,908 --> 01:29:29,372
[A lost kitchen junior?]

2137
01:29:29,372 --> 01:29:32,492
This is a tip I learned from a senior chef.

2138
01:29:32,492 --> 01:29:35,836
No matter which restaurant you go to,
if a sauce is really delicious,

2139
01:29:35,836 --> 01:29:38,316
you look in the storage room
or the open kitchen.

2140
01:29:38,316 --> 01:29:40,696
If you look at the sauces they have on display,

2141
01:29:40,696 --> 01:29:43,926
you can tell, "Oh, they use this
to bring out more sweetness."

2142
01:29:43,926 --> 01:29:46,456
- You can figure it out like that.
- Right.

2143
01:29:46,456 --> 01:29:48,986
[Sunny is scouting the produce warehouse]
Right now,

2144
01:29:48,986 --> 01:29:52,420
- You're actually seeing what's in there.
- I'm curious about what's in here.

2145
01:29:53,948 --> 01:29:55,146
[Turn]

2146
01:29:55,146 --> 01:29:56,380
[Feeling a bit guilty...]

2147
01:29:56,380 --> 01:29:59,324
You might look a little suspicious.

2148
01:29:59,324 --> 01:30:01,348
- Like you're stealing something.
- Yeah.

2149
01:30:02,174 --> 01:30:04,427
Where do you keep the ingredients?

2150
01:30:04,427 --> 01:30:06,012
- What?
- The ingredients.

2151
01:30:06,012 --> 01:30:07,101
The ingredients?

2152
01:30:07,101 --> 01:30:08,875
Where do you put them?

2153
01:30:10,380 --> 01:30:13,308
Where do you keep all these ingredients?

2154
01:30:13,308 --> 01:30:15,196
[Vaguely]
They're all upstairs.

2155
01:30:15,196 --> 01:30:17,206
[Like this...]
- Up there... - Oh, I see.

2156
01:30:17,206 --> 01:30:18,676
[Suspicious...]

2157
01:30:18,676 --> 01:30:21,276
- Do I put everything here?
- That's right.

2158
01:30:21,276 --> 01:30:24,006
[A fierce tug-of-war over trade secrets]

2159
01:30:26,266 --> 01:30:28,876
[There should be an ingredient warehouse...]

2160
01:30:29,606 --> 01:30:31,686
I need to sharpen this.

2161
01:30:31,686 --> 01:30:33,596
[Sunny goes to the hall to find the warehouse]

2162
01:30:33,596 --> 01:30:35,386
I couldn't find the warehouse here.

2163
01:30:35,386 --> 01:30:37,785
[Suddenly]
It's because it's so big.

2164
01:30:41,416 --> 01:30:44,506
Could you show me the...

2165
01:30:44,506 --> 01:30:46,552
- The menu?
- Yes.

2166
01:30:48,936 --> 01:30:50,456
[Studying the menu this time]
Menu.

2167
01:30:50,456 --> 01:30:52,216
[It's as thick as a dictionary!]

2168
01:30:52,216 --> 01:30:53,756
She's working hard.

2169
01:30:53,756 --> 01:30:56,356
[The number of menu items is...]
Actually, studying the menu...

2170
01:30:56,356 --> 01:30:58,939
- Chinese restaurants have so many items.
- That's a lot.

2171
01:30:58,939 --> 01:31:01,396
[A whopping 160 items]
That many?

2172
01:31:01,396 --> 01:31:03,741
- 160 items?
- 160?

2173
01:31:03,741 --> 01:31:05,866
[160 items!
The banquet hall has a massive menu]

2174
01:31:05,866 --> 01:31:07,946
It'll be impossible to memorize them all.

2175
01:31:07,946 --> 01:31:09,066
It's short.

2176
01:31:09,066 --> 01:31:10,296
Five days is short.

2177
01:31:10,296 --> 01:31:11,976
No matter which restaurant you go to,

2178
01:31:11,976 --> 01:31:13,276
the menu comes first.

2179
01:31:13,276 --> 01:31:15,976
- You study the menu as soon as you arrive.
- 160 is really...

2180
01:31:15,976 --> 01:31:18,579
- That's too many.
- I know.

2181
01:31:19,256 --> 01:31:23,526
[Final goal:
preparation for new menu development]

2182
01:31:28,136 --> 01:31:31,066
[Leaving the menu to go to the kitchen]

2183
01:31:31,066 --> 01:31:34,076
Take the menu with you...

2184
01:31:34,076 --> 01:31:35,258
Can I take it?

2185
01:31:35,258 --> 01:31:36,836
[Like lending a library book...]
- Really? - It's fine.

2186
01:31:36,836 --> 01:31:38,456
- Take it.
- Then when I leave work...

2187
01:31:38,456 --> 01:31:39,983
- She's so kind.
- Yes, let's do that.

2188
01:31:39,983 --> 01:31:42,942
[She spent her entire break studying]
- You can take it. - Thank you.

2189
01:31:42,942 --> 01:31:44,390
As expected.

2190
01:31:45,156 --> 01:31:47,016
[Taking a short breather]

2191
01:31:47,016 --> 01:31:51,176
[Employees returning to work]

2192
01:31:52,156 --> 01:31:53,416
Good afternoon!

2193
01:31:53,416 --> 01:31:54,619
- Good afternoon!
- Good afternoon!

2194
01:31:54,619 --> 01:31:56,680
[Evening assembly at 4:30 PM]
It's the afternoon...

2195
01:31:56,680 --> 01:31:59,038
- It's the evening assembly.
- They do an evening one, too?

2196
01:31:59,038 --> 01:32:02,248
- Is this the army?
- It really is like the army.

2197
01:32:03,036 --> 01:32:04,106
Assemblies all the time.

2198
01:32:04,106 --> 01:32:06,639
Yes, every morning and evening.

2199
01:32:09,256 --> 01:32:12,296
[Evening assembly starts with roll call]

2200
01:32:12,296 --> 01:32:13,836
Tian Fu Qiang.

2201
01:32:13,836 --> 01:32:16,246
[Scratching head]
Yang Tan Chun.

2202
01:32:16,246 --> 01:32:18,426
[When will my name be called?]
- Lin Fu Yong. - Yes!

2203
01:32:18,426 --> 01:32:20,396
- Sunny.
- Yes!

2204
01:32:20,396 --> 01:32:22,426
- Sunny.
- Yes!

2205
01:32:22,426 --> 01:32:24,546
[The kitchen junior answers confidently]
Tao?

2206
01:32:24,546 --> 01:32:25,645
Tao is here.

2207
01:32:25,645 --> 01:32:27,306
- Tao.
- Tao.

2208
01:32:27,306 --> 01:32:30,026
Now, go to your stations and work diligently.

2209
01:32:30,026 --> 01:32:31,656
Be people of character.

2210
01:32:31,656 --> 01:32:33,046
Do your work properly.

2211
01:32:33,046 --> 01:32:34,236
Character and proper work!

2212
01:32:34,236 --> 01:32:36,556
Service and customers first!

2213
01:32:36,556 --> 01:32:40,316
[The junior follows along]
Let's use this as our slogan.

2214
01:32:40,316 --> 01:32:43,556
[Preparing for dinner service]

2215
01:32:43,556 --> 01:32:45,286
This music is a bit...

2216
01:32:45,286 --> 01:32:47,156
It feels like it's foreshadowing something.

2217
01:32:47,156 --> 01:32:48,246
Like Squid Game.

2218
01:32:48,246 --> 01:32:51,736
[Chuckles]

2219
01:32:51,736 --> 01:32:55,181
- I'll show you how to shred meat.
- Okay.

2220
01:32:55,895 --> 01:32:58,936
[Prepping meat, not vegetables]
I'll show you how to shred it.

2221
01:32:58,936 --> 01:33:00,536
Lay it down thin...

2222
01:33:00,536 --> 01:33:03,546
and slice it. This is "pyeon" slicing.

2223
01:33:03,546 --> 01:33:05,866
Actually, meat is...

2224
01:33:05,866 --> 01:33:08,106
- much harder to handle than vegetables.
- That's right.

2225
01:33:08,106 --> 01:33:09,336
It's hard to slice...

2226
01:33:09,336 --> 01:33:11,944
and hard to keep the shape.

2227
01:33:13,046 --> 01:33:14,936
Give it a try.

2228
01:33:14,936 --> 01:33:16,406
It looks difficult.

2229
01:33:16,406 --> 01:33:18,026
It looks difficult.

2230
01:33:18,026 --> 01:33:20,773
[Taking the knife while acting humble]
- Take it slow. - Okay.

2231
01:33:22,623 --> 01:33:24,964
[Sunny's first attempt at slicing...]
How will she do?

2232
01:33:26,384 --> 01:33:28,975
She has to pretend she's bad at this.

2233
01:33:32,246 --> 01:33:37,576
Keep the knife level.

2234
01:33:37,576 --> 01:33:39,892
Take your time.

2235
01:33:40,886 --> 01:33:43,176
The back is a bit crooked.

2236
01:33:43,176 --> 01:33:45,476
[Try again]

2237
01:33:45,476 --> 01:33:48,019
[Grunt]

2238
01:33:50,826 --> 01:33:52,876
It's a bit thick, right?

2239
01:33:52,876 --> 01:33:54,456
- The thickness...
- It's a bit thick.

2240
01:33:54,456 --> 01:33:56,716
- It needs to be thinner.
- Slowly.

2241
01:33:56,716 --> 01:33:59,556
Knife work isn't learned overnight.

2242
01:33:59,556 --> 01:34:00,726
Right?

2243
01:34:01,366 --> 01:34:04,696
[Not overnight, but after 24 years...]

2244
01:34:04,696 --> 01:34:06,136
[Two layers of meat this time?]

2245
01:34:06,136 --> 01:34:08,136
- Two layers?
- Yes, now we shred it.

2246
01:34:08,136 --> 01:34:09,676
This is for shredding.

2247
01:34:09,676 --> 01:34:13,046
To shred, you have to hold it here.

2248
01:34:13,046 --> 01:34:16,055
- If you do this...
- I should watch and learn too.

2249
01:34:18,156 --> 01:34:19,496
He lays it down after each cut.

2250
01:34:19,496 --> 01:34:22,495
- In case they stick.
- So they don't stick together.

2251
01:34:23,310 --> 01:34:26,866
Once you're used to it, it's like this. See?

2252
01:34:27,816 --> 01:34:30,069
One by one.

2253
01:34:31,256 --> 01:34:34,456
[Loosening up his hand]
If you cut quickly, it's like this.

2254
01:34:34,456 --> 01:34:36,916
Depending on

2255
01:34:36,916 --> 01:34:38,986
[Sunny is laughing?]
how you feel.

2256
01:34:38,986 --> 01:34:40,776
- See?
- Why are you laughing?

2257
01:34:40,776 --> 01:34:42,836
You just cut it like this.

2258
01:34:42,836 --> 01:34:45,965
It's just funny to hear him
explain every little thing.

2259
01:34:46,756 --> 01:34:48,106
When you say it's funny...

2260
01:34:48,106 --> 01:34:50,112
- I already know this.
- It's ridiculous.

2261
01:34:50,112 --> 01:34:51,516
It's not exactly that it's funny.

2262
01:34:51,516 --> 01:34:53,054
It's more like,
"Do I have to sit through this?"

2263
01:34:53,054 --> 01:34:54,486
- Right.
- "Excuse me?"

2264
01:34:54,486 --> 01:34:56,376
He was being so kind and teaching me well.

2265
01:34:56,376 --> 01:34:57,786
She seems similar to me.

2266
01:34:57,786 --> 01:34:59,626
[Shaking his head]
No way.

2267
01:34:59,626 --> 01:35:00,836
You two are exactly the same.

2268
01:35:00,836 --> 01:35:03,725
Your future self is sitting right next to you.

2269
01:35:05,956 --> 01:35:08,916
[Just then, someone calls
the Prep Station Chief]

2270
01:35:09,709 --> 01:35:10,816
Give it a try.

2271
01:35:10,816 --> 01:35:13,226
[As the Prep Station Chief steps away]

2272
01:35:19,276 --> 01:35:23,172
While I was cutting earlier,
how should I put it?

2273
01:35:23,172 --> 01:35:26,136
"Should I just finish this quickly?"

2274
01:35:26,136 --> 01:35:29,217
"How long do I have to sit here
cutting like this?"

2275
01:35:29,217 --> 01:35:30,906
[Pacing herself for dinner prep]
"How long must I keep this up?"

2276
01:35:30,906 --> 01:35:32,726
- You have to pace yourself.
- Yes.

2277
01:35:32,726 --> 01:35:34,806
- If you're too good, it's obvious.
- Exactly.

2278
01:35:34,806 --> 01:35:37,183
But if you're too bad, they won't let you.

2279
01:35:37,846 --> 01:35:39,756
[Is anyone looking?]

2280
01:35:40,986 --> 01:35:44,026
[Her gaze suddenly changes]

2281
01:35:47,196 --> 01:35:48,696
With one stroke, just...

2282
01:35:48,696 --> 01:35:50,746
[Thud]
You were going slow at first.

2283
01:35:50,746 --> 01:35:52,516
[Thud]
But since he's not looking now...

2284
01:35:52,516 --> 01:35:54,356
I can't just be stuck on this one thing.

2285
01:35:54,356 --> 01:35:55,765
If I'm stuck on this,

2286
01:35:55,765 --> 01:35:57,436
- I can't look at other things.
- Exactly.

2287
01:35:57,436 --> 01:35:58,746
I was a bit anxious at first.

2288
01:35:58,746 --> 01:36:02,074
[Finishing swiftly to move on]
She wanted to finish quickly.

2289
01:36:04,596 --> 01:36:06,166
He saw it.

2290
01:36:06,166 --> 01:36:07,636
He's here.

2291
01:36:07,636 --> 01:36:08,906
I wonder what he'll say.

2292
01:36:08,906 --> 01:36:10,636
[Is she doing okay?]

2293
01:36:10,636 --> 01:36:13,279
"Wait, what's this?"

2294
01:36:14,426 --> 01:36:16,223
She's pretty good.

2295
01:36:18,966 --> 01:36:23,126
Earlier, she knew how to remove
the fish head and tail.

2296
01:36:23,126 --> 01:36:24,616
She must have seen what you did.

2297
01:36:24,616 --> 01:36:26,666
Of course she did, but...

2298
01:36:26,666 --> 01:36:31,470
[The juniors' suspicions suddenly resurface]

2299
01:36:32,166 --> 01:36:34,876
[Could it be...]

2300
01:36:34,876 --> 01:36:36,936
- Why?
- See, I was right.

2301
01:36:36,936 --> 01:36:40,486
[I told you so!]
You can tell by the way she cuts.

2302
01:36:40,486 --> 01:36:42,246
Good, good.

2303
01:36:42,246 --> 01:36:44,437
That's it. You can do it like this.

2304
01:36:46,745 --> 01:36:48,372
"She's doing well because I taught her well.

2305
01:36:48,372 --> 01:36:49,540
She's good, isn't she?"

2306
01:36:49,540 --> 01:36:52,148
So he's saying it's because he taught her well.

2307
01:36:52,148 --> 01:36:53,576
When they were exchanging looks...

2308
01:36:53,576 --> 01:36:55,079
they might be saying that

2309
01:36:55,079 --> 01:36:57,612
because they're scared she's a former boxer.

2310
01:36:58,304 --> 01:37:01,316
They say she's a boxer.

2311
01:37:01,316 --> 01:37:05,796
You might get your head bashed in.

2312
01:37:05,796 --> 01:37:07,756
[Are they too scared to speak?]
When they talk...

2313
01:37:07,756 --> 01:37:10,383
They all hesitate.

2314
01:37:11,076 --> 01:37:13,676
Can I see the front area?

2315
01:37:13,676 --> 01:37:16,236
[I'm curious about that place...]
Can I see the front area?

2316
01:37:16,236 --> 01:37:17,356
The front area.

2317
01:37:17,356 --> 01:37:19,746
I'll go ask.

2318
01:37:22,436 --> 01:37:24,636
[Welcome, Sunny]

2319
01:37:24,636 --> 01:37:26,385
Come this way.

2320
01:37:28,626 --> 01:37:30,426
Over here.

2321
01:37:30,426 --> 01:37:32,506
- Here?
- Yes.

2322
01:37:32,506 --> 01:37:35,046
[The place Sunny is curious about is?]
- Come here. - Hello.

2323
01:37:37,196 --> 01:37:39,909
[The first place you see
when entering the restaurant]

2324
01:37:39,909 --> 01:37:41,736
[Open kitchen]
It's the Cold Dish Department.

2325
01:37:41,736 --> 01:37:44,296
Yes, I was very curious about the front.

2326
01:37:44,296 --> 01:37:46,196
Cold dishes are...

2327
01:37:46,196 --> 01:37:47,556
They don't use heat,

2328
01:37:47,556 --> 01:37:50,229
and since they're served cold first...

2329
01:37:51,018 --> 01:37:53,426
[Cold Dish Department, no-fire cooking]
Most Chinese dishes use heat,

2330
01:37:53,426 --> 01:37:55,462
so she must have a lot of questions

2331
01:37:55,462 --> 01:37:58,191
[Separate from the Prep and Wok stations]
about cooking methods that don't.

2332
01:37:59,676 --> 01:38:01,276
It'll be more delicate,

2333
01:38:01,276 --> 01:38:03,206
and the ingredients will be more diverse.

2334
01:38:03,206 --> 01:38:04,826
That's what I was thinking.

2335
01:38:04,826 --> 01:38:07,146
It looks delicious.

2336
01:38:10,584 --> 01:38:12,331
Cold Dish Department... hello.

2337
01:38:12,331 --> 01:38:15,503
[Entering the long-awaited Cold Dish Dept.]

2338
01:38:16,406 --> 01:38:17,866
This is a cold dish.

2339
01:38:17,866 --> 01:38:19,816
Cold Dish Department... hello.

2340
01:38:19,816 --> 01:38:21,446
Wait, are they sitting down?

2341
01:38:21,446 --> 01:38:22,676
They're all sitting down.

2342
01:38:22,676 --> 01:38:24,616
[Oh my]
Basically...

2343
01:38:24,616 --> 01:38:26,536
- They aren't standing.
- They weren't standing.

2344
01:38:26,536 --> 01:38:29,126
[Why are you squatting there?]
They're sitting over there, too.

2345
01:38:29,126 --> 01:38:32,346
[Starting to observe closely]
Basically, they aren't standing up.

2346
01:38:32,346 --> 01:38:34,346
- This is chili oil.
- Chili oil.

2347
01:38:34,346 --> 01:38:35,729
Yes, it smells so savory.

2348
01:38:35,729 --> 01:38:37,439
Yes, it's savory.

2349
01:38:37,439 --> 01:38:38,666
[Interested]
Buckwheat noodles.

2350
01:38:38,666 --> 01:38:40,006
- Are these noodles?
- Yes.

2351
01:38:40,006 --> 01:38:42,555
- Buckwheat noodles.
- Buckwheat noodles.

2352
01:38:44,356 --> 01:38:46,726
This is the Cold Dish area,
so what's that area over there?

2353
01:38:46,726 --> 01:38:49,529
- That's the Steaming Department.
- Steaming?

2354
01:38:49,529 --> 01:38:50,956
[Right next to the Cold Dish Dept.]

2355
01:38:50,956 --> 01:38:53,336
So the Steaming Dept. is right next to it.

2356
01:38:53,336 --> 01:38:55,076
- Like dumplings?
- This is mantou.

2357
01:38:55,076 --> 01:38:57,706
[Steaming Dept. handles dumplings
and steamed dishes]

2358
01:38:58,536 --> 01:39:00,916
[Steamed Pork Belly with Sticky Rice]

2359
01:39:01,576 --> 01:39:04,236
[Meatball Soup]

2360
01:39:04,236 --> 01:39:07,052
[Steaming Dept. dishes are served
after simple preparation]

2361
01:39:07,052 --> 01:39:10,836
You just turn on the heat and steam them here.

2362
01:39:10,836 --> 01:39:12,996
This is dough made with vegetables.

2363
01:39:12,996 --> 01:39:14,936
Vegetable dough?

2364
01:39:15,606 --> 01:39:17,355
Visiting someone else's kitchen is

2365
01:39:17,355 --> 01:39:18,716
a great way to learn.

2366
01:39:18,716 --> 01:39:20,856
The ingredients themselves are different.

2367
01:39:20,856 --> 01:39:23,766
[24-year veteran, still learning]
Of course. There's so much.

2368
01:39:23,766 --> 01:39:26,316
I haven't even found the storage yet.

2369
01:39:26,316 --> 01:39:28,326
There's so much to do.

2370
01:39:28,326 --> 01:39:30,846
[The restaurant is so big,
it takes ages to get a handle on it]

2371
01:39:30,846 --> 01:39:32,538
It's been quite hectic.

2372
01:39:33,176 --> 01:39:38,956
[Dinner service begins]

2373
01:39:38,956 --> 01:39:42,676
[6:00 PM]
Shred it and stir-fry with glass noodles.

2374
01:39:42,676 --> 01:39:44,676
Then let's order this.

2375
01:39:44,676 --> 01:39:49,516
[Tables fill up as dinner time arrives]
You ordered two vegetable dishes, right?

2376
01:39:49,516 --> 01:39:52,376
[Orders start pouring into the kitchen]

2377
01:39:52,376 --> 01:39:53,706
Jingjiang rousi.

2378
01:39:53,706 --> 01:39:55,066
Jingjiang rousi.

2379
01:39:55,066 --> 01:39:56,236
[New Order: Jingjiang Rousi]

2380
01:39:56,236 --> 01:39:58,285
- That looks delicious.
- Truly delicious.

2381
01:39:58,956 --> 01:40:01,441
[Jingjiang Rousi]
Jingjiang Rousi.

2382
01:40:04,266 --> 01:40:06,296
[Shredded pork stir-fried in sweet bean sauce]

2383
01:40:06,296 --> 01:40:07,916
So they have Jingjiang rousi here too.

2384
01:40:07,916 --> 01:40:09,281
- They do.
- Is it the same as in Korea?

2385
01:40:09,281 --> 01:40:11,998
[A representative Chinese dish!]
Yes. They use tianmianjiang.

2386
01:40:12,696 --> 01:40:15,526
Jingjiang rousi.

2387
01:40:15,526 --> 01:40:18,506
[Checking the Jingjiang rousi]

2388
01:40:18,506 --> 01:40:21,044
[Tossing ingredients to the cooking station]
What's that?

2389
01:40:21,044 --> 01:40:22,780
He said he'd shred the meat,

2390
01:40:22,780 --> 01:40:24,028
and make Jingjiang rousi.

2391
01:40:24,028 --> 01:40:25,548
- Seasoning?
- Marinade.

2392
01:40:26,284 --> 01:40:27,656
Looks delicious.

2393
01:40:27,656 --> 01:40:29,532
- Is it pork?
- What?

2394
01:40:29,532 --> 01:40:31,178
- Is it pork?
- Yes, it's pork.

2395
01:40:31,178 --> 01:40:33,846
It's the pork we sliced earlier.

2396
01:40:33,846 --> 01:40:38,076
[Sunny's hard at work shredding pork]

2397
01:40:39,628 --> 01:40:43,788
[The Wok station starts Jingjiang rousi]

2398
01:40:44,508 --> 01:40:46,860
[While cooking at the Cooking station]

2399
01:40:48,716 --> 01:40:51,308
[Sunny starts moving instinctively]
She's moving, she's moving.

2400
01:40:55,884 --> 01:40:57,276
[Slides in]

2401
01:40:58,812 --> 01:41:01,980
[Jingjiang rousi for takeout]
- Takeout. - Takeout.

2402
01:41:03,252 --> 01:41:04,428
Can I serve it like this?

2403
01:41:04,428 --> 01:41:06,572
Just add this on top.

2404
01:41:06,572 --> 01:41:08,849
[Adds green onions]

2405
01:41:08,849 --> 01:41:10,348
[Checking the order slip]
That's right.

2406
01:41:10,348 --> 01:41:12,266
You can hand it over to the server.

2407
01:41:12,266 --> 01:41:15,700
[Jingjiang rousi is ready for delivery]

2408
01:41:19,756 --> 01:41:22,588
[What does she do after returning?]

2409
01:41:23,372 --> 01:41:26,348
[A clean finish]

2410
01:41:27,292 --> 01:41:28,988
An order for duck is in.

2411
01:41:28,988 --> 01:41:31,276
[Seeing that the senior looks busy]

2412
01:41:31,956 --> 01:41:35,580
[Handling things proactively]

2413
01:41:39,100 --> 01:41:41,713
[The plating area is neatly organized]

2414
01:41:41,713 --> 01:41:44,382
- I think Sunny is very smart.
- She is smart.

2415
01:41:44,382 --> 01:41:48,586
When using the wok, dirty dishes pile up.

2416
01:41:48,586 --> 01:41:52,396
But Sunny kept replacing them with clean ones.

2417
01:41:52,396 --> 01:41:54,828
- She's a smart person.
- Indeed.

2418
01:41:54,828 --> 01:41:56,910
She must seem like a very perceptive person.

2419
01:41:56,910 --> 01:41:58,140
Right?

2420
01:41:58,140 --> 01:41:59,788
- That's the kitchen junior's sense.
- Exactly.

2421
01:41:59,788 --> 01:42:01,484
- Sense.
- She's got sense.

2422
01:42:01,484 --> 01:42:03,308
- What's that?
- Looks good.

2423
01:42:03,308 --> 01:42:05,564
- Spicy seonji intestine soup.
- Intestine soup.

2424
01:42:05,564 --> 01:42:07,852
This is just perfect.

2425
01:42:07,852 --> 01:42:10,149
Should I sprinkle more pepper?

2426
01:42:10,956 --> 01:42:12,924
- Is it this one?
- No, not that.

2427
01:42:12,924 --> 01:42:15,516
[Is it this one?]
- The pepper? - Yes, the pepper.

2428
01:42:15,516 --> 01:42:18,545
[Handling spices proactively too]

2429
01:42:23,116 --> 01:42:24,557
[Garlic]

2430
01:42:25,644 --> 01:42:27,914
[Getting the garlic ready for the next step]

2431
01:42:28,716 --> 01:42:33,507
[The skill of holding the plastic bag open]

2432
01:42:36,716 --> 01:42:39,452
[After sprinkling the garlic...]

2433
01:42:40,856 --> 01:42:43,372
[Another clean finish]

2434
01:42:43,372 --> 01:42:46,156
This is what I always tell my staff.

2435
01:42:46,156 --> 01:42:47,484
Being good at your job is great.

2436
01:42:47,484 --> 01:42:49,228
But "having sense" is more important.

2437
01:42:49,228 --> 01:42:51,557
I say that a lot.

2438
01:42:55,620 --> 01:42:57,449
For example, while the senior is prepping...

2439
01:42:57,449 --> 01:42:59,429
I would have put out the trash
in advance or something.

2440
01:42:59,429 --> 01:43:00,667
I was trying to be quick-witted.

2441
01:43:00,667 --> 01:43:02,460
I was trying hard to make a good impression.

2442
01:43:02,460 --> 01:43:06,727
I think you're continuously improving.

2443
01:43:07,446 --> 01:43:10,284
It's different from when I first started.

2444
01:43:10,284 --> 01:43:14,044
It's different.

2445
01:43:14,044 --> 01:43:17,276
The results are different.

2446
01:43:17,276 --> 01:43:19,387
He's definitely different from you.

2447
01:43:19,387 --> 01:43:21,621
[She's the Queen of Chinese Cuisine]
Of course I am.

2448
01:43:23,256 --> 01:43:29,253
[After the first round
of food is served to the guests]

2449
01:43:33,416 --> 01:43:36,684
[A lull in the kitchen]

2450
01:43:37,926 --> 01:43:39,324
[Thud]

2451
01:43:40,940 --> 01:43:44,316
[Plops down]

2452
01:43:46,415 --> 01:43:48,291
[Plops down]
They're all sitting down.

2453
01:43:48,291 --> 01:43:49,541
Everyone is sitting.

2454
01:43:49,541 --> 01:43:51,516
[Wok station seniors take a break]
They each have their own chair.

2455
01:43:51,516 --> 01:43:53,306
But I think it's good.

2456
01:43:53,306 --> 01:43:55,715
You have to manage your own stamina as you go.

2457
01:43:55,715 --> 01:43:57,216
I think it's good.

2458
01:43:57,974 --> 01:44:00,368
[Glance]

2459
01:44:01,084 --> 01:44:03,916
[Watching the Wok station
seniors taking a break]

2460
01:44:03,916 --> 01:44:06,780
[She stares at them...]

2461
01:44:07,884 --> 01:44:11,070
I still have that "boss mindset."

2462
01:44:11,070 --> 01:44:14,188
Did you see the staff loafing around earlier?

2463
01:44:14,188 --> 01:44:16,332
Man, it was infuriating.

2464
01:44:16,332 --> 01:44:18,108
- Why?
- Why does that make you angry?

2465
01:44:18,108 --> 01:44:20,924
Wouldn't you be mad if people did that
in your restaurant?

2466
01:44:20,924 --> 01:44:23,528
That's what I was thinking.

2467
01:44:25,212 --> 01:44:27,004
But you're the kitchen junior now.

2468
01:44:28,931 --> 01:44:31,090
[Oh, right]

2469
01:44:31,090 --> 01:44:32,342
Right, right.

2470
01:44:32,342 --> 01:44:33,467
So I just thought,

2471
01:44:33,467 --> 01:44:35,660
"I guess that's how it is," and moved on.

2472
01:44:35,660 --> 01:44:38,008
But the owner kept walking back and forth.

2473
01:44:38,008 --> 01:44:40,268
[How will the owner react?]
The owner kept walking back and forth.

2474
01:44:40,268 --> 01:44:43,836
[He spots the staff!]

2475
01:44:43,836 --> 01:44:46,028
[Glance] [Not interested...]
He doesn't care at all.

2476
01:44:46,028 --> 01:44:47,607
- So it's just normal.
- Just normal.

2477
01:44:47,607 --> 01:44:50,142
[In China, staff rest if there's no work]
"Of course they're sitting."

2478
01:44:50,142 --> 01:44:51,420
"Because there's no work.

2479
01:44:51,420 --> 01:44:53,279
- It's okay to just sit."
- During this time.

2480
01:44:53,279 --> 01:44:55,275
Yeah, they rest when they can.

2481
01:44:55,275 --> 01:44:57,235
It's so strange. I can't quite...

2482
01:44:57,235 --> 01:44:58,620
Chinese kitchen culture is so different.

2483
01:44:58,620 --> 01:45:00,380
- About sitting down to rest?
- Yeah.

2484
01:45:00,380 --> 01:45:02,199
It's just that...

2485
01:45:02,199 --> 01:45:03,867
Usually in western cuisine,

2486
01:45:03,867 --> 01:45:05,354
not in every case, but...

2487
01:45:05,354 --> 01:45:07,468
- No place has them sitting like that.
- That's true.

2488
01:45:07,468 --> 01:45:09,706
Is it that there's no time to sit, or...

2489
01:45:09,706 --> 01:45:11,833
- you can't stand seeing them sit?
- There's no time, and...

2490
01:45:11,833 --> 01:45:13,340
I don't like just idling around.

2491
01:45:13,340 --> 01:45:14,396
Just idling around...

2492
01:45:14,396 --> 01:45:16,172
- I find that hard to do as well.
- Really?

2493
01:45:16,172 --> 01:45:17,500
There must be so much to do...

2494
01:45:17,500 --> 01:45:19,571
- Exactly.
- There's so much to clean up in between.

2495
01:45:19,571 --> 01:45:21,087
- Right.
- Exactly.

2496
01:45:23,935 --> 01:45:24,972
I see...

2497
01:45:24,972 --> 01:45:26,636
That's just how it was...

2498
01:45:26,636 --> 01:45:28,332
How do you feel about it?

2499
01:45:28,332 --> 01:45:31,096
I guess it's just the style here.

2500
01:45:31,996 --> 01:45:34,581
I think I'd just keep working.

2501
01:45:35,822 --> 01:45:37,420
I didn't sit down even once.

2502
01:45:37,420 --> 01:45:39,196
I think so too.

2503
01:45:39,196 --> 01:45:40,684
I sat down immediately.

2504
01:45:40,684 --> 01:45:42,974
- Everyone's different.
- He was even asking for a chair.

2505
01:45:44,316 --> 01:45:46,540
Rather than just staying still,

2506
01:45:46,540 --> 01:45:48,894
I think it's better to keep moving.

2507
01:45:50,172 --> 01:45:52,130
You can sit over there for a bit.

2508
01:45:52,130 --> 01:45:54,054
It's okay.

2509
01:45:58,268 --> 01:46:03,415
[Wiping down the dirty counters,
she can't stay still for a second]

2510
01:46:09,580 --> 01:46:13,849
[A chef has been watching
the diligent kitchen junior]

2511
01:46:16,188 --> 01:46:18,636
[Look at her go]

2512
01:46:19,228 --> 01:46:22,860
[He then says something to the owner]

2513
01:46:22,860 --> 01:46:25,580
Are you going to use dried chilies?

2514
01:46:25,580 --> 01:46:27,884
No, use salt.

2515
01:46:27,884 --> 01:46:31,852
[What is he going to do with salt?]

2516
01:46:32,962 --> 01:46:34,427
Sunny.

2517
01:46:35,932 --> 01:46:38,332
[Why is he calling me?]

2518
01:46:38,332 --> 01:46:40,204
You need to learn how to hold the wok first.

2519
01:46:40,204 --> 01:46:41,548
He'll teach you now.

2520
01:46:41,548 --> 01:46:44,476
You need to learn how to hold the wok first.

2521
01:46:45,196 --> 01:46:46,972
How to handle the wok.

2522
01:46:47,756 --> 01:46:49,848
- How do I do it?
- Why don't you try?

2523
01:46:49,848 --> 01:46:53,000
[Promoted from Prep to Wok in one day?]
- Right now? - I was so surprised.

2524
01:46:53,000 --> 01:46:55,052
[Chef Yang recognizes Sunny's hard work]
- Since she works hard... - He's so kind.

2525
01:46:55,052 --> 01:46:57,777
He's giving her a chance.

2526
01:47:00,524 --> 01:47:02,476
Wok handling must be really tough too.

2527
01:47:02,476 --> 01:47:04,172
[Wok handling]
It must be so hot.

2528
01:47:04,796 --> 01:47:07,576
[Wok training begins under the guidance
of Senior Chef Yang]

2529
01:47:07,576 --> 01:47:10,675
Fold your wok towel like this.

2530
01:47:11,580 --> 01:47:14,252
Hook your thumb on the handle with the towel.

2531
01:47:14,252 --> 01:47:17,292
Then you pull the wok toward you.

2532
01:47:17,292 --> 01:47:18,710
You shake the wok and pull it like this.

2533
01:47:18,710 --> 01:47:21,004
Pull it.

2534
01:47:21,004 --> 01:47:23,893
[After explaining the theory]

2535
01:47:24,940 --> 01:47:27,868
[He rummages under the shelf...]

2536
01:47:27,868 --> 01:47:30,296
[Curious]

2537
01:47:30,296 --> 01:47:31,500
[He takes out salt?!]

2538
01:47:31,500 --> 01:47:33,416
- Salt.
- With salt?

2539
01:47:33,416 --> 01:47:35,226
Normally, when you first start,

2540
01:47:35,226 --> 01:47:36,945
you practice with rice or salt.

2541
01:47:36,945 --> 01:47:38,313
I saw this in a movie.

2542
01:47:38,313 --> 01:47:39,900
- They practice with sand and stuff.
- Right.

2543
01:47:39,900 --> 01:47:41,603
Sand, salt, and rice.

2544
01:47:41,603 --> 01:47:44,140
- He's just showing her the wok handling.
- He's just making her practice the wok.

2545
01:47:44,140 --> 01:47:46,652
[Wok basics from the ground up]
It's not really cooking.

2546
01:47:46,652 --> 01:47:48,316
Do you stir-fry the salt?

2547
01:47:48,316 --> 01:47:50,108
It's for wok handling practice.

2548
01:47:50,108 --> 01:47:53,706
- It's to practice handling the wok.
- Oh, practice.

2549
01:47:53,706 --> 01:47:55,276
Pull and push. Pull and push.

2550
01:47:55,276 --> 01:47:56,620
Pull and push, like this.

2551
01:47:56,620 --> 01:47:57,708
Like that.

2552
01:47:57,708 --> 01:47:59,372
Now, you try holding the wok.

2553
01:47:59,372 --> 01:48:00,684
He's giving her a lesson.

2554
01:48:00,684 --> 01:48:03,678
[Rumors of the junior's wok lesson]
Everyone is watching.

2555
01:48:03,678 --> 01:48:05,290
They can't help but watch.

2556
01:48:05,290 --> 01:48:07,086
[Staff gather to watch]

2557
01:48:08,417 --> 01:48:09,537
Like this?

2558
01:48:09,537 --> 01:48:11,431
[Sunny finally steps up to the wok]

2559
01:48:12,108 --> 01:48:13,769
[Nervous]

2560
01:48:14,940 --> 01:48:18,364
[Will Sunny be able to show her skills?]

2561
01:48:20,060 --> 01:48:21,436
- Why? Why?
- No, this...

2562
01:48:21,436 --> 01:48:22,860
- Is it over?
- Does it end here?

2563
01:48:22,860 --> 01:48:24,276
Why are they cutting it here?

2564
01:48:24,276 --> 01:48:25,941
I'm so curious about this.

2565
01:48:25,941 --> 01:48:27,836
- But just now, when it flipped up...
- Exactly.

2566
01:48:27,836 --> 01:48:30,140
- Right, right.
- Her wrist snap was already...

2567
01:48:30,140 --> 01:48:32,316
The body remembers.

2568
01:48:32,316 --> 01:48:33,416
Right now...

2569
01:48:33,416 --> 01:48:35,076
- Everyone will be surprised.
- Exactly.

2570
01:48:35,076 --> 01:48:36,172
The next scene...

2571
01:48:36,172 --> 01:48:37,420
- I think they'll be shocked.
- In the next scene,

2572
01:48:37,420 --> 01:48:39,420
what if the salt spills on the floor?

2573
01:48:39,420 --> 01:48:41,276
No, it looked stable.

2574
01:48:41,276 --> 01:48:42,572
It all went back in, I'm sure.

2575
01:48:42,572 --> 01:48:44,524
[What's the result?]
- I'm curious too. - Me too.

2576
01:48:44,524 --> 01:48:46,204
- I'm curious.
- It's getting interesting.

2577
01:48:46,204 --> 01:48:47,644
But for now,

2578
01:48:47,644 --> 01:48:48,796
out of the three,

2579
01:48:48,796 --> 01:48:49,980
I feel like...

2580
01:48:49,980 --> 01:48:51,420
Chef Jung Ji Sun...

2581
01:48:51,420 --> 01:48:53,436
will be the first to move up.

2582
01:48:53,436 --> 01:48:54,716
I think so too.

2583
01:48:54,716 --> 01:48:55,964
[Huh?]
Well, I think...

2584
01:48:55,964 --> 01:48:57,392
- Oh, really?
- What?

2585
01:48:57,392 --> 01:48:59,916
I think who showed

2586
01:48:59,916 --> 01:49:02,116
the most productivity out of the three of us

2587
01:49:02,116 --> 01:49:03,676
is very important.

2588
01:49:03,676 --> 01:49:04,989
Right, it's a battle of pride.

2589
01:49:04,989 --> 01:49:07,664
- It's a battle of pride.
- A battle of pride.

2590
01:49:09,237 --> 01:49:12,012
[One thing on the undercover juniors' minds]
How do we get in there?

2591
01:49:12,012 --> 01:49:14,380
[Escape the position of a kitchen junior]

2592
01:49:14,380 --> 01:49:16,124
Four! Divide it into four.

2593
01:49:16,124 --> 01:49:17,756
Add some more.

2594
01:49:17,756 --> 01:49:19,736
[Senior chef territoriality]

2595
01:49:19,736 --> 01:49:21,452
[Former kitchen junior,
Current Sunny's direct supervisor]

2596
01:49:21,452 --> 01:49:22,470
[Add chili]

2597
01:49:22,470 --> 01:49:25,388
Today, he was ordering me
around like a regular employee.

2598
01:49:25,388 --> 01:49:26,860
[Hang in there]

2599
01:49:26,860 --> 01:49:28,380
[Hee Tae, gelato cart dispatch]

2600
01:49:28,380 --> 01:49:29,964
[Gelato?]

2601
01:49:29,964 --> 01:49:31,100
Hold on.

2602
01:49:31,100 --> 01:49:32,186
[Just before the collapse]

2603
01:49:32,186 --> 01:49:35,132
[Sam Kim, 27-year veteran chef]
Scooping the gelato was the hardest part.

2604
01:49:35,132 --> 01:49:38,088
[New tasks and pouring orders]

2605
01:49:39,601 --> 01:49:45,123
[To overcome all of this]

2606
01:49:47,208 --> 01:49:50,732
Kwon! Do you want to try making the potato pasta?

2607
01:49:50,732 --> 01:49:52,556
[Seize an unexpected opportunity]

2608
01:49:52,556 --> 01:49:55,772
[Can he make his presence known?]
I make the impossible happen.

2609
01:49:55,772 --> 01:49:57,340
This won't work.

2610
01:49:57,340 --> 01:49:59,811
The wok handling didn't work at all.

2611
01:50:01,161 --> 01:50:03,132
[Morning assembly]
- Good morning. - Good morning.

2612
01:50:03,132 --> 01:50:05,084
- Cai Jun, Jiang Qi Chang?
- Present.

2613
01:50:05,084 --> 01:50:07,227
Cai Ye Dao, Zhang Qiang?

2614
01:50:07,227 --> 01:50:09,308
[Only other people's names were called...]

2615
01:50:09,308 --> 01:50:10,684
[Attendance is over]

2616
01:50:10,684 --> 01:50:13,724
[Is Sunny's name missing from the roll call?]

2617
01:50:13,724 --> 01:50:17,884
[What happened to Sunny?]
